<TITLE>There's Math in Deviled Eggs #364</TITLE>
<BODY>

<H2>There's Math in Deviled Eggs</H2>

<H3>Strategies for Teaching Young Children</H3>

Professional Development, Teaching Techniques, and Mathematics for Preservice/Preservice/Inservice Educators of Kindergarten-Grade 2<P>

Examine a practical approach to converting preschool and kindergarten students' natural interest and curiosity into a strong mathematics foundation. The video program and suggested activities will help teachers prepare students for more complex mathematical thinking. Observe expert teachers interacting with their students as active partners in the learning process. Develop strategies for turning common classroom activities into valuable "hands-on" mathematical exercises. See examples of a mathematically stimulating environment, one which incorporates the tools and routines that encourage children to explore and use math. This imaginative video program and user's guide will help preschool through first-grade teachers
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>implement eight strategies for a more balanced and comprehensive approach to teaching children how to think mathematically
<LI>apply techniques for bridging teacher and child as active partners in learning
<LI>convert children's natural curiosity into skills and attitudes that move them toward more complex mathematical thinking
</UL><P>

<B>Make Teaching Math Easy</B><BR>
Easy to Use-One staff development video program and user's guide are ideal for group workshops or individual study. Easy to Learn-Proven strategies offer new options for developing a more balanced and comprehensive teaching approach. Easy to Apply-Methods for customizing teaching strategies to your students' needs and guidelines for creating a dynamic classroom.<P>

<B>There's Math in Deviled Eggs</B> was produced by the Erikson Institute for Advanced Study in Child Development and the University of Chicago Laboratory Schools (1993).<P>

<H3>Purchase</H3>
