<TR><TD>NV</TD>   <TD>NY</TD>   <TD>OH</TD>   <TD>OK</TD>   <TD>OR</TD>   <TD>PA</TD>   <TD>RI</TD>   <TD>SC</TD>   <TD>SD</TD>   <TD>TN</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>TX*</TD>   <TD>UT</TD>   <TD>VA</TD>   <TD>VT</TD>   <TD>WA</TD>   <TD>WI</TD>   <TD>WV</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
* Partial<P>

If you have any questions about consortium pricing qualifications, call AIT Customer Service at (800) 457-4509.<P>

<H3>Programs</H3>

1. <B>Choice (Opportunity Cost)</B> - Gordon's big choice is how to use his own scarce resource on an afternoon when he is invited to both a ball game and the amusement park. (19:41)<P>

2. <B>Malcolm Decides (Personal Decision Making)</B> - Malcolm decides how to use his gift certificate by employing a decision-making process: defining the problem, listing alternatives, stating criteria, evaluating alternatives, and making the decision. (19:25)<P>

3. <B>We Decide (Social Decision Making)</B> - A scarcity of school bicycle racks prompts a class to think of several ways the problem might be solved and then to analyze each alternative. (19:39)<P>

4. <B>Give and Take (Trade-off among Goals)</B> - Freddie and Jim differ about what is more important -- building a tree house or improving their go-cart track. They learn that all-or-nothing choices can be avoided, and that through tradeoffs they can give up some of one thing to get some of another thing. (19:31)<P>

5. <B>Less and More (Increasing Productivity)</B> - Ricky takes over the management of the family delicatessen and increases productivity. While the new efficiency helps raise wages and hold down prices, one waitress has to change jobs and the security of the elderly cook is threatened. (19:42)<P>

6. <B>Working Together (Specialization)</B> - Maury, Eddie, and Diane realize they can save valuable time if they specialize and work together to wash their fathers' cars. They also learn some disadvantages of specialization. (19:20)<P>

7. <B>Does It Pay? (Investment in Capital Goods)</B> - Bobby figures that it will take seven more weeks of work with his push mower to earn the remaining $100 he needs to buy the car of his dreams. Could he get the car faster if he bought a new power mower? (19:38)<P>

8. <B>Learning and Earning (Investment in Human Capital)</B> - To have a chance at the job of junior playground supervisor, Judy takes an eight-Saturday training course. She pays $20 for books and gives up the $80 she would make at the supermarket. Eventually the investment pays off. Andrea, who takes the same course, is not so fortunate. (19:00)<P>

9. <B>Why Money? (Voluntary Exchange)</B> -  After a day-long round of trading, Christina finally gets her skateboard. She learns that using money is much more convenient than trading, and that checks as well as currency can be used as money. (19:54)<P>

10. <B>To Buy or Not to Buy (Buyers and Market Demand)</B> - When Uncle Gus agrees to let Sharon and her friends sell his bakery's Danishs door-to-door, he suggests they begin with a market survey. They learn how price and other factors affect market demand. (19:40)<P>

11. <B>To Sell or Not to Sell (Sellers and Market Supply)</B> - Cathy weighs the costs and benefits of making trays for Mrs. Guthrie's gift shop against those of gardening for neighbors. (19:55)<P>

12. <B>At What Price? (Market Clearing Price)</B> - Jennifer and Judy discover that when sale prices are set too low, a shortage develops. Bert and his friends try to determine a price that will just "clear the market" without either a surplus or a shortage, when they set up a refreshment stand. (19:22)<P>

13. <B>How Could That Happen? (Interdependence of Market Price)</B> - How could an "Arnie Oates" music craze lead to an increased supply of hamburgers and a shortage of football helmets? Such riddles can be solved by understanding the interdependence of prices in a market system. (19:30)<P>

14. <B>Innocent Bystanders (Market Intervention: Reducing Indirect Costs)</B> -  Jerry's Friday night rock band practice throws his sister and their neighbor into an uproar. A TV game show called "Innocent Bystanders" takes up the question of who should pay for a place for the band to practice. (18:29)<P>

15. <B>Helping Out (Market Intervention: Increasing Indirect Benefits)</B> - Sarah is saved from a series of painful rabies shots because Shogun, the dog who bit her, had been vaccinated. How can the town council ensure that all dogs get their rabies shots? Should town funds be used to provide the shots? (18:45)<P>

<HR>
"well balanced and interestingly presented, providing a thinking process which ultimately will help students to become more effective decision makers and responsible adults."<P>

Julia M. Suglia, teacher, Little Falls Middle School<BR>
 -- from a review in "The Docket" (New Jersey Council for the Social Studies)
