<HTML>
<TITLE>Up Close & Natural #270</TITLE>
<BODY>

<H2>Up Close & Natural</H2>

Life Science and Natural Science for Grades 1-4<P>

Bring the field, lake, and forest into the classroom and develop students' appreciation for and sensitivity to the wonders of the natural world. Help students sharpen their skills of observation, description, and classification.<P>

Explore the anatomy and behavior of animals that live in the wild, and the various elements of habitats that help animals survive. Encourage children to discover more about nature, and observe how animals adapt to seasonal changes.<P>

<B>Up Close & Natural</B> was produced by New Hampshire Public Television with a grant from the Corporation for Public Broadcasting (1983).<P>

<H3>Purchase</H3>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD>Each Program </TD><TD></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>$62.50</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Series</TD><TD>(#270-VVV)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>895.00</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>VideoKit&reg;</TD><TD>(#270-VK)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>525.00</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Teacher's Guide</TD><TD>(#270-TG)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>1.30</TD></TR>
</TABLE><P>

<TABLE>
<TR><TD>WINNER</TD><TD>Certificate of Award, International Wildlife Film Festival (1984)</TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD>Golden Electra Certificate of Award for Best Early Childhood Videotape, Birmingham International Educational Film Festival (1984)</TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD>Ohio State Award (1985)</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<H3>Programs</H3>

<B>1. Introduction</B> - Children study the creatures of nature by looking at them closely and asking questions. Students meet a snowy owl and a green darner dragonfly to learn about seasonal changes, habitats, life cycle changes, and differences between living and non-living things. (12:58)<P>

<B>2. Animals without Backbones</B> - Different kinds and numbers of body parts distinguish animals from one another. Invertebrates take many forms and live in many different environments. Introduce students to earthworms, spiders, and crayfish. (13:17)<P>

<B>3. Insects</B> - Insects all have three body parts and six legs, but vary greatly in size, color, shape, wings, and behavior. Discuss the life cycle and how many insects benefit humans. Students observe a monarch butterfly, praying mantis, grasshopper, cricket, fireflies, ants, and bees. (13:44)<P>

<B>4. Fish</B> - Fish are distinguished by their different sizes, colors, shapes, fin structures, and behaviors. Learn how fins, scales, slime, ears, and gills help fish survive in their underwater environment. Students visit a lake and the New England Aquarium where they see trout, porcupine fish, stingray, flatfish, minnows, and sunfish. (12:16)<P>

<B>5. Frogs, Toads, and Salamanders</B> - Amphibians are animals without hair, fur, feathers, or scales that live both on land and in the water. Students observe a bullfrog, a leopard frog, and a spotted salamander to learn about the double life of amphibians and what special adaptations enhance their chances for survival. (13:07)<P>

<B>6. Turtles</B> - Turtles are cold-blooded vertebrates with dry, scaly skin, a shell, four feet, a tail, and bony mouth ridges. Introduce the different kinds of turtles, their different habitats, and the many different foods they eat. Students learn the difference between a box turtle, a painted turtle, and a snapping turtle. (14:40)<P>

<B>7. Snakes</B> - Snakes are cold-blooded animals whose bodies take on the same temperature as their environment. Study the features that make snakes unique and how they benefit humans. Students are introduced to a garter snake and a seven-foot eastern indigo snake. (14:36)<P>

<B>8. What Is a Bird?</B> - Most birds can fly, but not all birds live in the same kinds of environments. Illustrate the commonalities of birds and some special adaptations that help birds survive: wings, feathers, good eyesight, ears, and beaks. Students see a pigeon, a great horned owl, loons, and great blue herons. (14:06)<P>

<B>9. Mammals</B> - Mammals are warm-blooded vertebrates with hair or fur that usually bear live young, and nurse them with special milk glands. Explain that mammals come in various shapes, sizes, colors, and body forms, and live in many places. Students are introduced to a baby raccoon and two fawns to study the distinctive characteristics of mammals. (12:53)<P> 

<B>10. Winter at Squam Lake</B> - Different animals have different ways of adapting to the winter. Emphasize that even though all living things eventually die, people must be careful not to destroy animal habitats and upset nature's balance. Students observe a snowy owl, white-tailed deer, and an American black bear to see different adaptations to winter's cold. (12:59)<P>

<B>11. Life in the Winter Forest</B> - The forest is a complex habitat, containing many different types of life. Learn how animals use a variety of means to survive the winter: hibernating, growing protective coverings, collecting large amounts of food, or utilizing a type of "anti-freeze" in their blood. Students examine the white-footed mouse, gray squirrel, porcupine, opossum, and fisher. (15:08)<P>

<B>12. The Pond</B> - A pond is a vital habitat for a variety of resident animals and transient visitors. See how the amount of animal activity changes with the seasons and how animals have adapted to the habitat in which they live. Students see a bullfrog, crayfish, newt, paramecia, and some water striders. (13:10)<P>

<B>13. Marsh and Swamp</B> - Marshes and swamps are examples of wetlands. Learn about habitats, the food chain, and that wetlands are breeding grounds for many animals and need to be protected from human destruction. Students are introduced to a variety of wetland-area animals including a turtle, duck, heron, red-winged blackbird, beaver, and barred-owl. (11:52)<P>

<B>14. In the Field</B> - Fields are habitats for a large variety of mammals, rodents, birds, and insects. Illustrate that all animals have a strong sense of survival which drives them to find food, seek shelter, and avoid danger. Students observe a fox, woodchuck, opossum, skunk, and kestrel (a swift bird of prey) to learn that many animals have specialized body parts and unique behaviors that enhance their chances of survival. (12:39)<P>

<B>15. Outside Your Door</B> - Animals can be found living just about anywhere. Backyard naturalists study creatures close to home: millipedes, centipedes, spiders, bees, sowbugs, and spittle bugs. Students learn how nature centers and zoos simulate the habitats of exotic animals, so people can observe tortoise, flamingos, and other animals they might not ordinarily see. (12:45)<P>

