<TR><TD>GA</TD>   <TD>HI</TD>   <TD>IL</TD>   <TD>IN</TD>   <TD>IA</TD>   <TD>KS</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>KY</TD>   <TD>LA</TD>   <TD>ME</TD>   <TD>MA</TD>   <TD>MN</TD>   <TD>MS</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>MO</TD>   <TD>NE</TD>   <TD>NH</TD>   <TD>NJ</TD>   <TD>NM</TD>   <TD>NY</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>NC</TD>   <TD>OH</TD>   <TD>OK</TD>   <TD>OR*</TD>   <TD>SD</TD>   <TD>TN</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>UT</TD>   <TD>VA</TD>   <TD>WI</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
*Partial membership<P>

<H3>Programs</H3>

<B>Limited Government and the Rule of Law</B><BR>
Demonstrate how the U.S. Constitution establishes rule by law, limiting the government's power over its citizens. Bill Moyers explains in detail how and why this works, examining issues from the Revolutionary War to Watergate. The dramatic segment raises the issue of rights of an individual accused of crime and the limits of government under a Constitution that guarantees the rule of law.<BR>
<TABLE><TR><TD>#251-001</TD><TD COLSPAN=2>30-minute video program</TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD>$180 (Standard)</TD><TD>$130 (Consortium)</TD></TR></TABLE><P>

<B>Federalism</B><BR>
Illustrate how powers are divided and shared between the state and federal governments. Bill Moyers examines the effect of the Civil War, the Depression, and the civil rights movement on the balance of governmental powers. The dramatic segment shows how the division of power between the states and the national government affects the daily lives of citizens.<BR>
<TABLE><TR><TD>#251-002</TD><TD COLSPAN=2>30-minute video program</TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD>$180 (Standard)</TD><TD>$130 (Consortium)</TD></TR></TABLE><P>

<B>Separation of Powers with Checks and Balances</B><BR>
Show why the Founding Fathers created three branches of government that cooperate and contend with one another in using power to govern effectively and in checking power to protect the liberties of individuals. Bill Moyers discusses how separation of powers with checks and balances has historically functioned, especially in times of crisis. The dramatic segment illuminates the complex interactions of the judicial, executive, and legislative branches.<BR>
<TABLE><TR><TD>#251-003</TD><TD COLSPAN=2>30-minute video program</TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD>$180 (Standard)</TD><TD>$130 (Consortium)</TD></TR></TABLE><P>

<B>Freedom of Expression</B><BR>
Focus on how this constitutional right often raises questions about the liberty of one person versus the security of all. Bill Moyers discusses issues involving the Sedition Act of 1798, the Espionage Act of 1917, and the Smith Act. The dramatic segment considers issues about the constitutional right to free speech and legitimate governmental limits on it.<BR>
<TABLE><TR><TD>#251-004</TD><TD COLSPAN=2>30-minute video program</TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD>$180 (Standard)</TD><TD>$130 (Consortium)</TD></TR></TABLE><P>

<B>Equal Protection of the Laws</B><BR>
Discuss the growth of equality under law, from its beginning as a right that protected only white male citizens to modern-day affirmative action. Bill Moyers focuses on the role of the Supreme Court, using the Fourteenth Amendment to show that the meaning of a law may hinge on that body's interpretation of it. The dramatic segment examines the issue of age discrimination in employment and employers' rights to hire whoever they feel is best for business.<BR>
<TABLE><TR><TD>#251-005</TD><TD COLSPAN=2>30-minute video program</TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD>$180 (Standard)</TD><TD>$130 (Consortium)</TD></TR></TABLE><P>

<B>The Constitution and the Economy</B><BR>
Study how the Constitution gives the national government power to regulate the economy and to provide for the general welfare. Bill Moyers traces the steady increase of this power and the issue of how much economic power the federal government should exert, from the separate visions of Thomas Jefferson and Alexander Hamilton to modern governmental deregulation. The dramatic segment demonstrates an issue about government regulation of private business.<BR>
<TABLE><TR><TD>#251-006</TD><TD COLSPAN=2>30-minute video program</TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD>$180 (Standard)</TD><TD>$130 (Consortium)</TD></TR></TABLE><P>

<HR>
"[<B>The U.S. Constitution</B>] should be required viewing. From the opening logo to the final credits, the programs do rival the best PBS documentaries. Bill Moyers brings a veteran journalist's grace as narrator/instructor. . . . [<B>The U.S. Constitution</B>] also spares no effort in digging up the best archival material--from Revolutionary pictures to newsreels to original broadcasts by John Chancellor. Moyers takes us to the floor of Independence Hall, the bowels of the National Archives, and to major landmarks in Washington, D.C."<P>

Eitv (Educational Industrial Television)
<HR><P>

<HR>
The Commission on the Bicentennial of the United States Constitution has granted <B>The U.S. Constitution</B> official recognition as a project "of exceptional merit with national significance, and substantial educational and historical value."
