<TITLE>Wasting Away #282</TITLE>
<BODY>

<H2>Wasting Away: Identifying Anorexia and Bulimia</H2>

Guidance/Mental Health and Health/Nutrition for Grades 7-12, Adult, and Preservice/Inservice Educators<P>

Observe the signs of eating disorders, considering adolescent development and particular pressures on girls and young women.<P>

Illustrate how eating disorders reflect a vulnerable individual's response to family problems and to a troubled and conflicted sociocultural environment.<P>
  
<B>Wasting Away</B> focuses on feelings, because feelings, more than food, are at the heart of these disorders. Identify the myriad pressures on young women in our culture. Explain the severity and complex nature of these disorders and learn how to talk with someone you suspect has anorexia or bulimia.<P>

<B>Wasting Away</B> was produced by Newington Children's Hospital, Newington, Connecticut (1987).<P>

<H3>Purchase</H3>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD>The Program</TD><TD>(#282-001)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>$75.00</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Teacher's Guide</TD><TD>(#282-TG)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>1.90</TD></TR>
</TABLE><P>

<TABLE>
<TR><TD>VIDEO</TD><TD>One 25-minute program</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>PRINT</TD><TD>26-page teacher's guide</TD></TR>
</TABLE><P>

<HR>
"<B>Wasting Away: Identifying Anorexia and Bulimia</B> is an excellent dramatized case study . . . an accurate portrayal of one type of situation that frequently leads to eating disorders."<P>
 
"Science Books & Films"
