<TITLE>We Are the Children #374</TITLE>
<BODY>

<H2>We Are the Children</H2>

Social Studies and Multicultural Education for Grades 4-6<P>

<B>Cultivate greater understanding of other cultures with stories told by their children</B><P>

The more we know about other people, the better we understand one another. This is the rationale behind <B>We Are the Children</B>, a unique 36-part series that introduces viewers to the peoples who comprise the vast cultural quilt of southern Africa, from Bushman to Zulu, from Chinese to Greek. Each program looks at the world through the eyes of a child, and each child tells his or her own story, which is always linked to an important event in the youngster's own life. The story may deal with the fulfillment of an ambition or the resolution of a moral dilemma, or it may involve a traditional experience. These programs
<UL>
<LI>illuminate the backgrounds, traditions, customs, and lifestyles of many diverse cultural groups
<LI>introduce students to an important part of the world that is now experiencing remarkable changes, as previously separated peoples begin sharing political power
<LI>open new horizons of understanding through stories that address issues 
of concern to children in any land
</UL><P>

<B>We Are the Children</B> is suitable for social studies and multicultural education in grades 4-6. The programs serve as engrossing supplements to regular curricula. Part of the acclaimed "Kideo" concept, <B>We Are the Children</B> is produced by Safritel of Johannesburg, South Africa, and distributed by AIT. &copy;1995<P>

<B>We Are the Children</B> and these are our stories . . .<P>

<B>Meet "Debbie, the Chinese Girl"<BR> 
(Program 19)</B><P>

Chinese proverbs are an integral part of life, and in this story Debbie Pon, a budding young drum majorette, illustrates the importance of honesty. Debbie is busy rehearsing a dance for the famous Double Ten Ceremony, but afterwards she loses the hat that she is supposed to wear during her performance. She is too ashamed to tell her parents that she lost the hat, but finally, when she admits her negligence and her parents help her, she realizes that she should have behaved differently. With her parents' help, the hat is returned to her at the last minute. But it was nearly too late, for without the hat she would not have been allowed to participate in the celebration.<P>

