<HTML>
<TITLE>Writer's Realm</TITLE>
<BODY>

<H2>Writer's Realm</H2>

Communication Skills for Intermediate<P>

Who is a creative writer? Everyone who ever scribbled a note, that's who. In <B>Writer's Realm</B> students in grades four through six will meet writers of many kinds -- favorite authors and people their own age. Dramatic segments, animation, interviews, notes, drafts, revisions, and finished products illustrate how real people go about writing.<P>

No two people do it in exactly the same way, but everybody learns to write by writing, and that's the point. These programs suggest alternatives rather than lay down rules. They illustrate how writing for different purposes needs to be different. They stimulate young writers to keep looking for ways to improve what they have written and, above all, to enjoy the process.<P>

<B>Writer's Realm</B> was produced by Maryland Instructional Technology in association with AIT (1987).<P>

<H3>Purchase</H3>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD>Each Program</TD><TD></TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>$125.00</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Series</TD><TD>(#264-VVV)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>1,495.00</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Teacher's Guide</TD><TD>(#264-TG)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>5.50</TD></TR>
</TABLE><P>

<TABLE>
<TR><TD>VIDEO</TD><TD>Fifteen 15-minute programs</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>PRINT</TD><TD>64-page teacher's guide</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>WINNER</TD><TD>Honorable Mention, Film Council of Greater Columbus, 1987, for program #7.</TD></TR>
</TABLE><P>

<H3>Programs</H3>

1. <B>Put It in Writing</B> - Writing is part of many different jobs. It's part of social life too. Understanding the steps in the writing process can improve the end product. (13:49)<P>

2. <B>What's the Idea?</B> - Writers get started in different ways, but the first step is observing. Techniques such as brainstorming, freewriting, and narrowing in on a manageable topic are shown. (13:49)<P>

3. <B>The Search Begins</B> - Encyclopedias aren't the only resources for writers. Others may require legwork but yield interesting results. Web diagrams of questions may help the researcher. (13:52)<P>

4. <B>That's Worth Noting</B> - There's a difference between retelling and mere copying. Taking notes helps writers collect and organize information, especially for nonfiction writing. (13:46)<P>

5. <B>Asking the Right Question</B> - Effective planning makes for a good interview, whether of a famous person or a family member. (13:49)<P>

6. <B>Picture This</B> - Historical fiction is one type of writing that requires writers to research the facts and then fill in details with their imagination. (13:46)<P>

7. <B>Let's Get Organized</B> - There's often no right order for a piece of writing, but sometimes order does matter. Using a time line is one way to organize the telling of a story. (13:50)<P>

8. <B>Show Me What You Mean</B> - Vivid, specific words make settings, characters, and problems come alive for the reader. (13:49)<P>

9. <B>It's Like This</B> - Figurative language paints pictures, especially in poems.  Metaphors can make a written work clearer and more interesting. (13:50)<P>

10. <B>Just the Right Tone</B> - Just as whining and sweet-talking evoke different reactions, so choosing the tone of written words matters, especially in persuasive writing. (13:49)<P>

11. <B>See What I'm Saying</B> - Sometimes a writer is specifying something that will actually be seen. Scriptwriting, for example, requires care with both visual and verbal elements. (13:49)<P>

12. <B>A Little Help from Your Friends</B> - Friends who respond with specifics can help writers focus and build on their good points. (13:50)<P>

13. <B>Details, Details</B> - How much detail is enough? How much is too much? The right details to put in a letter depend on the recipient. (13:49)<P>

14. <B>Everything in Its Place</B> - When readers need more details, sticking them at the story's end is seldom the solution.  Writers need to find good places to embed additional information. (13:49)<P> 

15. <B>Checking It Out</B> - Some people make their living as editors. Young writers can use checklists to proofread one another's writing and their own for clarity, interest, grammar, and mechanics. (13:50)<P>

<HR>
"An exciting approach to writing [that] melds interviews with well-known children's authors, the 'publishing' or sharing of students' written work, and creative vignettes embodying desired goals in the writing process . . . extraordinary fare for viewers in school libraries."<P>

ALA's "Booklist"
<HR><P>

