<HTML>
<TITLE>Zoolab #248</TITLE>
<BODY>

<H2>Zoolab</H2>

Ecology and Life Sciences for Junior High, and High School<P>

Animals star in these appealing studies of applied biology, which illustrate basic biological concepts and introduce junior high and high school students to some fascinating behind-the-scenes research -- at the zoo and in the field. Produced on location with the cooperation of the Cincinnati Zoo, the series features scientists, keepers, and others who are caring for exotic animals and working to return endangered species to the wild.<P>

<B>Zoolab</B> was produced by The Greater Cincinnati Television Educational Foundation (WCET), with financial assistance from The Kettering Family Foundation (1985).<P>

For purchase information please call AIT Customer Service at (800) 457-4509<BR>
Ten programs, approximately 30-minutes in length<BR>
24-page Teacher's Guide<P>

<H3>Programs</H3>

1. <B>How Do You Get a White Tiger? (Genetic)</B> - Applied genetics matters in a zoo, where most animals and birds are born in captivity. Interbreeding keeps lowland gorillas genetically strong. However, Bengal tigers bred for white fur with white stripes (both recessive) must be homozygous. Basic research and the International Species Inventory System help both endangered species and zoos. (28:45)<P>

2. <B>Animal Engineering (Physiology)</B> -  Specialized bones, feathers, and sight help birds live in the air. A gorilla's muscular head is related to its diet. A cheetah's large nasal passages contribute to its speed. The eyes of the "four-eyed fish," spirades of the Madagascar hissing cockroach, exoskeletons of insects, slow metabolism of turtles, and long necks of giraffes all have specialized functions. (28:45)<P>

3. <B>Community: How Do You Live with Your Neighbors (Adaptation)</B> - in wild communities everything depends on everything else. As food sources disappear, so do tropical species. In the temperate forest many animals share food and water, and vultures clean up. Antelope, wildebeest, and zebras warn other grassland animals of danger. Ostrich eggs need to hatch near other ostrich eggs. Drinking and eating habits of elephants and lions benefit other species. (28:45)<P>

4. <B>Environment: There' No Place Like Home (Adaptation)</B> - Polar bears, penguins, and woodchucks adapt differently to cold, fennecs, gopher tortoises, tarantulas, and burrowing fish survive heat. The zoo provides a special environment for an insect from Java. Dissection reveals a mackerel's gills and air bladder, and the sea lion's built-in equipment for long-distance underwater swimming is contrasted with what a human must carry. (28:43)<P>

5. <B>And Then There Were None (Endangered Species)</B> - The venom of a Russell's viper kills arthritis pain, and a chemical from the more common rosy periwinkle treats leukemia. More important plants, herbivores, omnivores (including humans), predators, scavengers, and decomposers need one another in a continuing cycle of food, oxygen, minerals, water, and energy. Humans upset this balance by destroying vast habitats -- but some are cooperating to save endangered species. (28:45)<P>

6. <B>Nutrition, Fitness, and Stress (Health)</B> - A diet of bear biscuits and water would be good for people, too, but carnivores need different food. Keepers must stir blood for vampire bats, mix aardvark food to the texture of termites, and treat water for saltwater fish. The right kinds of exercise space and retreat cages increase fitness and reduce stress in captive animals. (28:45)<P>

7. <B>Can You Teach an Old Dog New Trick ? (Animal Behavior)</B> - Studying the behavior patterns of animals in the wild is important to breeding and training animals in captivity. Banding and radio transmitters let observers follow birds and study the social life of bush babies. A cougar, a falcon, a capuchin and a spot-nosed monkey, a baby Siberian lynx, and a 60-year-old alligator demonstrate behavior natural to each. (28:43)<P>

8. <B>How to Trace a Family Tree (Clarification)</B> - A tiger is traced through its kingdom, phylum, subphylum, class, order, family, genus, species, and subspecies. Many animals illustrate the characteristics of their classes, and a nusty-kneed tarantula shows how spiders differ from insects. Puzzlers include the echidna and the koala. (28:4<P>

9. <B>What Can You Learn from an Aardvark? (Animal Research)</B> - Much zoo research is aimed at reproducing rare animals, such as the aardvark. House cats may become surrogate mothers of exotic cats. Rare bongo antelope have already been born to more common eland mothers, and more bongo embryos await transfer in Cincinnati s frozen zoo." Embryo splitting increases the frozen herd and frozen semen collected from wild bongos widens the zoo's gene pool. (28:45)<P>

10. <B>Life among the Tt Tub (Biological Career)</B> - A background in biology is important for zoo research scientists, veterinarians, animal keepers, educators, animal technicians and many other workers at a zoo. (28:45)<P>

<CENTER>
