<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Corporate Profile--Cooperative Development</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>

<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>

<H1><I>Corporate Profile&#151;</I></H1>
<HR>
<H1 align=center><I>Cooperative Development</I></H1>
<BR>

<TABLE width="20%" align=right border cellpadding=10>
<TR><TD align=center><FONT color="780000"><B>
Professional program coordination<HR width=50>
Maintaining long-term relationships<HR width=50>
Economical educational packages<HR width=50>
U.S. state & Canadian provincial governments<HR width=50>
Interagency project development<HR width=50>
Cooperative funding
</B></FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="drop_s.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>ince 1970, AIT has developed more than thirty-six major educational series in cooperation with education and technology authorities from all fifty U.S. states and the twelve Canadian provinces and territories.  A single project may involve work with as many as forty government agencies.  One recent series was initiated by Health and Welfare Canada, a government agency, with funding on behalf of all Canadian provinces and territories.  AIT then expanded the consortium to include educational agencies from all U.S. state governments in the same project.</P>

<P>These cooperative projects arise from identification of a curriculum need that could best be solved by instructional technology.  Typical projects involve developing educational material for core curriculum subjects in grades K&#150;12.  Recently, however, we have also produced an increasing number of series in such related fields as vocational education and teacher development.</P>

<P>AIT begins by preparing a prospectus to which state and provincial education agencies respond with advice and funding.  Depending on the project, additional financial support may come from private education agencies, technology organizations, and corporate and philanthropic sponsors.  The funding agencies then become a consortium of project advisers and partners.  When a project is completed, consortium members retain unrestricted rights to broadcast and duplicate the series videos, reprint accompanying materials, and buy components at reduced prices from AIT.</P>

<P>As projects are scripted and produced, AIT also works with classroom teachers and students to conduct formative evaluations.  These reports are an important research and development resource.  They allow us to measure accurately the effectiveness and adjust our educational materials as they are being developed.</P>

<TABLE align=right>
<TR><TD>
<IMG SRC="/profile/cd_blbox.gif"><IMG SRC="/profile/monument.jpg">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<P>Although the economic climate of the &#146;90s has placed serious restrictions on the budgets of many government educational agencies, AIT has continued to develop a broad range of projects.  We have worked successfully both to maintain a high level of quality and to reduce development and production costs.  Despite the considerably more complex technologies of current projects, our fees to the educational community are significantly lower today than they were ten years ago.</P>

<BR clear=right>
<HR>

<CENTER><TABLE cellpadding=25>
<TR><TD><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>
<IMG SRC="/images/dot_bl.gif"><A HREF="/profile/open.htm">Opening Statement</A><BR>
<IMG SRC="/images/dot_bl.gif"><A HREF="/profile/growth.htm">Agency Growth</A><BR>
<IMG SRC="/images/dot_bl.gif"><A HREF="/profile/alliance.htm">Strategic Alliances</A><BR>
<IMG SRC="/images/dot_bl.gif">Cooperative Development
</I></FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>
