<HEAD>
<TITLE>Corporate Profile--TECHNOS Press</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>

<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>

<H1><I>Corporate Profile&#151;</I></H1>
<HR>
<H1 align=center><I>TECHNOS Press</I></H1>
<BR>

<TABLE width="20%" align=right border cellpadding=10>
<TR><TD align=center><FONT color="780000"><B>
Current topics & new technologies<HR width=50>
High-profile writers & personalities<HR width=50>
A forum for new ideas<HR width=50>
Combining policy & issues<HR width=50>
Focus on reform<HR width=50>
Leadership
</B></FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="drop_i.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>n addition to developing, producing, and distributing ground-breaking instructional materials, AIT helps to shape current thinking and influence policy on a wide range of educational issues.  <I>TECHNOS:  Quarterly for Education and Technology</I>,  the Agency&#146;s journal devoted to the discussion of ideas about the use of technology in education, provides a forum for leading authorities on current topics and trends, educational policy and reform, and new technologies.</P>

<P>Begun in 1992, <I>TECHNOS Quarterly</I> signaled the launch of TECHNOS Press.  Our journal is a periodical &#147;think piece&#148; that provides the kind of information and perspectives that knowledgeable readers need to make reasoned decisions about the future direction of education.  <I>TECHNOS Quarterly</I> has featured a wide range of prominent writers, from U.S. Secretary of Education Richard Riley to leaders such as  business management expert Tom Peters, Nobel economist Milton Friedman, and the beloved Captain Kangaroo. The journal&#146;s audience includes government officials in Washington, D.C., all fifty states, and the Canadian provinces; directors of major educational and  philanthropic organizations; prominent print and broadcast journalists; and librarians, researchers, and educators at every level around the world.</P>

<P>In addition to <I>TECHNOS Quarterly</I>, TECHNOS Press gives us the opportunity to sponsor authors who are at the forefront of educational theory and policy  by establishing the AIT Distinguished Fellows Program. The Distinguished Fellows Program was designed to publish new works by leading researchers, writers, and experts and to provide substantive, thought-provoking, and original contributions to the field through concise, informative writing and analysis. The first AIT Distinguished Fellow in 1995 was Dr. Gerald Bracey who wrote &#147;Final Exam:A Study of the Perpetual Scrutiny of American Education.&#148; The 1996 AIT Distinguished Fellow, Morton Marcus, is writing a book on financing education in the 21st century, to be published by TECHNOS Press in the fall of 1996. In conjunction with the annual Fellows&#146;  books, TECHNOS Press publishes monographs.</P>

<TABLE align=left>
<TR><TD>
<IMG SRC="/profile/technos.gif"><IMG SRC="/profile/tp_blbox.gif">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<P>In 1994, AIT expanded its leadership role still further by sponsoring The Educational Fair Access and the New Media National Conference in Washington, D.C.  The Conference brought together, for the first time, major interest groups and experts to address the issues of copyright and electronic availability of multimedia materials in educational settings. Additional conferences will be organized by AIT that will provide similar forums for the exchange of ideas on other important topics.  Other TECHNOS Press plans include future online debates and forums on relevant and provocative issues in education, as well as increased electronic interactivity with education and technology leaders.</P>

<BR clear=left>
<HR>

<CENTER><TABLE cellpadding=25>
<TR><TD><FONT SIZE="+1"><I>
