<HEAD>
<TITLE>On Location: Projects now in production</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1>On Location</H1>
<H2>Projects now in production</H2>
<HR>

<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD>
<P>The AIT production crew worked with staff from the U.S. Geological Survey, Hawaii Volcano Observatory Division, to document the current progress of the Mauna Pia lava flow.  AIT has recently completed a significant video shoot at Hawaii Volcano National Park for the new <B>Science Links</B> &reg; curriculum being produced by AIT and distributed by <A HREF="http://www.thomson.com">Thomson Science</A>.</P></TD>
<TD WIDTH="200" ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/sc_link2.gif"><BR><SMALL>&copy; 1996 Agency for Instructional Technology</SMALL></TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<P><B>Science Links</B> &reg; is an integrated high school curriculum targeted primarily  toward a ninth grade audience.  It will be one of the first curriculums available to be based upon the new National Science Education Standards.  It also provides an integrated approach to teaching science.  Using a thematic approach, each of the ten modules will lead students into investigations in biology, chemistry, earth/space, and physics.</P>


<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD WIDTH="200" ALIGN=LEFT><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/sc_link1.gif"><BR><SMALL>&copy; 1996 Agency for Instructional Technology</SMALL></TD>
<TD><P>Roger Denlinger, of the USGS, took the AIT production crew to within 80 meters of the lava's point of entry into the ocean so that students will be able to view up close the incredible earth forces at work.  Roger will explain to students about energy, chemical reactions, earth movement, and the effects of volcanos.</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE>


<P>AIT is proud to be able to equip teachers with this new resource filled with dramatic footage and tested student investigations.  Look for <B>Science Links</B>  &reg;  in the Fall of '96. For more information on current production of <B>Science Links</B> &reg; call AIT at 800-457-4509 ext. 210. </P>

