<HEAD>
<TITLE>On Location: Projects now in production</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1>On Location</H1>
<H2>Current Thoughts on Brain Waves to Power Lines</H2>
<HR>


<P>Electricity is the theme of module 4 in <B>Science Links &reg;</B>.  Students and teachers will get a charge out of discovering how electricity is integrated in biology, chemistry, physics, and earth/space sciences.  Newly  taped video footage will do more than introduce students to basic concepts.  They'll see safety applications, medical uses, employment of math skills, and the many uses and effects of electricity.</P>

<!--[ photo of patient being wired, and Med Center logo which is a hyperlink]-->
<A HREF="http://medicine.indiana.iupui.edu/"><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/iumc.gif" ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/patient.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P>The AIT production crew recently shot at the Pulmonary Sleep Disorder Center at the Indiana University Medical Center.  Here students will observe the placement of tiny electronic sensors on a patient and the sleep information gathered during monitoring.<BR CLEAR=ALL></P>

<!--[photo of Dr. Foresman, and patient data]-->
<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/data.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>Dr. Bryan Foresman of the Sleep Disorder Center explains in the video what they do, &#147;Various stages of sleep are characterized by the electrical signals in the brain.  The signals that we measure are very low voltage.  Looking at the information gathered, we can measure the sleep stages.  We compile the information, compare it, and make a diagnosis.&#148;<BR CLEAR=ALL></P>

<!--[photo of electrician, Cinergy Logo which is a hyperlink]-->
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
<P>Students will also travel with Louis Bridgwaters of PSI Energy and experience what is involved in being and electrical line repair person.  Louis has to know a lot about electricity to do his job.  Knowing how electricity works is important for both safety and proper installation.  It takes hot work and plenty of know how, to keep your lights coming on at the flip of a switch.</P>
</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/electric.gif"><BR>
<A HREF="http://www.powerclinic.com/index.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/psi_logo.gif"></A>
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P>These video segments are part of the exciting development work going on now for <B>Science Links &reg;</B>.  But, the videos are only a portion of the entire curriculum.  The four color textbook will be filled with many interesting investigations, features, graphics, discussion topics, readings, career links, and a collection of additional resources.</P>

<!--[photo of Marvin Druger]-->
<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/druger.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>Every aspect of the <B>Science Links &reg;</B> project  is reviewed and evaluated to assure that schools end up with a top notch curriculum.  Teachers and reviewers from around the country will contribute to the evaluation process.  The chief consultant for <B>Science Links &reg;</B> is <A HREF="MAILTO:druger@sued.syr.edu">Dr. Marvin Druger</A> of Syracuse University.  Dr. Druger is the Immediate Past President of the National Science Teachers Association (NSTA).<BR CLEAR=ALL></P>

<P>If you are interested in your class testing investigations for module 4, <B>Current Thoughts</B> from <B>Science Links &reg;</B>, then please e-mail us your name, school name, and phone number to <A HREF="MAILTO:bbloom@ait.net">bbloom@ait.net</A></P>


