<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Look Ahead - AD/HD:  What It Is.  What It Isn't.  What To Do.</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H2><BIG>AD/HD:</BIG>  What It Is.  What It Isn't.<BR>What To Do.</H2>
<HR>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Staff Development</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>One 60-minute program for teachers, administrators, and parents</P>
<HR>

<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/adhd1.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<H3>When Attention Deficit Disorder is&#151;or isn't&#151;the problem.</H3>

<P><BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<B><I>AD/HD:  What It Is.  What It Isn't.  What To Do.</I></B> is an in-depth look at this troubling phenomenon.  ADD is often the first diagnosis for any attention problem&#151;but when are other factors at work?  How often is this a misdiagnosis because it is so easy to pin a simple label on inattentiveness?</P>

<P>Exploring ADD itself and the other causes of inattentiveness, such as emotional distress, cognitive or language processing problems, medical disorders or medication side-effects, environmental mismatches, this workshop program focuses not just on identifying the true causes of inattention, but effective management techniques for dealing with them.  Learn to:
<UL>
<LI>Identify problems that need further professional evaluation.
<LI>Understand what ADD is   and what it isn't!
<LI>Identify other attention problems that could be misdiagnosed as ADD.
<LI>Develop effective management techniques for various attention disorders.
</UL></P>

<P><B><I>AD/HD:  What It Is.  What It Isn't.  What To Do.</I></B> consists of a 60-minute program and accompanying facilitator's guide.  Pause points and reproducible materials allow teachers to work through the examples of students in need of help with their attention deficit problems.  It was developed by Southern Illinois University School of Medicine and AIT. &copy; 1997</P>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<P><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/adhd2.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><I>AD/HD:  What It Is.  What It Isn't.  What To Do.</I></B> is a video workshop and facilitator's guide that focuses on the problem of identifying Attention Deficit Disorder <I>and</I> avoiding misdiagnosing attention problems.  Not all attention problems are ADD.</P>

<H2>Program Segments</H2>

<P><B>Segment one</B> of the program introduces viewers to what ADD is and points out that not all inattentive behavior is ADD.  It outlines the basic approach needed to identify attention problems and the steps appropriate to gaining a meaningful dianosis.  We will also see a good example of a successful management strategy for a child with an attention disorder and learn more about <I>when</I> inattention may <I>not</I> be due to ADD.</P>

<P><B>Segment two</B> examines Case Study #1, Seth.  Seth and his parents are troubled by his inability to do well in school.  He is bright and well attuned to the needs and feelings of others, but he just cannot focus.  The smallest things will distract him and he constantly feels the need to move&#151;to fidget, stand, <I>be active</I>.  His desk is a mess and his handwriting is illegible.  He loves hands-on work but he seems totally disorganized otherwise.  Seth has ADD and we see the strategies developed to help Seth become successful in school.</P>

<P><B>Segment three</B> presents Case Study #2, Cameron, a first grader.  She also has trouble focusing on what is going on around her.  She is constantly watching other students to see what they are doing.  Cameron often gives wildly inappropriate responses to her teacher's question and seems confused.  She is well-behaved but seems disconnected.  Cameron does <I>not</I> have ADD&#151;she has a language processing problem.</P>

<P><B>Segment four</B> reviews the various issues of what ADD is and isn't and the various strategies that can be used to improve performance and self-esteem.</P>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/adhd3.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<H2><I>AD/HD: What It Is.  What It Isn't.  What To Do.</I></H2>
<H3>Could you define and diagnose what is taking place in this scenario?</H3>

<P><B>Mom:</B>  When Seth got into pre-school, he was pretty rough with the other kids.  He was not a favorite and was seldom invited over to other kid's houses or birthday parties.  He had a great year in kindergarten.  He could work at his own pace at learning centers.  He also had a good third grade experience but the other years have been pretty awful.  We don't know what to do.  He is always busy at home&#133;he's captivated by gadgets, always taking things apart and putting them back together.  We think he's smart and he's got a heart of gold.  But we don't know why he's doing so badly in school.</P>

<P><B>Dad:</B>  I work with him on homework when I can, but he often forgets what homework he has, or I just can't take the battle of trying to get him to focus.  Sports have been an experience.  Every time a fly ball came to him, he was examining an ant hill or messing with his shoelaces.</P>

<P><B>Seth:</B>  I don't know.  The <I>one</I> thing I <I>like</I> about school is the science experiments.  Other subjects just kind of lose me.  I just&#133;drift off and start thinking about other stuff.  Like these solar panels I ordered from&#133;oh.  Oh, yeah, I forget my homework a lot or I do it and <I>then</I> can't find it in my desk or backpack.  I forgot one whole page of a math test once.  Another time, I filled in all the answers on this stupid computer sheet in the wrong place&#151;like putting answer two where answer three goes.  I don't know.</P>

<HR>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
