<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Look Ahead - Civics at Work: People, Government, and a Civil Society</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1>Civics at Work:</H1>
<H2>People, Government, and a Civil Society</H2>
<HR>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Social Studies</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
Five 15-minute programs for high school students</P>
<HR>

<TABLE WIDTH="100%" CELLPADDING="5">
<TR><TD>
<H3>We <I>are</I> our government!</H3>
<B><I>Civics at Work</I></B> is contextual learning that teaches much more than how government works and our roles as citizens&#151;it demonstrates how intimately we are involved in the processes of our democracy.  The functions and needs of governing are not mere abstract principles&#151;in myriad ways, it is how we all interconnect.
</TD><TD>
<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/civics1.gif"><BR>
<SMALL><B>Discover the relationship between<BR>individuals and government.</B></SMALL>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<P>This series explores:</P>
<UL>
<LI>The "rule of law" vs. the "rule of men."
<LI>The Constitution, and the people as the ultimate source of power.
<LI>The forms and functions of representative democracy.
<LI>The branches of government and the key amendments in the Bill of Rights.
<LI>Diplomacy, treaties, trade, human rights and the elements of foreign policy.
<LI>What it means to be a citizen in the United States today.
</UL>

<P><B><I>Civics at Work</I></B> uses everyday situations to illustrate how individuals interact in ways that parallel the workings of government.  The relationship between government and individuals is not one of hierarchy&#151;we are the microcosm that shapes, reflects, <I>interweaves</I> our governmental system.</P>

<P>The CD-ROMs extend the video series, presenting many topics of discussion and extended activities from a historical perspective.</P>

<P><B><I>Civics at Work</I></B> is a series of five 15-minute videos accompanied by a teacher's guide and the CD-ROM series <I>U.S. Government: The First 200 Years</I> (&copy; 1995 Clearvue/eav).  It is being produced and distributed by AIT. &copy; 1997 AIT</P>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/civics2.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><B><I>Civics at Work</I></B> is a powerful exploration of how each one of us, in our daily lives, uses the principles of government.  It further explains what the principles and functions of government are.</P>

<H2>Modules<BR><SMALL>(working titles and concepts)</SMALL></H2>
<P><B>Module 1: What Is Government and Does It Do?</B><BR>
Authority, power, consent of the governed, common good,  civil society, voluntary organization, rule of law vs. "rule of men," individual rights, anarchy, fairness, freedom under law, and ordered liberty.</P>

<P><B>Module 2: Individual Rights and the Common Good</B><BR>
People as the ultimate source of power, government of limited powers, constitution as higher law, our Constitution, representative democracy, direct democracy, elections, and representation.</P>

<P><B>Module 3: Liberty and Justice for All</B><BR>
Legislative branch, executive branch, judicial branch, checks and balances, Federalism, state governments, rights of the accused, due process, right to counsel, adversarial and inquisitorial systems.</P>

<P><B>Module 4: Foreign Policy and the Economy</B><BR>
Sovereignty, diplomacy, treaties and agreements, sanctions, military force, free and open trade, human rights, foreign policy, trade/tariffs, and international economics.</P>

<P><B>Module 5: Citizenship in the 21st Century</B><BR>
Citizenship, naturalization, quality of life, property rights, and freedom of expression.</P>

<H2>CD-ROM Series<BR>
<SMALL>U.S. Government: The First 200 Years<SUP>*</SUP></SMALL></H2>

<P><B>Part 1&#151;</B>The issues that led to the creation of the Constitution, the emergence of political parties, Federalism from Jackson to Lincoln, the Civil War, and more.</P>

<P><B>Part 2&#151;</B>The Reconstruction, Johnson's impeachment, the ICC, increasing government influence on everyday life, special interests, presidential power, and more.</P>
<P><SMALL>*&copy; 1995 Clearvue/eav</SMALL></P>

<HR WIDTH="50%:">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Shaping and defining our democracy.</H2>

<P><B><I>Civics at Work</I></B> is a powerful tool, combining video and CD-ROM to investigate the uses and functions of government and our role in shaping and defining our democracy.  Using examples from everyday life (a group of tenants forming an organization, a ride with a police officer, employer/employee interactions, students debating a foreign policy issue, etc.), we see how what we do mirrors and is a microcosm of our government in action.</P>

<P>The videos stimulate classroom discussion on a level that is rarely achieved with print alone.  The CD-ROMs extend the process by presenting our legacy of government in the historical context.  <I>U.S. Government: The First 200 Years</I> explores the changes in our government with interactive multimedia programs. Many interesting topics and extended activities examine the political parties, the impact of government on territorial expansion and immigration, and the effects of industrialization, to name only a few. The CD-ROMs include a complete encyclopedia and dictionary for looking up key terms and concepts.</P>

<P>We have met our government&#151;and it is us!</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/civics3.gif"><BR><SMALL><B><I>Learn how the principles of government affect people's everyday interactions.</I></B></SMALL></P>

<HR>

