<HEAD>
<TITLE>Look Ahead - Economics at Work</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1>Economics at Work</H1>
<HR>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Social Studies</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
Five modules of economics instruction for students in grades 9&#150;12, post-secondary, and adult education courses</P>
<HR>

<H3>Journey with us to the world of economics - the one in everyone's home town!</H3>

<P>Contextual learning is what it's all about.  In the complex arena of economics we often hear references to interest, savings, consumption, profit, overhead, production, and a myriad other factors.  Without a context, they are just theories and fancy words!</P>

<P><B><I>Economics at Work</I></B> uses real-world examples (and charming narrators, who walk us through every stage of the process), to accomplish these prime goals:</P>
<UL>
<LI>Interpret economic events through the application of economic concepts to the workplace, public policies, and everyday life.
<LI>Acquire the critical-thinking, decision-making, and collaboration skills needed for career success.
<LI>Examine the interrelated activities of individuals, companies, labor, and government.
<LI>Understand how the market system works in today's global economy.
<LI>Apply economics concepts to problem scenarios within seven occupational clusters.
</UL>

<P>Career-to-work curricula are more important than ever and <B><I>Economics at Work</I></B> creates a home-town atmosphere that plunges students right into the process&#151;what decisions would I need to make as an entrepreneur?  How would I control costs?  How could I become more innovative?  Should I invest&#133;and in equipment or new products?  Above all, how does an economy work?</P>

<P><B><I>Economics at Work</I></B> consists of five modules on video and laserdisc, teachers' guides, student guides, software for application activities in seven different career clusters, a classroom utilization component, a teacher training video, and a workshop handbook.  It was developed by AIT, the National Council on Economic Education, and a consortium of state education agencies.  &copy; 1996</P>

<TABLE WIDTH="75%" CELL PADDING=5 ALIGN=RIGHT>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<B><I>Darci and Ann discover that a higher price for laptop computers can be an incentive for computer manufacturers to increase teh quantity of computers sold.</I></B></TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="/images/pictures/needs_women.jpg">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER><I>Economics at Work</I></H2>

<P><B><I>Economics at Work</I></B> explores the five primary aspects of economics: <I>Producing, Exchanging, Consuming, Saving,</I> and <I>Investing</I>.  Each module presents three real-life examples of how economics shapes the world we live in:</P>

<H2>Modules</H2>

<P><IMG SRC="/images/prodlogo/368produ.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Module 1&#151;Producing&#151;</B>introduces us to Market Street, USA.
<UL TYPE="DISC">
<LI>A bicycle shop is going out of business but understanding profit and loss, competition and production, and supply and demand leads to innovative solutions.
<LI>In the unpredictable computer industry we analyze the labor market, fixed and variable costs, and technology when faced with complex unemployment issues. 
<LI>How do supply and demand, relative prices, and international trade affect the athletic shoe industry?
</UL></P>

<P><BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/images/prodlogo/368excha.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B>Module 2&#151;Exchanging&#151;</B>explores what is needed to deliver goods to consumers.
<UL TYPE="DISC">
<LI>Markets, opportunities, and transaction costs are involved in surprising ways when we purchase tickets for rock concerts, the NBA playoffs, or the Indy 500.
<LI>How do barter and exchange rates affect the decision-making process when U.S. car-makers import foreign parts?  
<LI>We work with a photographer who needs to borrow money for new equipment, and see how inflation affects fiscal and monetary policy.
</UL></P>

<P><BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<IMG SRC="/images/prodlogo/368consu.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Module 3&#151;Consuming&#151;</B>explains why prices rise and fall; supply and demand; equilibrium and price control policies; and complementary and substitute goods.
<UL TYPE="DISC">
<LI>Spring break!  Why are prices for the same product higher or lower in different areas?
<LI>A construction company owner explains shortages and surplus, and why replacement cost is not necessarily the same as original cost.
<LI>Next, we investigate unemployment statistics and income levels; students must then analyze production costs and demand to adjust prices.
</UL></P>

<P><BR CLEAR=LEFT>
<IMG SRC="/images/prodlogo/368savin.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B>Module 4&#151;Saving&#151;</B>takes us into the world of interest rates and loans.
<DD><UL TYPE="DISC">
<LI>Saving, spending and buying on credit: two students are faced with many choices and factors in planning to get the most for their money.
<LI>What is the role of the Federal Reserve Bank in regulating the flow of money?  How do fixed-interest loans compare to floating rate loans?
<LI>Changes in disposable income may affect people's spending and saving behavior   supply and demand apply to money, too!
</UL></P>

<P><BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<IMG SRC="/images/prodlogo/368inves.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Module 5&#151;Investing&#151;</B>delves into the complex area of investing: What is investing? What are the various kinds of investing? When should we invest?
<DD><UL TYPE="DISC">
<LI>Investing in human capital   come along as high school graduates do a cost/benefit analysis to make decisions about training and education.
<LI>What is the difference between present and future value?
<LI>Productivity and robots - what types of investment can play a role in upgrading industrial potential?
</UL><BR CLEAR=LEFT></P>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER><I>Economics at Work</I><BR><SMALL>is a leap into the world of economics&#151;into our daily lives!</SMALL></H2>

<P>The forces that shape the complex interrelations of economics are brought to life through this highly engaging video and print series.  Using home-town examples and real-life interactions, students learn the ins and outs of economics&#151;the variables, decisions, and realities that form the basis or our economic life.</P>

<P>In contexts that students can relate to, <B><I>Economics at Work</I></B> takes us on a journey through every aspect of the consumer/business relationship.  <I>Producing, Exchanging, Consuming, Saving,</I> and <I>Investing</I>&#151;we all need an understanding of these basic forces and how they affect our lives.</P>

<P>Economics does not have to be dry, dull, and routine!  Capture the imagination of your students&#151;bring economics home to each and every one of them!</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/prodlogo/368logo.gif"></P>
<HR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>Click here for more information on <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm">Economics at Work</A>!</P>
<HR>

