<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Look Ahead - The Language of Algebra</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1>The Language of Algebra</H1>
<HR>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Mathematics</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
Sixteen 15-minute algebra programs for grades 7&#150;12</P>
<HR>

<TABLE BORDER  WIDTH="35%" CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN=RIGHT>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<B><I>Using the powerful teaching combination of video and print, </I>The Language of Algebra <I>provides a unique opportunity to use the start-and-stop technique that challenges students with substantial, concrete algebra situations.</I></B>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<H3>Involve students directly in exploring their own ability to speak the language of algebra!</H3>

<P><B><I>The Language of Algebra: Everyone Counts!</I></B> is based on an entirely new approach, developed in accordance with NCTM guidelines.  Instead of by-hand manipulative exercises, algebra is presented as a problem-solving, multi-dimensional experience in the world that we all live in.  Contextual learning means learning to remember, learning that stays with a person in every aspect of daily life.</P>

<P><BR CLEAR=RIGHT>We all "speak" algebra&#151;we just don't realize it. <B><I>The Language of Algebra</I></B> extends and refines the language of algebra that we experience in our day-to-day life.  The interactive lessons present real-world problems that draw students into the process, into the skills and extensions of algebra thinking that they will carry with them into a world that increasingly demands these career skills.</P>

<P>Students will learn to:
<UL>
<LI>Reason logically and clearly in an algebraic context
<LI>Develop skills that the real world demands, not mere abstract principles
<LI>Define, formulate, and reason algebraically
<LI>Communicate effectively in algebraic language
<LI>Extend these principles on their own into real-world contexts
</UL></P>

<P><B><I>The Language of Algebra: Everyone Counts!</I></B> is a series of sixteen 15-minute videos which can be used either in linear fashion, in the stop-and-start mode of classroom instruction, or as a remedial/independant learning series.  The package also includes teacher's guides, student guides, blackline masters for extended work, and computer templates that provide hands-on spreadsheet and database lessons.  The integrative nature of these materials is intended to serve as an invaluable resource.  <B><I>The Language of Algebra</I></B> is being developed by New Leaf Media and the North Carolina Department of Public Instruction and will be distributed by AIT. &copy; 1997</P>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>The living language of algebra&#151;<BR>brought home to our everyday life!</H2>

<TABLE WIDTH="100%" BORDER CELLPADDING=5>
<TR><TH><BIG>Programs</BIG></TH>
<TH><BIG>Working Concepts</BIG></TH></TR>
<TR><TD><H4>Program 1</H4><H4>Program 2</H4></TD>
<TD>Introduce the concepts of real numbers and expressions using real numbers.  Students learn to perform basic operations with real numbers.  Topics include determining additive and multiplicative inverses and absolute values, raising a real number to a power, writing numbers in scientific notation, using scientific notation on a calculator, distinguishing between rational and irrational numbers, finding approximations for square roots, simplifying radical expressions, and multiplying binomials which contain square roots.</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><H4>Program 3</H4><H4>Program 4</H4></TD>
<TD>Focus on solving equations and inequalities with one variable.  Students use problem-solving skills to solve real-world and word problems which involve a linear equation or formula.  Topics include solving simple equations using additive and multiplicative inverses; and solving an equation with similar terms, with a radical, and with an absolute  value.</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><H4>Program 5</H4><H4>Program 6</H4></TD>
<TD>Develop an elementary understanding of relations and functions.  Students learn to graph and locate sets of real numbers on a number line, to graph ordered pairs of numbers on the coordinate plane, to interpret information related to these sets of points, to find the distance between two points on a number line, to graph a relation on the coordinate plane, and to use a computer or graphing calculator to explore the graphs of functions.</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><H4>Program 7</H4><H4>Program 8</H4></TD>
<TD>Teach students to graph and use linear equations and inequalities.  Students learn to judge if data are behaving in a linear fashion, to graph a linear equation in two variables, to graph a line given its slope and y-intercept, to write equations ion a line given its slope and its intercept, and to write the equation of a line which models a set of real data.</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><H4>Program 9</H4><H4>Program 10</H4></TD>
<TD>Teach students to graph and solve systems of linear equations and inequalities.  Students learn to use a computer or graphics calculator to solve systems as well as using graphs to find the solution of a pair of linear equations.  They also learn the substitution, addition, and subtraction methods to find the solutions of a pair of linear equations in two variables and a system of linear equations.</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><H4>Program 11</H4><H4>Program 12</H4></TD>
<TD>Students will learn to perform operations with polynomials including addition, subtraction, and multiplication.  They will also learn to factor polynomials by finding common monomial factors and to factor a simple quadratic trinomial.</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><H4>Program 13</H4><H4>Program 14</H4></TD>
<TD>Students will discover how to work with ratios, proportions, and percentages.  Students will also learn to simplify ratios with algebraic expressions, to solve proportions, to use ratios and proportions to solve problems, and to solve problems involving percents.</TD></TR>
<TR><TD><H4>Program 15</H4><H4>Program 16</H4></TD>
<TD>Students will build an understanding of how to graph an interpret nonlinear equations.  Students will learn to graph a quadratic equation and to use an automatic grapher to find its solution.  They will also learn to use the automatic grapher to relate the solutions of quadratic equations and the x-intercepts, to solve a quadratic equation by using the quadratic formula, and to use quadratic equations to solve real-world problems.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Do You Speak Algebra?</H2>

<P>Can you&#133;
<UL>
<LI><I>define</I>
<LI><I>formulate,</I> and 
<LI><I>reason</I> algebraically?
</UL></P>

<P><B><I>The Language of Algebra</I></B> involves students&#151;draws them into the language of algebra that we all speak!  In a world increasingly dependent on mathematical skills in the workplace and in everyday life, contextual learning is essential.  Nothing brings mathematics to life like seeing how we interact every day with algebra.  Whether buying group tickets for several different events and times, calculating distance and mileage, predicting <I>your</I> choice for that player you want at the free-throw line, figuring interest on money deposited or borrowed, or analyzing the factors that go into a pollster's questions and answers, algebra is all around us!</P>

<P><B><I>The Language of Algebra</I></B> extends, refines, and infuses the student/teacher interaction with an experience never to be forgotten.  Using a combination of video, print instruction, blackline masters for extended activities, and computer templates for real-world problem solving in a spreadsheet format, <B><I>The Language of Algebra</I></B> is an invaluable resource.  It represents a shift from by-hand manipulative learning to hands-on contextual learning.  Algebra is a language that we all speak&#151;we need to learn how fully it can integrate into our lives!</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/algebra1.gif"><BR>
<B><I>use real examples of traveling by car to calculate distance and mileage in </I>Program 1: Planes, Trains, and Automobiles <I>(working title).</I></B></P>

<HR>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
