<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Look Ahead - Positive Insights on Education</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1>Positive Insights on Education</H1>
<HR>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Staff Development</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
Twelve 30-minute programs; Education reform and issues training on current theory for teachers, administrators, and parents.</P>
<HR>

<H3>Twelve interviews on the cutting edge of current theory and practice in education.</H3>

<P><B><I>Positive Insights on Education</I></B> is a compelling series of in-depth interviews highlighting some of the most important issues and critical ideas in education reform today.  The field of education never stops changing and professionals are under constant pressure to keep up.</P>

<P><B><I>Positive Insights on Education</I></B> introduces the people behind the headlines, books, and movements that challenge teachers, parents, and school systems to rethink their assumptions:
<UL>
<LI>Are the needs of at-risk students really any different from those of "normal" or even "gifted" students?
<LI>Will violence destroy public education?
<LI>What are collaborative school systems and do they work?
<LI>Are there effective alternatives to outcome-based education?
<LI>Are standardized tests really effective?  Is there another way?
<LI>Is bureaucracy strangling our school systems?
</UL></P>

<P>These are only a few of the many wide-ranging questions being asked.  The focus too often has been on students who "won't" learn or teachers who "can't" teach.  Perhaps the problems, and the solutions, are more complex&#151;and more deeply grounded in our society&#151;than we are willing to admit.  <B><I>Positive Insights on Education</I></B> documents truly original approaches, designed to deepen our insight and revolutionize basic attitudes.</P>

<P><B><I>Positive Insights on Education</I></B> includes two facilitator's guides (covering six sessions each) that profile the experts involved, give directions on setting up workshops or seminars to be used in conjunction with the twelve 30-minute programs, and follow-up questions to further stimulate debate and understanding.  The program was produced by Phi Delta Kappa, Bloomington, Indiana, in conjunction with AIT.  &copy; 1996</P>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<H2><I>Positive Insights on Education</I></H2>

<H2>Programs</H2>

<P><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/meier.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Deborah Meier <I>Collaborative Schools: Sharing the Power</I></B><BR>
Ms Meier focuses on the idea that schools should view themselves as membership communities in which students, teachers, and parents work collaboratively; a "membership community," not a "service organization." (28:55)</P>

<P><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/levin.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Henry Levin <I>Accelerated Schools: Raising the Speed Limit</I></B><BR>
Dr. Levin argues that no student need be subjected to the "remedial" approach and that all students have the same basic needs for stimulation and creative thinking; at-risk students excel under accelerated learning just as all other students. (29:37)</P>

<P><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/prothrow.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Deborah B Prothrow-Stith<I> Youth Violence: A New Public Health Issue</I></B><BR>
Dr. Prothrow-Stith confronts the issue of violence in the schools and presents it as a public health issue; what are the roots of school violence?  Is it an outgrowth of our society?  How do we deal with it in the very real world of the neighborhood school? (29:10)</P>

<P><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/daggett.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Willard R. Daggett <I>American Schools: Catching Up to the Future</I></B><BR>
Dr. Daggett propels us into the debate on why American schools need to do a better job of preparing students for the world in which they will work; is American education caught in a time-warp? (29:31)</P>

<P><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/spady.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>William G. Spady <I>Outcome-Based Education: Panacea or Poison</I></B><BR>
Dr. Spady  concentrates on outcome-based attitudes in education: "Anything that's new and isn't old and familiar is being challenged, if not outlawed&#133; [and] that leaves education in an extremely vulnerable position." (29:18)</P>

<P><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/simonds.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Robert L. Simonds <I>Beyond OBE: Seeking Common Ground</I></B><BR>
Dr. Simonds argues that the needs of traditional Christian families are not being met by the public schools: "If we can get schools back to what they used to be, that's what made America famous anyway&#133;our education system." (29:10)</P>

<P><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/shakesha.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Charol Shakeshaft <I>Preventing Sexual Abuse in Schools</I></B><BR>
Dr. Shakeshaft  focuses on the problem of sexual abuse and sexual harassment&#133;from data gathered nationwide, Dr. Shakeshaft has found that it occurs in all kinds of districts, to all kinds of students, and at all grade levels.</P>

<P><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/neil.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Monty Neil <I>Alternatives to Standardized Testing</I></B><BR>
Dr. Neil argues that standardized testing is harmful to the educational health of a majority of students.  He proposes an alternative assessment system that provides teachers with a more effective evaluative process to improve learning, curriculum, and teaching.</P>

<P><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/coles.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Robert Coles <I>Moral Development of Children</I></B><BR>
Dr. Coles discusses moral development in education; what is the place of teaching values in modern-day America? Dr. Coles believes that there are both positive and negative moral lessons being taught in our schools and urges a closer look at the values that we convey.</P>

<P><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/sternber.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Robert Sternberg <I>Intelligence, Creativity, and Thinking Styles</I></B><BR>
Dr. Sternberg speaks to the question of the "single trait notion of intelligence."  IQ testing is fundamental to American education; but what are the true components of intelligence?</P>

<P><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/howard.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Jeff Howard <I>Redefining Intelligence</I></B><BR>
Dr. Howard contends that our belief structure of innate intelligence has had devastating results: "smart is not something that you are, but something you get."  He calls for an alternative paradigm of development.
</P>

<P><BR CLEAR=LEFT><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/moe.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Terry Moe <I>Institutional Reform and the Future of Schools</I></B><BR>
Dr. Moe argues that schools are being buried by bureaucracy, making it impossible for educators to teach effectively.  He argues that schools must be taken out of politics, allowing parents and teachers to develop the most effective ways of teaching. </P>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Moving into the 21st Century&#151;<BR><SMALL>creative solutions to the most difficult educational problems.</SMALL></H2>

<P>Critics have subjected our school system to a withering barrage of fire:  The schools are violent and unsafe&#133;students aren't learning enough&#133;traditional morality is being undermined&#133;tax dollars should go to private schools, who do the job better.  There are those who feel the entire system is falling apart.</P>

<P><B><I>Positive Insights on Education</I></B> provides a thorough guide to the most compelling recent thinking on education reform, in a question-and-answer format conducted by program host Dr. Phillip Harris, director of the Center for Professional Development and Services for Phi Delta Kappa International.  The videos are designed to address the concerns not only of educators, but of parents and every individual concerned about quality education today.</P>

<P><B><I>Positive Insights on Education</I></B> leads us into the world of new horizons, new thinking, and proven innovative techniques.  It is designed to be the basis for workshops and seminars that involve diverse elements of the educational process in the most compelling debate of our time.</P>

<HR>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
