<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Look Ahead - Respecting Diversity</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1>Respecting Diversity</H1>
<H2>in the Classroom</H2>
<HR>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Staff Development</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
One 60-minute program; Multicultural training for administrators,<BR>teachers, and pre- and in-service staff</P>
<HR>

<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/resp1.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<H3>How do diversity, ethnicity, and cultural pluralism operate in our culture?</H3>

<P><BR CLEAR=RIGHT><B><I>Respecting Diversity</I></B> presents many actual classroom situations to demonstrate why multiculturalism is important, offering innovative ideas in exploring the richness of culture and ethnicity.
<UL>
<LI>What is the difference between culture, ethnicity, and race?
<LI>Do children in a classroom respond (or fail to respond), interact (or fail to interact), due to cultural differences, and not necessarily because of our preconceived expectations?
<LI>What is the importance of religion and language in the multicultural framework?
</UL></P>

<P><B><I>Respecting Diversity</I></B> offers a variety of ways to use the material.  As broadcast programming it is a tool for self-paced, in-school staff development; it can also be used as a workshop program.  Wither way, <B><I>Respecting Diversity</I></B> meets these key goals:</P>
<UL>
<LI>To provide strategies for developing multicultural curricula.
<LI>To help teachers be responsive, well-informed, and sensitive to the issues confronting students from diverse backgrounds.
<LI>To suggest effective skills and strategies for teachers working with multicultural classrooms.
<LI>To provide a theoretical framework for work in multicultural education.
</UL>

<P><B><I>Respecting Diversity</I></B> includes a 50-page facilitator's guide with video tie-ins (including breaks for full-day and half-day workshops) and handout masters for each aspect of the program.  The program and companion guide were produced by Del Rey Communications, Chicago, in association with AIT. &copy; 1996</P>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<P><B><I>Respecting Diversity</I></B> presents the wide sweep of multiculturalism.  We see the positive side of a multicultural curriculum in action as a Native American woman introduces children to the process and philosophy behind making a "button blanket."  The students make their own blankets, and in so doing describe their own lives.  Suddenly, Native American culture merges with mainstream and other cultures, each retaining its identity, but seeing the world through new eyes.</P>

<H2>Program Segments</H2>
<DL>
<DT><B>Segment 1</B>
<DD>Involves viewers by getting them to think about their own cultural background: " List the top four cultural identifiers which best describe who you are."
<DT><B>Segment 2</B>
<DD>Introduces more complex cultural identifiers: "Try using thin/thick descriptors to define your own culture."
<DT><B>Segment 3</B>
<DD>Brings family backgrounds into the equation: "Describe the ways you and your family regard your own cultural orientation."
<DT><B>Segment 4 </B>
<DD>Confronts street language in the school: "If the content is accurate and communication clear, should a teacher accept linguistically different English?"
<DT><B>Segment 5</B>
<DD>Raises the question, do we sometimes exclude others on the basis of mistaken impressions?: "How can teachers and students change 
communication patterns so that students feel more involved?"
<DT><B>Segment 6</B>
<DD>Stimulates sensitivity to the needs of others: "What concerns about religious observance should be respected in school?"
<DT><B>Segment 7</B>
<DD>Puts viewers in others' shoes: "How can we use the experience of a Puerto Rican immigrant in a multicultural approach to thematic exploration?"
<DT><B>Segment 8</B>
<DD>Broadens the learning experience through interaction with another culture: "The Button Blanket Project: A lesson in participating in another world."
<DT><B>Segment 9</B>
<DD>Tests communication skills with all students: "What strategies can you use to address differences in learning style and social interaction?"
<DT><B>Segment 10</B>
<DD>Asks, Is multiculturalism necessary?: "Some critics feel that multiculturalism may disunite America.  What do you think?"
</DL>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Exploring the Richness of Our Cultures,<BR>Celebrating Diversity&#151;An Exciting<BR>Experience for Teacher and Student Alike!</H2>
<BR>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Walk a Mile in My Shoes</H2>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
If I could be you,<BR>
and you could be me,<BR>
for just one hour&#151;</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
If we could find a way<BR>
to get inside<BR>
each other's minds.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
If you could see you<BR>
through my eyes<BR>
instead of your ego,<BR>
I believe you'd be<BR>
surprised to see<BR>
that you've been blind.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<I>chorus</I><BR>
Walk a mile in my shoes,<BR>
Walk a mile in my shoes,<BR>
Hey, before you accuse,<BR>
Criticize and abuse<BR>
Walk a mile in my shoes.</P>

<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
&#151;Written by Joe South,<BR>Courtesy of Lowery Music, Inc.</P>

<P><B><I>Respecting Diversity in the Classroom</I></B> is the ideal pathway to a widening of our cultural horizons.</P>

<HR>

