<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Look Ahead - Technology in the Classroom</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1>Technology in the Classroom</H1>
<HR>

<H2>Staff Development</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
Four 15-minute technology training programs for teachers, administrators, and adults</P>
<HR>

<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/technol1.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<H3>The on-ramp to the superhighway.</H3>

<P><BR CLEAR=RIGHT>Confused and intimidated by the myriad, bewildering technological choices?  This timely video program addresses the issue of integrating the latest classroom technologies into today's learning experience.  <B><I>Technology in the Classroom</I></B> is for both the computer novice and the techno-literate.</P>

<P>CD-ROM, laserdisc, the World Wide Web, multimedia&#151;just what is all this and exactly how does it work?  Come discover:</P>
<UL>
<LI>The basics of digital vs. analog, and what terms such as CPU, RAM, and hard drive mean.
<LI>A comprehensive look at LAN, modems, new storage devices, and the Web.
<LI>The multimedia explosion&#151;on-board cameras, midi-sound, 16-bit sound and 24-bit color, interactive platforms, and more.
<LI>The world of e-mail, the Internet, satellite links, and the entire broad avenue of worldwide communication.
</UL>

<P><B><I>Technology in the Classroom</I></B> is a series of four 15-minute programs and companion in-depth training guide that explains fully and engagingly the latest teaching technologies.  It is being developed by the technology experts at New Leaf Media and will be distributed by AIT). &copy; 1997</P>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Explore the New Wolrd&#151;A World of Possibilities</H2>

<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/technol2.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P>An exploration of the most powerful new classroom tools ever developed, <B>Technology in the Classroom</B> takes us on a tour of a world of possibilities.</P>

<H2>Programs</H2>
<OL>
<LI><P><B>The Internet and Your Classroom</B> What does the Internet mean for you and your classroom?  This fast-paced program takes an informative look at the Internet and its evolution.  Viewers learn terms and concepts such as FTP, e-mail, and the World Wide Web.  An in-depth look at this world-linking technology!</P>

<LI><P><B>Inside Multimedia and the CD-ROM</B> The advent of the CD-ROM, sound cards, and video cards have transformed computers from high-tech typewriters to multimedia teaching tools.  But how do they work and what can they do for me?  Viewers will soon come to understand key concepts such as analog to digital conversion, 16-bit sound, and 24-bit color, just for starters!  A must for those who field student questions about technology, troubleshoot, and offer input on media purchasing decisions.</P>

<LI><P><B>Understanding Our Digital World</B> What do such terms as digital tape, digital sound, and digital video mean?  This program emphasizes understanding the information revolution in terms of how it is used via computer discs, RAM circuitry, digital tape, and optical discs.  How is the information transferred down phone lines, through TV's, or via satellite?  The essential processes of the technology age are explained.</P>

<LI><P><B>The New Computer Technology</B> Computers aren't what they used to be&#151;they are much more!  Modems, LAN systems, new storage devices, CD-ROM, external hard drives, on-board cameras, and midi-sound have radically changed the way we use computers in the classroom.  This video examines not only the basics of RAM, CPU, and hard drives, but covers the latest technologies as well.  An excellent introduction for the novice and an invaluable update for the techno-literate.</P>
</OL>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Surviving the Information Age!</H2>

<P><B>Technology in the Classroom</B> covers the latest developments in a fast-paced, informative format.  From the real basics, such as RAM, hard drives, and the CPU to the most advanced technolgies in CD-ROM, the WWW, and laserdiscs, this timely series can be a lifesaver.  Few programs can explain not only the <I>what</I> but the <I>why</I> and <I>how</I> of these bewildering computer advances.  The Information Age demands that these new technologies be integrated into the classroom&#151;<B>Technology in the Classroom</B> offers you the opportunity to experience just how fulfilling it can be!</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/technol3.gif"><BR>The world is only inches away, and this series will take you there!</P>

<HR>

