<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Look Ahead - We Are the Children</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1>We Are the Children</H1>
<HR>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Social Studies</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
Thirty-six 20-minute Multi&#150;cultural education programs for students grades 4&#150;6.</P>
<HR>

<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/childrn1.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<H3>Hold on to your hats!  You and your students are about to embark on a unique journey.</H3>

<P><BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<B><I>We Are the Children</I></B> gives you an insider's look into cultures as diverse as the wide world has to offer.  Explore 36 different cultures, from the vantage point of children involved in real-life adventures.  Just seeing children from other cultures living lives much as their own (and yet so different!), students learn to appreciate and explore the source of our wonderful human variety.</P>

<P>In many countries, cultures from all over the world have retained their identity and unique flavor.  The videos provide a dazzling glimpse of this great diversity and the accompanying guide will engage students in many cross-curricular activities.  Students become involved in the process of exchanging ideas and thinking critically about just what makes us alike, and what makes us different.</P>

<P>From each lesson students will learn to:</P>
<UL>
<LI>Locate the geographic regions that are discussed in each program.
<LI>Identify special features of each culture's customs and traditions.
<LI>Compare and contrast the life of other children with their own.
<LI>Learn about language, religion, and each culture's unique contribution to the arts.
<LI>See how the parents and families from other cultures make their living, whether it be farming, mining, fishing, the professions, or one of dozens of others.
</UL>

<P><B><I>We Are the Children</I></B> is a collection of 36 20-minute videos accompanied by a teacher's guide that includes Learning Goals, a Program Summary, Video Facts and Places, Key Terms, Discussion Questions, and Activities.  It is distributed by AIT (the Agency for Instructional Technology) and was produced by the South African Broadcasting Corporation (SABC). &copy; 1995 by AIT.</P>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER><I>We Are the Children</I></H2>
<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/childrn2.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P><B><I>We Are the Children</I></B> transports us to the villages and farms, towns and cities of 36 different cultures.  Join the children of the world in this fascinating look into their customs and traditions, their problems and explorations.  Use the videos and the accompanying guide to create specialized activities for individuals, groups, or the entire classroom!  Choose any of the programs or all 36.</P>

<H2>Programs</H2>
<OL>
<LI><B>Strike, the Tswana Boy</B> (17:49)
<LI><B>Maya the Hindu Girl</B> (19:13)
<LI><B>Errol, the Boy from Mitchell's Plain</B> (18:50)
<LI><B>Tshidi, the Mosotho Girl</B> (18:12)
<LI><B>Racquel, the Spanish Girl</B> (18:11)
<LI><B>Francois, the Drakensberg Choir Boy</B> (18:11)
<LI><B>Mngevisa, theTsonga Boy</B> (19:08)
<LI><B>Sholem, the Jewish Boy</B> (18:21)
<LI><B>Tojo, the Portuguese Boy</B> (17:32)
<LI><B>Rupert, the German Boy</B> (17:33)
<LI><B>Tfolakela, the Swazi Girl</B> (17:35)
<LI><B>Fatima, the Muslim Girl</B> (19:07)
<LI><B>Muofhe, the Venda Girl</B> (18:34)
<LI><B>Dimitri, the Greek Boy</B> (18:24)
<LI><B>Safira, the Polish Girl</B> (19:27)
<LI><B>Sylvia, the Hungarian Girl</B> (18:44)
<LI><B>Marco, the Italian Boy</B> (19:15)
<LI><B>Naomi, the Afrikaans Girl</B> (18:24)
<LI><B>Debbie, the Chinese Girl</B> (19:15)
<LI><B>Malope, the Pedi Boy</B> (18;55)
<LI><B>Kees, the Dutch Boy</B> (19:31)
<LI><B>Craig, the English Boy</B> (19:06)
<LI><B>Mandla, the Zulu Boy</B> (19:11)
<LI><B>Judy and Her Dutch Huguenot Connections</B> (19:39)
<LI><B>Yandisa, the Xhosa Boy</B> (19:21)
<LI><B>Kim, the Austrian Girl</B> (18:49)
<LI><B>John, the Scots Boy</B> (19:36)
<LI><B>Robert, the Boy from Yugoslavia</B> (18:32)
<LI><B>Marina, the Russian Girl</B> (19:09)
<LI><B>Keval, the Sugar-Cane Prince</B> (19:15)
<LI><B>Tahla, the Lebanese Girl</B> (18:40)
<LI><B>Valerie, the Mauritian Girl</B> (19:24)
<LI><B>Pepe, the Chilean Boy</B> (19:21)
<LI><B>Elif, the Turkish Girl</B> (18:52)
<LI><B>Kgopiso, the Mosotho Boy</B> (19:43)
<LI><B>Brett, the American Girl</B> (19:31)
</OL>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>The great experiment!</H2>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>As the world's cultures become increasingly interconnected,<BR> can we all learn to get along?</H3>

<P><B><I>We Are the Children</I></B> explores 36 different cultures through the eyes and lives of their children.</P>

<P>Meet:</P>
<P><B>Debbie, the Chinese Girl</B>&#151; Debbie and her brother, Colin, are shopping for gifts for their grandmother's birthday when she loses her special hat.  It is part of the costume she must wear for the Dragon Dance and she is afraid to tell her mother.  Debbie can't enjoy preparing for her grandmother's birthday and at last tells her mother what has happened.  Her mother knows all about it!  The shopkeeper found the hat, which arrives just in time for the dance.  Debbie learns an important lesson&#151;it is better to admit having done wrong and then do your best to make it right.</P>

<P><B>Robert, the Boy from Yugoslavia</B>&#151;Robert is a dreamer; he needs to finish his project in industrial design, but he is thinking about ice hockey, his dog, golf and tennis, and especially his grandparents, who have come from Croatia for a visit.  The family attends Catholic services on the Feast Day of St. Jerome (Robert's middle name).  By working in his father's butcher shop, Robert earns enough money to pay for obedience lessons for Tina, his dog.  He also manages to finish his project, and his father gives him a hockey helmet to recognize his achievements.</P>

<P><B>Tfolakela, the Swazi Girl</B>&#151; Tfolakela lives in a rural district.  The youngest child&#151;and only girl&#151;she has never been far from home.  Her grandmother arrives to take her by car to the big city.  Grandmother is known as  Mother Culture" because she has established a Swazi museum by collecting artifacts.  Tfolakela is astounded by the beautiful things in her home&#151;a microwave and real beds!  She and Musa, a young friend of grandmother, tour the city.  When it is time to go home, Tfolakela gives grandmother her prize hen as a sign of her gratitude.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/childrn3.gif"><BR><B>We Are the Children&#133;<I>of the world!</I></B></P>

