<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Look Ahead - World in the Balance</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1>World in the Balance</H1>
<HR>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Ecology/Geology</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
Four 15-minute programs for students in grades 7&#150;12</P>
<HR>

<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/world1.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<H3>The tangled web of economic growth, geometric population expansion, and environmental protection.</H3>

<P><BR CLEAR=RIGHT><B><I>World in the Balance</I></B> takes us on a tour of the world to explore the interrelated problems of population expansion, the inevitable development that follows in a consumer world, and the need to generate a sensible response to environmental damage.  Beautifully photographed, this wide-ranging investigation identifies the many elements of this critical issue.  In a balanced and thoughtful approach, Cliff Lonsdale guides us through the maze of conflicting interests and answers.</P>

<P>Who are the players, what are the stakes, is degradation inevitable? <B><I>World in the Balance</I></B> presents numerous viewpoints that pose often diametrically opposed responses.  Will free-market forces resolve the problems on their own?  Controlled growth, no growth?  Government policy vs. local response?  Nothing shows our interrelatedness more than exploring how every decision we make in the modern world affects every economy, every culture, every environment.</P>

<P><B><I>World in the Balance</I></B> consists of four 15-minute videos, plus a teacher's guide, designed for in-depth classroom discussion and review.  The program is a production of Black Ink Productions. &copy; 1996</P>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<P><B>Part 1: <I>6.4 Billion: Will the Earth Drown in People?</I></B>  opens in India, with the basic needs and harsh realities of life in a developing nation.  Soon all developing nations will be entering the consumer age; since development is inevitable, will the earth be slowly strangled as a result?</P>

<P><B>Part 2: <I>Opposing Options/Conflicting Answers</I></B> presents the many conflicting views that reasonable people have on the most basic questions.  Will the free-market economy heal all wounds, address all problems through the power of marketplace forces?  Is government policy, unifying purpose and setting goals, the only curb on greed and devastation?</P>

<P><B>Part 3: <I>Government as Hero, Government as  the Problem</I></B> assesses several strategies for balancing growth with environmental health.  What works, what doesn't?  Subsidies, incentives, governmental regulation in general are explored, along with the national government/local action scenarios.  Who controls growth and how&#151;what are the alternatives to misguided policies?</P>

<P><B>Part 4:  <I>Symbiotic Solutions:</I></B>  The Local Connection  presents several alternatives that demonstrate local solutions to global problems:  a village in Zimbabwe uses tourism to stop the slaughter of poaching; a group of industrial plants in Denmark create a symbiotic relationship that turns one plant's pollution into another plant's useful product.  Innovative answers can restore ecological balance.</P>

<TABLE WIDTH="75%" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
"If only another one or two billion of us start behaving like Western consumers, how on earth are we all going to survive the 21st Century?"
</TD><TD ROWSPAN=2>
<IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/world2.gif">
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>
&#151;Cliff Lonsdale, host
</TD</TR>
</TABLE>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>

<HR WIDTH="50%">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>It is <I>our<BR><B><BIG>World in the Balance</BIG></B></I></H2>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>World population will reach 6.4 billion by the<BR>year 2000&#151;is environmental disaster inevitable?</H2>

<P><B><I>World in the Balance</I></B> is a beautifully photographed examination of the dichotomy of economic growth and environmental protection.  Cliff Lonsdale travels the globe to demonstrate the problems and some novel solutions.  From India to China, Zimbabwe to Ontario, Denmark to Maryland, <B><I>World in the Balance</I></B> discusses the role of government, free-market forces, local action, environmental activism, and industrial self-regulation as it probes today's solutions.  The problems may grow geometrically if we do not develop innovative answers today.</P>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="/images/ahead/first/world3.gif"><BR>
<B><I>Will man's impact on a fragile planet ultimately strangle us?</I></B></P>

<HR>

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
