<HEAD><TITLE>Generating Tips on AIT.Net</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1><I>AIT.NET</I> Tips</H1>
<HR>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Generating Tips on AIT.Net</H1>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>By</H3>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>John C. Rauch</H2>
<HR WIDTH="75%">

<TABLE WIDTH="100%" CELLPADDING="5"><TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP><H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Grade Levels</H4>
<UL><LI>Adult Continuing Education
</UL></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>Curriculum Areas</H4>
<UL><LI>Math
<LI>Science
</UL></TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT Products</H4>
<UL><LI>Workplace Readiness
</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=3>
<H4>Keywords</H4>
Test Trial Sample Example Hint Hints HTML Tip Tips Create Creating Writing </TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR>
<P>Since the text that you enter into the text box on the <I>Submit a Tip to AIT.Net</I> page will be placed in an HTML file, you can use HTML commands to visually enhance your tip.</P>
<P></P>
<P>HTML commands are plain text typed inbetween less than (&lt;) and greater than (&gt;) symbols.  All of the commands that you will be interested in using will have both a beginning and ending command.  The ending command differs from the beginning command only by the addition of a slash to the right of the less than symbol (&lt;/HTML Command&gt;).</P>
<P></P>
<P>The following list shows some of the HTML commands, and how they will affect the text:</P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Bold-face:</B> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;B&gt;Bold-Face&lt;/B&gt;
<LI><I>Italis: </I> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;I&gt;Italics&lt;/I&gt;
<LI><BIG>Increase type size: </BIG> &nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;BIG&gt;Increase type size&lt;/BIG&gt;
<LI><SMALL>Decrease type size:</SMALL> &nbsp; &nbsp; &lt;SMALL&gt;Decrease type size&lt;/SMALL&gt;
<LI>Super<SUP>Script</SUP>: &nbsp; &nbsp; Super&lt;SUP&gt;Script&lt;/SUP&gt;
<LI>Sub<SUB>Script</SUB>: &nbsp; &nbsp; Sub&lt;SUB&gt;Script&lt;/SUB&gt;
</UL>
<P></P>
<P>Additionally of interest, there are some characters which are not recognized by HTML as simple characters.  To use these characters, you need to know their equivalent HTML named value.  Some of these characters which you may find useful are cited below, with their equivalent HTML named value:</P>
<UL>
<LI>&amp; Ampersand:&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &amp;amp;
<LI>&lt; Less Than: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&amp;lt;
<LI>&gt; Greater Than: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &amp;gt;
<LI>&copy; Copyright: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; $amp;copy;
<LI>&reg; Registered Trademark: &nbsp; &nbsp; &amp;reg;
<LI>&#153; Tradmark: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &amp;#153;
<LI>&#151; Em-Dash: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &amp;#151;
<LI>&#150; En-Dash: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &amp;#150;
</UL>
<P></P>
<P>These commands should prove helpful for accenting your tips, but this is only the tip of the iceberg.  For those of you who are motivated self-learners, I would suggest the O'Reilly &amp; Associates book <I>HTML: The Definitive Guide</I>.  This is the book with the koala on the cover.  On-Line HTML primers also exist, a simple search on the World Wide Web for <I>"Learning HTML"</I> using <A HREF="http://www.lycos.com/">Lycos</A> yeilded <A HREF="http://wwwhost.utexas.edu/learn/pub/html.html">Learning to Publish - Learning HTML</A></P>
<HR>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Information about John C. Rauch</H2><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><I>Software Developer and Web-Master</I></H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><BIG>AIT<BR>Agency for Instructinal Technology<BR>Bloomington, IN</BIG></P>
<HR WIDTH="75%">

<H2>Teaching Background:</H2>
<P>While I am not an educator, I have found that teaching comprises a surprisingly large amount of my time.  As the Web-Master for AIT, I have found a need and employee interest in educating some of AIT's employees on the Internet, and the development of Web Pages.</P>
<P></P>
<P>To this end, I have offered HTML training classes to those employees who have indicated an interest in developing their own Home-Pages on the World Wide Web.  These classess were well recieved, and everyone who took the course gained, at minimum, a working knowledge of the HTML language, and how the internet works.</P>
<H2>Personal Interests:</H2>
<P>One never stops learning, but I finished my Bachelor's Degree in Electrical Engineering from the University of Missouri-Rolla in 1994.</P>
<P></P>
<P>After graduation, I accepted employment with the Flight Simulation department of McDonnell Douglas Aerospace.  While working for McDonnell Douglas, I was responsible for the maintenance and upgrade of some of the Image Generation systems used for "Out-The-Window" visuals and target generation.</P>
<P></P>
<P>In February of 1996, I opted to be closer to my fiance&#233; and her family, taking this position at AIT.  My current position is that of Software Developer and Web-Master, working to bring a strong Internet presence to AIT.</P>
<P><B>John C. Rauch</B> may be reached via E-mail at <A HREF="MAILTO:jrauch@ait.net">jrauch@ait.net</A>.
<HR>

