<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Fall 1995 - Tips from teachers</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Fall 1995</H1>
<HR>

<H1>Tips from teachers</H1>

<P>Tips from teachers topped the list when we asked educators what they wanted in an online service. In response, AIT has created <A HREF="/tips/"><B>AIT.Net Tips</B></A>,  an online tips exchange for teachers, and <B>Tips from teachers</B>, a section of "AIT.Net News" that includes some of the tips received through <A HREF="/tips/"><B>AIT.Net Tips</B></A> or by fax, phone, or mail.</P>

<P>A classroom tip is anything: any hint, activity, strategy, game, resource, project, or lesson plan that you think will help another teacher. It's easy to share or seek a tip. Simply access <A HREF="/tips/"><B>AIT.Net Tips</B></A>.</P>

<HR ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=50%>

<P><B>When were you born?</B> submitted by Rhonda Hutto, Lawrence County Center of Technology, Lawrence County, Moulton, Alabama. In addition to completing in-class projects based on <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.htm"><B>Applied Communication</B></A> materials, Ms. Hutto's students work on career-oriented research papers and literature.</P>

<P>One tip that I learned at an <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.htm"><B>Applied Communication</B></A> workshop is to have the class silently organize themselves according to their birthdates. I use this activity when I'm teaching Module 1, Lesson 2 (Barriers that Affect Workplace Communication). Because my class is small, I take them outside and ask them to organize themselves by birthdate without using words or writing. They usually do a very good job. Since the lesson is taught soon after the school year begins, it's a fun activity for the kids and is also an icebreaker of sorts.</P>

<HR ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=50%>

<P><B>Creating Billboards and Yellow Page Ads</B> submitted by Rose M. Kipp, Wyalusing High School, Wyalusing Area School District, Wyalusing, Pennsylvania. Grade levels 9-12 are offered <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.htm"><B>Applied Communication</B></A>, along with a complementary literature component. Kipp notes that "most of [my students] desire to seek better jobs and many want to leave the area.... About one third of my classes attend the local vo-tech school. Some are, as seniors, involved in the on-the-job training or youth apprenticeship programs. Many are simply looking for a purpose . . . These courses are valuable for all these groups."</P>

<P>One of the things my kids enjoyed was designing an advertisement like a billboard and an ad for the yellow pages for a business they'd like to work for in the future. They highlighted the things the company would offer. The billboard posters and yellow page ads were displayed around the room during open house and attracted a lot of positive attention. These kinds of kids often have a better idea of what they want to do as a career goal than someone going on to college. It was good for them to get these ideas down in an artistic way.</P>

<HR ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=50%>

<P><B>"Take This Job . . . "</B> submitted by Susan Bizzozero, Yough High School, Herminie, Pennsylvania. Susan Bizzozero uses <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.htm"><B>Applied Communication</B></A> as supplemental material in two courses, Career Prep 11 and Career Prep 12. Local businesses are involved in guest presentations and mock interviews.</P>

<P>"Take This Job " is designed to give the career prep student practical experience in obtaining a job. To supplement the present curriculum, we use a Total Quality Learning plan that is divided into five stages: deciding upon a career, creating a r&eacute;sum&eacute;, applying for a position, taking a job interview, and preparing an action plan. Our goal is for each career prep student to graduate with a career portfolio that consists of the following:
<OL TYPE=1>
<LI>A personal inventory of job skills, experience, and preferences.
<LI>A r&eacute;sum&eacute; (6-10 copies on linen paper).
<LI>Three letters of reference.
<LI>Interviews with employees, employers, and classroom speakers.
<LI>Reference material (models of letters of application and cover letters, models of job applications and r&eacute;sum&eacute;s, and a database of contacts).
<LI>Mock interview assessment.
<LI>Assessments by self, a peer, and a professional.
<LI>Computer disk containing the r&eacute;sum&eacute;, references, and a database of contacts.
<LI>Plan of action.
</OL></P>

<P>During the initial stage of our plan, students use a variety of sources to determine career interests and options. For example, a self-assessment inventory is used to determine occupational strengths, interests, and experience. Once suitable career areas are chosen, students learn more about them through research by using written sources and observing and interviewing others. Each student assesses his or her findings, all of which are kept in a career portfolio to determine if a particular career choice is suitable for him or her.</P>

<P>In the second stage, students write and create professional job-quality r&eacute;sum&eacute;s using the five Macintoshes that are available. The r&eacute;sum&eacute; is saved on a disk so it can be updated at any time during or after high school. If a student is applying for a job, he or she can obtain a professional copy of the r&eacute;sum&eacute; through the English teacher. Upon graduation, each student who completes the course receives 12 copies of the r&eacute;sum&eacute; printed on linen paper for use in seeking future employment. Each student is also encouraged to obtain three letters of reference for the career portfolio.</P>

<P>In the third stage, students hunt for jobs through a variety of sources, including local newspapers, employment offices, and contact people. Using the Macintosh to write cover letters, students apply for up to three positions which interest them. At this point, students focus on the importance of good writing skills in developing persuasive letters of application. These letters are also stored on the student's personal disk for future reference.</P>

<P>In the fourth stage, students learn how to speak, act, and dress during job interviews. Books, videotapes, and peer evaluations are used to prepare students for "Mock Interview Day." On mock interview day, members from the community conduct mock interviews of career prep students. Students are assessed by the professional interviewer as if they were applying for a real position. The professional and self-assessments of the mock interview help students evaluate, refine, and improve their job interviewing skills.</P>

<P>In the final stage, each student develops a plan for seeking career employment. Each student then determines what steps to take next, how to take those steps, what realities need to be faced, and what his or her vision is for the future. This, too, is kept in the career portfolio.</P>

<P>It is important for all students to learn <A HREF="http://www.bio.com/hr/search/search_1.html"><B>job-seeking skills</B></A>, but for the career prep student it is essential. A goal of <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.htm"><B>Applied Communication</B></A> is to make students aware of a workplace that stresses Total Quality Management, "a perfect product every time"; therefore, the use of a Total Quality Learning format benefits career prep students by serving as a model for TQM in the workplace and providing a means of refining and upgrading students' job-seeking skills. The result: students are better prepared to obtain and maintain a job in today's changing workplace.</P>

<HR ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=50%>

<P><IMG SRC="/images/pictures/tips_kch.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT ALT="Let's Cook!">
<B>Prep for Success Course Outline</B> submitted by Kris Laughlin, Highview Alternative Program, Robbinsdale #281, New Hope, Minnesota. Ms. Laughlin teaches in a suburban area and has 15 to 18 students per class. She has integrated <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c317.htm"><B>Workplace Readiness</B></A> material into a course called Prep for Success.<BR CLEAR=LEFT></P>

<P><B>Outcomes:</B>
<OL TYPE=1>
<LI>To incorporate themes/skills for being successful in life.
<LI>To incorporate the <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c317.htm"><B>Workplace Readiness</B></A> concepts of teamwork, problem solving, and self-management skills.
<LI>To incorporate projects into the curriculum.
</OL></P>

<P><B>Themes/Skills for Success:</B>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD> September</TD><TD> Who Am I?</TD></TR>
<TR><TD> October</TD><TD> Careers (awareness, research, experience)</TD></TR>
<TR><TD> November</TD><TD> Goal Setting</TD></TR>
<TR><TD> December</TD><TD> Thinking/Decision Making Skills</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>January</TD><TD> Communication Skills/Getting Along with Others</TD></TR>
<TR><TD> February</TD><TD> Studying Skills</TD></TR>
<TR><TD> March</TD><TD> Organizational Skills/Time Management</TD></TR>
<TR><TD> April</TD><TD> Community Involvement</TD></TR>
<TR><TD> May</TD><TD> Leisure Time</TD></TR>
</TABLE></P>

<P><B>Schedule:</B><BR>
<I>Mondays</I>:  Activities that develop team-building, problem solving, and self-management skills.<BR>
<I>Tuesdays-Thursdays</I>:  Projects, field trips, and activities incorporating skills.<BR>
<I>Fridays</I>:  Themes/skills for success.</P>

<P><B>Evaluation</B>:  Typically, projects will be evaluated on the team-building, problem solving, and self-management skills used, as well as quality. Field trips will be evaluated on participation, questions, and follow-up. Skills for success (Friday themes) will be evaluated on participation and quality of work.</P>

<P><B>Seminars</B>:  Transition skills such as cover letters, r&eacute;sum&eacute;s, and interviews will be handled in seminars. These may take place at an hour other than the Prep for Success class.</P>

<P><B>Individual project/book</B>:<BR>
An individual project will be required for the first credit and a book for the second credit. [The credit outline lists a wide variety of books, videotapes, audiocassettes, and projects. Books include "One Minute Manager;" "Men Are from Mars, Women Are from Venus;" and "Managing Assertively." Videotapes include "Take this Job and Love It!" and "How to Get Results with People." Audiocassettes include "Making Love Work" and "Seven Habits of Highly Effective People." Projects include <A HREF="http://www.pathfinder.com/@@FwMIdJFoQgAAQBJC/vg/Welcome/welcome.html"><B>gardening</B></A>, surveying former students, planning a field trip, organizing a bedroom, and <A HREF="tips_extra.htm"><B>volunteering</A></B> in the community.]</P>

<H4>Fall 1995 AIT.Net News</H4>
