<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Fall 1995 - Technology Watch: Going online</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Fall 1995</H1>
<HR>

<P><B>TECHNOLOGY</B>WATCH</P>
<H2>Going online</H2>
<H3>A guide to getting started on the Internet</H3>
<P>(Part One in a Series)</P>

<P><B>Hey, wait a minute! I'm online already. Why should I read this?</B> You're right--you probably know all about getting started, but we've included this article for those who want basic information <B>for someone else...a friend, a co-worker, or the principal down the hall.</B></P>

<P>Have you considered going online, but are not quite sure where to start? This article is the first in a series designed to give you the information you need to get started on the information highway. Future articles will cover choosing an Internet provider, exploring the Internet "toolbox," finding funding for online access, and other aspects of building an onramp to the Information Highway for educators and students.</P>

<P><B>What You Need To Get Online</B><BR>
To go online, you'll need a computer, a modem, telecommunications software, a telephone line, and an Internet provider. The following information is intended to provide an overview of what you should expect and look for. Specific requirements and costs for these items will vary depending on your needs and existing equipment.</P>

<P><B><BIG><BIG>1.</BIG></BIG> A computer.</B> Almost any computer will do. If you have a Mac or PC running Windows, you'll be able to use the more friendly graphical telecommunications software. While even an old Apple IIE can run standard software, it can't run the more popular and easy-to-use graphical interfaces.</P>

<P><B>Costs:</B> Basic desktop computers begin in the $1,000 to $2,000 range; a basic multimedia package will add $300 to $400. If you're buying a computer that runs Windows, be sure to ask about the video card. A 486 computer needs a minimum 1 megabyte RAM (random-access memory) and at least a 32-bit video card.</P>

<P><B><BIG><BIG>2.</BIG></BIG> A modem.</B> The modem is the device that dials a telephone number and allows your computer to communicate on the telephone line. Modem speeds are measured in baud rates or bytes per second (bps). Get the fastest modem that you can--it will save you money in the long run. At a minimum, consider purchasing a 14400 bps modem or even a 28800 bps modem (these are usually referred to as "fourteen four" or "twenty-eight eight" modems). Modem speed determines how quickly you can access online information. Double your modem speed, and you should roughly double your speed of access. An external modem--one that is separate from the computer--is preferable to an internal one. Consider choosing a name brand with a 30-day return policy.</P>

<P><B>Costs:</B> 14400 bps modems begin around $100; 28800 bps modems are closer to $200.</P>

<P><B><BIG><BIG>3.</BIG></BIG> Telecommunications software.</B> Telecommunications software enables your modem and computer to talk to each other and lets you interact with the network. Software with a graphical interface is easy to use, and is often provided free from an Internet service provider, but it can usually be used with only that provider. Standard "terminal emulator" software is available on all computers and works for most providers, but it may be harder to learn and use than graphical software.</P>

<P><B>Costs:</B> Software with a graphical interface is often free from an Internet provider. Internet starter kits include the software and begin around $25.00.</P>

<P><B><BIG><BIG>4.</BIG></BIG> A telephone line.</B> A regular telephone line will work for most online users. (Refer to your phone book for instructions to disable call waiting.) The telephone line can be commercial or residential. Remember, when you dial into a system for online access, you will be using the phone line, and no one else will be able to use the telephone for the duration of your use.</P>

<P><B>Costs:</B> No additional cost, if the Internet provider you choose can be accessed with a local telephone number.</P>

<P><B><BIG><BIG>5.</BIG></BIG> An Internet provider.</B> The phone number your modem dials connects you to a company or organization that provides access to the Internet. Internet providers include freenets, colleges and universities, state or local government, and commercial systems. Freenets are local community bulletin board systems whose services are either free or available for a very low cost. Call your local library or computer store for current information on freenets in your area. Many colleges and universities have Internet connections and provide user accounts for students, employees, and alumni. For state and local government providers, call the state or local department of education to find out if either provides access to the Internet for educators. Commercial systems can be accessed from all over the country for a fee. Most provide free trials and software to access them.</P>

<P><B>Costs:</B> Many commercial Internet providers provide free startup and 10 free hours of use. Monthly fees range from $4.95 to $23.00, the number of free hours per month varies, and charges for additional hours range from $2.00 to $9.00 per hour.</P>

<P><B>TROUBLE</B>SHOOTING</P>

<P>Remember to write down the "help line" telephone numbers for your computer, modem, and software and keep them handy. The people answering those lines are employed to assist you and are your best bet for support.</P>

<P>Adapted from "A Roadmap to Getting Started on the Information Highway" by CalTIP, a joint project of Far West Laboratory and the Santa Clara County Office of Education, funded through the California Department of Education, and from "Basic Internet" &copy;1995, The Greater Cincinnati Television Educational Foundation.</P>

