<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Fall 1995 - Fast Forward: When more than money matters</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Fall 1995</H1>
<HR>

<P><B>FAST</B>FORWARD</P>
<H2>When more than money matters . . . </H2>
<H3>Introduce your students to "Economics at Work"</H3>

<P>What do ice cream, high-top sneakers, and mufflers from Mexico have in common with night school and interest rates? The economics of living and working underlies nearly everything in the world, from the newest flavor launched by <A HREF="http://infonews.com/franchise/baskin"><B>Baskin-Robbins</B></A> to an increase in <A HREF="http://www.llnl.gov/fstc/principals/chase_manhattan.html"><B>Chase Manhattan</B></A>'s lending rate. Your students may understand the costs involved in buying the latest style of high-top sneakers, but do they understand the costs and benefits involved in attending night school?</P>

<P>You know that <A HREF="http://econwpa.wustl.edu/EconFAQ/EconFAQ.html"><B>economics</B></A> is more than money matters--it's a way of understanding life that can give your students an edge in the workplace and throughout their lives. Now you can help your students develop that edge with <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm"><B>Economics at Work</B></A>, a one-semester interactive course developed by the Agency for Instructional Technology and the National Council on Economic Education.</P>

<P>Each of the five modules in the "Economics at Work" curriculum is organized around a central economic activity: producing, exchanging, consuming, saving, and investing. Each module contains up to eight lessons spanning from 12 to 20 class periods of 50 minutes each. Taken together, the five modules provide a comprehensive semester-long experience (75 class periods) in applied economics that meets the guidelines of the SCANS reports and answers the call for a school-to-work curriculum. Lesson content has been drawn from "A Framework for Teaching the Basic Concepts, with Scope and Sequence Guidelines" (1995), the National Council's Master Curriculum Guide in Economics.</P>

<P>When you bring "Economics at Work" into your classroom, your students will see people like themselves involved in real-life situations. The interactive video included in 20 of the 27 lessons gives your students the ability to interact with the stories as they unfold on screen, answering questions and choosing options to solve problems that occur at home and on the job. This interaction will help your students realize how economic concepts and trends, such as the following ones, can affect their own lives and careers.</P>

<P><B>The long-term shift from goods-producing to service-producing employment is expected to continue</B>, according to the <A HREF="http://www.bls.gov"><B>Bureau of Labor Statistics</B></A>, with service industries accounting for 24.5 million of the 26.4 million jobs that are expected to be added during the 1992-2005 period. Although the overall number of manufacturing jobs will decrease, some industries will be adding new jobs. These industries produce newspapers, medical instruments, plastic products, and other goods related to the service sector of the economy.</P>

<P>In <B>Module 1, Producing,</B> your students will learn about the activities needed to transform resources into goods and services that satisfy individual and collective wants.  The production of goods and services may be from material resources, such as the leather and rubber needed to make high-top sneakers, or human resources, such as the knowledge needed to run a machine. As students complete the eight lessons in Module 1, they will
<UL>
<LI>look to the shirts on their backs for a lesson in efficiency,
<LI>see how pretzels put the fizz in soft drink sales, and
<LI>watch a bike shop shift gears in its race to survive.
</UL></P>

<P><IMG SRC="/images/pictures/more_tony.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT>
<I>In the lesson "Personal Best" in Module 1, Anthony learns that profits are a message that a business is doing something right.</I></P>

<P>In one lesson, "Personal Best," Anthony and Kim must start looking for jobs when Mrs. Terhune decides to close her bike shop. As the co-workers apply for positions elsewhere, they--and your students--learn that the ability to earn profits is the driving force of a market economy. Students become active participants in the story as they answer questions (Where should Anthony begin his job search? What could Mrs. Terhune do to increase her profits?) and learn how their answers may affect the situation.</P>

<P><B>The exchange of goods and services can involve transaction costs.</B> The costs of trading with another country for goods or services can include an unfavorable exchange rate or added transportation time. An unintended cost of domestic manufacturing activities can include the cost of handling the discarded containers and packaging that account for 32 percent of all material in America's landfills, according to the <A HREF="http://www.epa.gov"><B>Environmental Protection Agency</B></A>.</P>

<P>The four lessons in "Module 2, Exchanging," cover the activities needed to deliver what is produced to consumers. Students will learn that this exchange may involve goods, such as tickets to a concert, or services, such as the time and effort they'll put in for paychecks. As they work through the module, students will
<UL>
<LI>see how inflation can let the air out of their earnings,
<LI>consider who really pays when they take out the trash, and
<LI>travel the world for parts to build the "all-American" car.
</UL></P>

<P>In the lesson "Build You a 'Vette?" your students will travel to Mexico as they consider whether a parts buyer for an American car manufacturer should buy American or accept a bid from a foreign country. This lesson focuses on money as a medium of exchange, a unit of account, and a store of value; on foreign exchange rates; and on the costs and benefits of foreign trade.</P>

<P><B>Prices for some goods can be affected by state and federal taxes. High prices can lead to improvements in related goods</B>. In 1994 gasoline taxes varied from 7.5 percent in Georgia to 23.7 percent in Nebraska, according to the "Statistical Abstract of the United States." The high gas prices caused by the 1973 oil embargo prompted U.S. car manufacturers to respond to buyer preference for more fuel-efficient vehicles and improve the fuel efficiency of American cars an average of 51 percent, from 13.3 miles per gallon in 1973 to 20.1 mpg in 1991, according to the Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory in Berkeley, California.</P>

<P>The activities needed to satisfy the desire of people to consume are covered in <B>Module 3, Consuming</B>. In six lessons, Module 3 explains why prices for goods and services vary from business to business, state to state, and country to country. As students work through the activities, they will
<UL>
<LI>scour the seas of the market for high-tech pirates and illegal CDs,
<LI>see why discouraged workers are out of the employment picture, and 
<LI>understand why customers always pay more when one company controls the monopoly board.
</UL></P>
 
<P>The lesson "What Can a Government Do?" introduces students to the role that government plays in the economy by providing public goods that are characterized by shared consumption and nonexclusion. Students also learn how governmental regulations can affect productivity and costs and how governments may intervene in markets when externalities-secondary or unintended consequences--exist. Instead of an interactive video, this lesson presents students with three case studies. In "Manuel Goes to the Movies," students consider how the limited number of movie tickets indicates that movie attendance is an exclusive activity if the theater sells out, some consumers will be excluded. In the second case study, "SeaFree," students learn about productivity when they form groups and play the role of employees in the packaging department of a large pharmaceutical company. In the third study, "The Saga of Goodestock," students consider the positive and negative externalities created when Sally Goode hosts a rock festival at her cotton farm.</P>

<P><B>Saving and borrowing patterns can have long-term effects on its economy</B>. A reduced savings rate will reduce the funds available for personal and business investments. In the United States, the national savings rate slipped from 9.8 percent of the Gross Domestic Product in the 1960s to 3.6 percent in the 1980s, according to the Congressional Budget Office. And while Americans on average are saving less, the American government is borrowing more. The national debt has mushroomed from $43 billion in 1940 to nearly $4.7 trillion in 1994.</P>

<P><B>Module 4, Saving,</B> focuses on the activities and institutions needed to satisfy the desire of people to consume less now so that they can consume more later. In four lessons, Module 4 explains how the borrowing and saving activities of people work together to form the market for loanable funds. As students complete the activities in Module 4, they will
<UL>
<LI>learn to speak the language of lenders, 
<LI>build their own budgets, and 
<LI>uncover the costs of buying on credit.
</UL></P>
 
<P>In the lesson "Why Save?" students learn that funds are transferred from savers to borrowers through banks and other financial institutions that act as intermediaries and charge interest for their services. In the video segment, students consider whether Laura should buy a used car, buy a new computer, pay tuition for tech school, or keep her money in her savings account. As they work through the options, students realize how every decision to buy or save involves an opportunity cost.</P>

<P><B>Investing in human capital can yield impressive returns</B>. In 1994 high school graduates with no college education earned an average of $465 per week. High school graduates who completed associate's degrees earned an average of $572, and graduates with bachelor's degrees averaged $821 per week, according to the <A HREF="http://www.bls.gov"><B>Bureau of Labor Statistics</B></A>.</P>

<P><B>Module 5, Investing,</B> covers the economic activity in which people and businesses engage to increase their resources and productivity. Several of the five lessons in this module focus on the value of considering people as investments. Students will realize that one of their most important resources stares back at them when they look in a mirror. As students work through the activities, they will
<UL>
<LI>catch up on the careers of four high school graduates, 
<LI>take five steps to get a jump on the job market, and 
<LI>learn how to survive in the high-tech world of the future.
</UL></P>

<P>The lesson "Invasion of the Robots" introduces students to the idea that businesses can increase productivity by investing in new technology and by improving the human capital of their workers. Through the video segments, students will help two lab managers decide how they should meet the increased demand for lab services--Should the lab buy the latest equipment and lay off one of the technicians?</P>

<P><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm"><B>Economics at Work</B></A> sets the principles and concepts of economics in an everyday or workplace context and challenges students to draw on a range of information, knowledge, and skills to manage problems, often in cooperation with one another. AIT's newest resource will give your students real-world, hands-on applications of economics concepts they can use today and throughout their lives. If you would like to receive a video overview of <B>Economics at Work,</B> give AIT a call at (800) 457-4509 and ask for the <B>Economics at Work</B> video mailer.</P>

