<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Fall 1995 - In Progress: Workplace Civics & Government</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Fall 1995</H1>
<HR>

<P><B>IN</B>PROGRESS</P>
<H2><I>Workplace Civics & Government</I></H2>
<H3>AIT and CCE join forces to develop multimedia curriculum</H3>

<P>AIT has joined forces with the <A HREF="http://www.primenet.com/~cce"><B>Center for Civic Education</B></A> to give students a challenging curriculum in applied civics and government. Using new technologies and proven methods of instruction, AIT and CCE are developing "Workplace Civics & Government," a comprehensive multimedia series scheduled to be available in the spring of 1997.</P>

<P>The semester-long course is designed to help secondary students better understand civics and government and the social, organizational, and technological systems of which they are a part. "Workplace Civics & Government" will allow students to apply learning to virtual workplace experiences. The curriculum will be organized into five modules, each focusing on one of the following five questions:<OL TYPE=1>
<LI>What is government and what should it do?
<LI>What are the foundations of the American political system?
<LI>How does the government established by the Constitution embody the principles of American democracy?
<LI>What is the relationship of American politics and government to world affairs?
<LI>What are the roles of the citizen in the American political system?
</OL></P>

<P>Videodiscs will be used to present realistic workplace and civic settings, inviting scenarios, graphics, and high-quality animation. (Linear video is also available.) Each module will have a corresponding student resource guide and an annotated teacher's guide. An accompanying CD-ROM will feature illustrative problem scenarios from seven career clusters, with a menu that directs students to material relevant to each module.</P>

<P>Modules will include from six to ten lessons each, to be taught over twelve to twenty 50-minute class periods. Together, the five modules will provide a comprehensive 75-class period (semester-long) applied civics and government experience.</P>

<P>"Workplace Civics & Government" is being designed to enhance civic competence and enhance workplace competencies as identified by the SCANS report. The curriculum will include activities that encourage students to develop critical thinking skills, broaden students' perspectives on the world of work, and are adaptable for non-traditional students (the linear videos include closed captioning).</P>

<P>For additional information, contact John Nelson at (800) 457-4509, extension 204 (or "e-mail <A HREF="MAILTO:jnelson@ait.net"><B>jnelson@ait.net</B></A>") or your state department of education.</P>

