<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Fall 1995 - Meeting Needs: New resources from AIT</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Fall 1995</H1>
<HR>

<A NAME="econw">
<P><B>MEETING</B>NEEDS</P></A>
<H2>New resources from AIT</H2>
<H3><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm"><B>Economics at Work</B></A>, <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm"><B>Mathemedia</B></A>, Professional Development</H3>

<P><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm"><B>ECONOMICS AT WORK</B></A><BR>
<A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm">Economics at Work</A> is a multimedia, contextual economics curriculum that combines videodisc, videocassette, print, and computer software in a comprehensive, one-semester course designed around five major economic activities. The five instructional modules contain a total of 27 lessons--20 combine video and print; seven are based only on print. Together, the lessons provide a comprehensive course that can be taught in 75 class periods. <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm">Economics at Work</A> was developed by AIT, the National Council on Economic Education, and a consortium of state education agencies.</P>

<P><B>Producing, Module 1,</B> examines how human and nonhuman resources are transformed into goods and services. In eight lessons, students will learn why
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>profits rise and fall,
<LI>businesses hire and fire workers,
<LI>the output of some firms is sold outside the United States, and
<LI>the resource mix used to produce a good may vary from nation to nation.
</UL></P>

<P><B>Exchanging, Module 2,</B> examines the process of getting what is produced to consumers. In four lessons, students will learn why
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>firms sell goods and services in many types of markets,
<LI>businesses accept many forms of payment,
<LI>firms purchase foreign-produced goods and services, and
<LI>inflation benefits some people but hurts others.
</UL></P>

<P><IMG SRC="/images/pictures/needs_women.jpg" WIDTH=216 HEIGHT=163 ALIGN=LEFT>
<I>In Module 3, Ann and Darci discover that a higher price for laptop computers can be an incentive for computer manufacturers to increase the quantity of computers supplied.</I><BR CLEAR=LEFT></P>

<P><B>Consuming, Module 3,</B> examines the activities and institutions needed to satisfy individual and collective wants. In six lessons, students will learn why<BR>
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>some prices increase and some decrease;
<LI>prices for the same product vary between businesses, areas, and countries;
<LI>government regulations influence market prices;
<LI>price increases seem to occur immediately while price decreases seem to occur over a longer period of time; and
<LI>some goods and services are produced locally, whereas others are produced in distant places.
</UL></P>

<P><B>Saving, Module 4,</B> examines the process of satisfying the preference to consume less now in order to receive the benefits at some later date. In four lessons, students will learn why
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>banks and other financial institutions pay lower interest to depositors than they charge borrowers,
<LI>consuming more later requires less consumption now,
<LI>a person's income may fall but business investment increase when the interest rate decreases, and
<LI>changes in the money supply may change interest rates.
</UL></P>

<P><B>Investing, Module 5,</B> examines the process of increasing resources and using resources to produce new capital. In five lessons, students will learn why
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>well-trained and -educated workers earn more than other workers,
<LI>$100 payable tomorrow is worth less than $100 today,
<LI>highly educated people might not find work in their chosen field,
<LI>people are replaced by machines in the production of goods and services, and
<LI>potential Gross Domestic Product increases are the result of investment.
</UL></P>

<P><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm"><B>Economics at Work</B></A> will help you develop your students' critical-thinking, decision-making, and collaborating skills by using real-world examples, context-based learning activities, and peer-age instruction.</P>

<P><IMG SRC="/images/prodlogo/368slogo.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Materials</B>: Each module includes one or two Level 1 barcode-driven videodiscs, one videocassette, and one teacher's guide. Student guides are sold separately. The "Economics at Work" computer software and classroom utilization component includes a set of Windows  and Macintosh  diskettes, one teacher training video program, and one workshop leader's handbook.<BR CLEAR=LEFT></P>

<P>To receive a free video information kit, call Customer Service at (800) 457-4509 and ask for the <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm"><B>Economics at Work</B></A> video mailer. "Economics at Work" implementation training is available from AIT. See below for more information.</P>

<P><A HREF="/news/v1n1/"><B>Return to Table of Contents</B></A></P>

<A NAME="mathm"><HR></A>

<P><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm"><B>MATHEMEDIA</B></A><BR>
<A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm">Mathemedia</A> presents pre-algebra mathematics in everyday and workplace contexts to help teach students in grades 7-12 to apply mathematics principles to real-world situations. Each of its 12 programs include documentary footage in a real business or industrial setting, and dramatizations feature peer-age actors who solve problems that students may face now or in the future. Another segment of each program shows teens solving abstract, conceptual problems in non-workplace settings.</P>

<P>The 12 modules of "Mathemedia" focus on the following key mathematical concepts:
<UL TYPE=DISC><IMG SRC="/images/pictures/372mod2.jpg" ALIGN=RIGHT>
<LI>Graphs
<LI>Decimals and exponents
<LI>Logical reasoning
<LI>Measurement
<LI>Fractions
<LI>Positive and negative numbers
<LI>Formulas
<LI>Ratios
<LI>Percentages
<LI>Area and volume
<LI>Probability
<LI>Coordinates
</UL></P>

<P>The modules consist of interactive video segments and print lessons. Each module includes three different video segments that allow students to experience real-life math problems and test their own solutions.</P>

<P>In <B>Module 2, Decimals and Exponents,</B> for example, students visit a currency exchange and meet a currency trader who describes how the market works. Then students travel to Brazil and try to figure out the best way to change dollars into Brazilian currency. Students will also watch two young women try to buy 53 chairs on a limited budget and decide whether Maria's quick estimate is accurate enough to keep them on budget. In the third video segment, Toby and Rhonda use exponents to express and calculate very large numbers, as they try to estimate the likelihood that aliens from Arcturus will invade a Texas swimming pool.</P>

<P><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm"><B>Mathemedia</B></A> modules are based on the NCTM Standards and correlate to more than 30 mathematics textbooks from 14 different educational publishers. With video segments and textual activities correlated to SCANS competencies, "Mathemedia" modules can be used in any order and can also be integrated into a traditional curriculum or used as the core of tech prep or applied mathematics courses.</P>

<P><IMG SRC="/images/prodlogo/372slogo.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>Materials</B>: Three Level 1 barcode videodiscs, a linear version of the videodisc material on six VHS videocassettes, two annotated teacher's guides. Student guides are sold separately.<BR CLEAR=LEFT></P>

<P>To receive a free video information kit, call Customer Service at (800) 457-4509 and ask for the <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm"><B>Mathemedia</B></A> video mailer.</P>

<P><A HREF="/news/v1n1/">Return to Table of Contents</A></P>

<A NAME="workshops"><HR></A>

<P><B>PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT</B></P>

<P><B>AIT Performance Support Workshops</B><BR>
The true success of any applied academics curriculum depends on more than the development of classroom materials. That's why AIT created Performance Support Workshops training that will give you the confidence and know-how to utilize our award-winning Tech Prep resources in your classrooms. AIT Performance Support Workshops provide
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>an introduction to product and training materials
<LI>effective implementation and teaching strategies
<LI>hands-on practice with immediate feedback
<LI>sample lesson and action plans
<LI>practical assessment strategies
<LI>an opportunity to network with other educators
<LI>hands-on laserdisc and computer training with product
</UL></P>

<P>The <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm"><B>Economics at Work</B></A> workshop includes an overview, implementation strategy, and interactive modeling, participation, and demonstration of the course's videodiscs, videocassettes, print, and computer software.</P>

<P>In <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c317.htm"><B>Workplace Readiness</B></A> Introductory Training, participants develop a plan for implementing a School-to-Work transition/Employability Skills curriculum; learn effective techniques for teaching "Workplace Readiness" skills; and receive sample lessons, action plans, and assessment strategies.</P>

<P>AIT offers two workshops on <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.html"><B>Applied Communication</B></A>--a curriculum designed to help students develop their communication skills. In "Applied Communication" Introductory Training, participants learn teaching strategies, develop lesson plans, and receive helpful supplemental material. In "Applied Communication" Integrating Literature, participants analyze methods of integrating literature, develop lesson plans, learn how to tie "Applied Communication" modules with reading selections, and receive an extensive bibliography of literature selections.</P>

<P>The "Communication 2000" workshop provides an opportunity for teachers to learn through interactive demonstration and practice how to implement and use the course's videodiscs, videos, print, audio cassettes, and computer templates. They will also learn how "Communication 2000" helps their School-to-Work/Applied Academics reform initiatives.</P>

<P>For more information on attending or hosting one of these workshops, call <A HREF="MAILTO:mjlip@ait.net">Mary Jane Lipp</A> at (800) 457-4509, extension 255.</P>

<B>Let AIT Work for You</B><BR>

<P>AIT is developing a new series of practical classroom workshops, including workshops in integrative mathematics.  These new resources are being created to help you develop the professional within and better meet your students' needs.  Future offerings could also include training tailored to meet your specific needs.  Look for further details in future issues of "AIT.Net News."</P>

<P><B>Staff Development Resources</B><BR>
AIT offers a wide range of staff development resources, from <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c366.htm"><B>Managing the Disruptive Classroom</B></A> and <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c344.htm"><B>Caring for Children</B></A> to <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c373.htm"><B>The Road to School-to-Work: A Map for Implementation</B></A> and <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c371.htm"><B>Dorothy Rich's Families & Schools</B></A>. The newest staff development resources include <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c385.htm"><B>Before the Bell Rings: What Every Paraeducator Should Know</B></A> and <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c386.htm"><B>Respecting Diversity in the Classroom</B></A>.</P>

<P>The roles and duties of teacher aides/assistants have evolved and become more complex since they were introduced in the 1950s. In today's schools, they can more accurately  be described as paraeducators, as they participate in all phases of the instructional process and in the delivery of other direct educational services to students and their parents.</P>

<P><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c385.htm"><B>Before the Bell Rings: What Every Paraeducator Should Know</B></A> provides a foundation on which school districts can build to implement ongoing professional-development programs for paraeducators in preschool, elementary, and secondary education. The 58-minute videotape is divided into six parts, each of which should be viewed separately. The topics addressed on the tape are
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>team building
<LI>roles and responsibilities of teachers and paraeducators
<LI>professional and ethical responsibilities of paraeducators
<LI>communication and problem solving
<LI>behavior management
</UL></P>

<P>"Before the Bell Rings" has been derived from a competency-based curriculum developed for paraeducators by the National Resource Center for Paraprofessionals in Education and Related Services. The professional-development activities in the facilitator's guide are designed to be conducted during a one-day (six-hour) workshop or a series of four 1-1/2-hour or three 2-hour sessions.</P>

