<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Fall 1995 - TECHNOS Press: Making it real</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Fall 1995</H1>
<HR>

<P><B>TECHNOS</B>PRESS</P>
<H2>Making it real</H2>
<H3>New releases include fall TECHNOS and FINAL EXAM</H3>

<P>When administrators asked for suggestions about what kind of new school they should build, Lincoln district students answered: "Make it real!" Linda Myers, associate superintendent of Educational Services for the Lincoln Unified School District, discusses how the district is reaching this goal in the Fall 1995 issue of <A HREF="/technos/technos/"><B>TECHNOS: Quarterly for Education and Technology</B></A>.</P>

<P>Winner of the 1995 EdPress Distinguished Achievement Award, <A HREF="/technos/technos/"><B>TECHNOS Quarterly</B></A> was first published in 1992 as a forum for leading authorities on current topics and trends, educational policy and reform, and new technologies. The lineup of articles in the Fall 1995 issue continues AIT's dedication to shaping current thinking and influencing policy on educational issues.
<UL>
<LI>In a guest editorial, Alan D. Morgan, New Mexico superintendent of public instruction, contends that control of public education systems is best left to local interests.
<LI>Ernest L. Boyer, president of The Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching, shares his insights on teaching values and reforming education through the use of technology.
<LI>A call for a new model for pedagogy is issued by AIT's Executive Director Michael F. Sullivan, who argues for models for pedagogy that include technological access and put kids first.
<LI>Linda Myers, Lincoln Unified School District, shares the district's blueprint for making learning real.
<LI>Ralph Brauer, executive director of the Transforming Schools Consortium, welcomes readers into the "virtual schoolhouse," where the Internet becomes the school and students are free to explore nearly unlimited learning resources available online.
<LI>AIT's first Distinguished Fellow Gerald W. Bracey contends that American public education has been doing a better job than we think.
<LI>In the TECHNOS Colloquium, Mark A. Shields, assistant professor of technology, culture, and communication at the University of Virginia, reasons that although techno-utopianism is the message of the day, it isn't the answer to all our educational problems.
<LI>"TECHNOS: Quarterly for Education and Technology" is published by TECHNOS Press as the journal of the Agency for Instructional Technology.  Selected articles from past issues of "TECHNOS Quarterly" are available online in <A HREF="/technos/technos/"><B>AIT.Net TECHNOS</B></A>.
</UL></P>

<P><B>AIT Distinguished Fellows Program, TECHNOS Press Books</B><BR>
The Agency's Distinguished Fellows Program was successfully launched in 1994 with the appointment of noted research psychologist, education consultant, and writer Gerald W. Bracey, Ph.D., as the first AIT Distinguished Fellow.</P>

<P>His TECHNOS Press book, "FINAL EXAM: A Study of the Perpetual Scrutiny of American Education," was just released in October 1995 and provides a history of standards, outcomes, assessment, and criticism of U.S. public schools with commentary on two predominant philosophies of learning in this country: that of Thomas Jefferson's "aristocracy of worth and genius" and that of "all children can learn."</P>

<P>Reviewers have praised "FINAL EXAM" as an "engaging" and "lively" work that makes "a very valuable contribution to the scene because of its scholarship and its honesty." </P>

"FINAL EXAM" is available from AIT for $24.98, plus $4.00 shipping and handling, per copy. Subscribers to AIT.Net can purchase "FINAL EXAM" at 10% off. <A HREF="/ait-bin/survey.htm"><B>Register</B></A> online today, and ask for product number 387-BB-1.

<P>Accepting a position as the second AIT Distinguished Fellow is economist Morton Marcus, director of the Indiana Business Research Center at Indiana University. As part of his fellowship, Mr. Marcus will conduct original research and write a book about new methods of funding public education in the United States. Marcus writes a weekly syndicated column on economics that is published in Indiana newspapers, and his wry commentary on economics and society has been heard on <A HREF="http://www.npr.org"><B>National Public Radio</B></A>. His book will be published in September 1996.</P>

<P><B>TECHNOS Press Monographs</B><BR>
The TECHNOS Press Monographs premier this fall with the publication of "Setting Standards in the Age of Knowledge: A Framework for Establishing and Using Educational Standards" by Yesha Y. Sivan, Ed.D. The author has developed a process for educators to follow as they set standards in K-12 and higher education. This 56-page monograph is available for $9.95 each from TECHNOS Press. Receive a discount on the monograph when you <A HREF="/ait-bin/survey.htm"><B>register</B></A> online and order a copy of "FINAL EXAM."</P>

<P><B>National Conference on Educational Fair Access and the New Media</B><BR>
In an effort to answer questions about <A HREF="copy.htm"><B>copyright law</B></A>, fair-use guidelines, and new technologies, AIT paired with the Consortium of College and University Media Centers to cohost the National Conference on Educational Fair Access and the New Media in June 1994. The conference was convened to begin developing new fair-use guidelines in the wake of an explosion in multimedia--digitized, networked media that are easily accessed and manipulated by computer. Educators should be concerned about obtaining access to and fair use of such materials for classroom purposes.</P>

<P>The conference brought together major interest groups and a host of copyright experts to address these issues. To further discussion, AIT released a 96-page report on the conference. "What's Fair? A Report on the Proceedings of the National Conference on Educational Fair Access and the New Media" includes
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>keynote speeches and presentations,
<LI>summaries of working committee reports,
<LI>current copyright laws and fair-use guidelines, and
<LI>a list of readings on the subject of copyright.
</UL></P>

<P>"What's Fair?" is available from AIT's TECHNOS Press for $14.95 plus $2.00 for shipping and handling per copy. For prepaid orders, AIT will pay shipping costs.  For more information on these publications, contact TECHNOS Press at (800) 457-4509, extension 220; fax (812) 333-4218; or contact TECHNOS at technos@ait.net. <A HREF="/ait-bin/survey.htm"><B>Register</B></A> with AIT.Net, and you can order "What's Fair?" for 50% off.</P>

