<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Fall 1995 - Tune In: FirstView '95</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Fall 1995</H1>
<HR>

<P><B>TUNE</B>IN</P>
<H2>FirstView '95</H2
<H3>AIT presents new resources</H3>

<P>Each year, new programs for broadcast/audiovisual use are debuted at FirstView, the national meeting of instructional television professionals. The products introduced by AIT at FirstView '95 included the following nine resources.</P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Mathematics Is Elementary</B> brings mathematics to life for students in grades 2-4 by showing how many mathematical concepts are found in their daily lives. Produced by General Learning Video and distributed by AIT, this series includes thirteen 15-minute student programs. Available August 1996.
<LI><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c370.htm"><B>Looking from the Inside/Out</B></A> gives children in grades 3-5 the skills they need to make healthy decisions. Produced by AIT, this series includes fifteen 15-minute programs being developed as a preproduction lease. Available January 1996.
<LI><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c383.htm"><B>Front Row Center</B></A> inspires students in grades 6-12 to discover a deeper appreciation for the performing arts. Produced by WDCN, this series includes seventeen 15-minute programs. Available Now.
<LI><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c336.htm"><B>Solo para Mi</B></A> is the Spanish version of <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c336.htm"><B>Just for Me</B></A>, a series that teaches second- through fourth-graders the skills they need to make healthy decisions.  These six 15-minute programs present peer-aged children encountering difficult health issues and choices at school and at home.  Available Now.
<LI><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c371.htm"><B>Dorothy Rich's Families & Schools: Teaming for Success</B></A> shows administrators, teachers, parents, and students how they can experience the benefits of family and community involvement with their schools.  This two-part 60-minute workshop includes informative interviews with Dorothy Rich.  Available Now.
<LI><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c373.htm"><B>The Road to School-to-Work: A Map for Implementation</B></A> takes a comprehensive look at how administrators, teachers, parents, and others can incorporate the new school-to-work mandates into their education offerings.  This six-part, 74-minute program is available now.
<LI><B>Get Writing!</B> teaches viewers how to follow four basic steps for writing and how to apply those steps in different situations.  This program was developed by the University of Mississippi's LEAP project.  Available June 1996.
<LI><B>Tales from Africa</B> introduces students in kindergarten through second grade to the art of story telling with folktales told by a native storyteller.  Each of the twenty-six, 5-minute programs in this series ends with a song and a summary.  Available June 1996.
<LI><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c378.htm#closer"><B>Everybody's School House: A Closer Look</B></A> brings viewers into classrooms that are successfully implementing inclusion programs.  These three new videos discuss ways to tailor education to include all students in the classroom.  Available Now.
</UL>

<P>For further information on these and other instructional programs, contact Barb Ravellette at (800) 236-6248.</P>

