<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996 - Tips from teachers</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996</H1>
<HR>

<H1>Tips from teachers</H1>
<H2>From desert survival to stock market savvy</H2>
<P>
Give me more tips from teachers, Claudia Conner said in response to <I>AIT.Net News'</I> fall survey. So many of our readers agreed with this senior high school teacher at River Ridge School in New Port Richey, Florida, that we've included 12 teaching tips in this issue. Even more tips are available in <A HREF="/tips/">AIT.Net Tips</A>.</P>
<P>
<A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/prodlogo/372slogo.gif" BORDER=0>
<H3><I>Mathemedia</I></H3></A>
<P><B>Following the <A HREF="http://www.lib.lsu.edu/bus/finance.htm">stock market</A>.</B> I like to expand <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm">Mathemedia</A></I> lessons with mini-units. In the section on logic, we do a logic box unit and the students even write their own logic box problems. In the unit on decimals and the money exchange system, I include a unit on the <A HREF="http://www.secapl.com/cgi-bin/qs">stock market</A> that has students &quot;buying&quot; 100 shares of a stock and then following its performance for a week. I really like these mini-units as starting points to build on <I>Mathemedia </I>lessons.
<BR><I>Patty Gainey, Creston Junior High, Indianapolis, Indiana</P>
<P>
</I><B>Click here to see how <A HREF="correl.htm"><I>Mathemedia </I>adds up to workplace skills</A>.</B></P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/pictures/ait2-1a.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT><BR><BR>
<B>Whether your students choose hard hats or high finance, they'll improve their communication survival skills with <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.htm"><I>Applied Communication.</I></A></B><BR></P>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/prodlogo/275slogo.gif" BORDER=0></P>
<H3><I>Applied Communication</I></H3></A>
<P><B>Take note.</B> My students keep a notebook in which they write all the main points and key concepts organized by module number, lesson number, and title. On test day, I let them use their notebooks for five minutes during the test before collecting them for a 100-point daily grade.
<br><I>Janet E. Davis, Southside High School, Batesville, Arkansas
<P></I><B>Learning a new language. </B>When studying Module 5, my students get excited about selecting an occupational area and working independently to do the &quot;Application&quot; from Lesson 10. Each student presents his or her new language to class for understanding and discussion.
<br><I>Gladia M. Perry, Middleton High School, Saulsbury, Tennessee
<P></I><B>Calling for customer service. </B>After I teach the unit &quot;Communicating with Clients and Customers,&quot; the students use real telephones and role-play &quot;difficult&quot; and &quot;irate&quot; customer situations. Worked great with seniors!
<br><I>Phyllis L. Wright, Dothan High School, Dothan, Alabama
<P></I><B>A younger audience. </B>My seniors prepare a report on the vocation of their choice and present it (orally and with visuals or activities) to younger students (grades 5-6). Presentations are also made in our classroom so students must vary their presentations to fit the appropriate audience.
<br><I>Sherry Hott, <A HREF="http://isbe.state.il.us/~dhendric/litch.htm">Litchfield High School,</A> Litchfield, Illinois
<P></I><B>Integration. </B>We are integrating our <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.htm">Applied Communication</A></I> course called Technical Communications (English) into the trades taught at our Career Development Center. In two areas, <A HREF="http://www.english.upenn.edu/~schwebel/theater.htm">theater arts</A> and <A HREF="http://www.carsurvey.com/links.htm">auto,</A> the English teacher works in the trade space and meets regularly with the instructors to coordinate the curriculum.
<br><I>Candace Burkle, ACDC, Addison Northeast, Middlebury, Vermont
<P></I><B>Exploring local businesses.</B> Each of my students researches a business and writes a paper. We use Modules 2 and 16 as well as additional materials. It has worked well, and my students learn a great deal about companies that they would like to work for or that they patronize.
<br><I>Shelia Penick, Yates Center High School, Yates Center, Kansas
<P></I><B>A place for <A HREF="http://oksw01.okanagan.bc.ca/fiar/research.htm">art.</A></B> We've added several units to our <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.htm">Applied Communication</A></I> class. One unit covers <A HREF="http://oksw01.okanagan.bc.ca/fiar/research.htm">art</A> through visual imagery by combining <A HREF="http://www.bubl.bath.ac.uk/BUBL/Photography.htm">photography</A> with <A HREF="http://www.rpi.edu/~cheny6/link_poetry.htm">poetry</A>. This unit helps students learn to express their ideas in a dual modality.
<br><I>Marilyn D. Gattuso, Wahconah Regional High School, Dalton, Massachusetts
<P></I>
<A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c317.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/prodlogo/317slogo.gif" BORDER=0>
<H3><I>Workplace Readiness</I></H3></A>
<P><B>Only the shadow knows.</B> A career unit we added last year requires students to research a career and give an oral and written report. To gather material, students shadow someone working in that career for a day. Students observed <A HREF="http://www.purdue.edu">Purdue</A> athletic trainers, Embassy Suites managers, pediatricians, travel agents, etc. After the job shadow day, two students realized their careers of choice were not the careers they wanted. That's O.K. Mission accomplished!
<br><I>Char Rogers, Clinton Prairie High School, Frankfort, Indiana
<P></I><B>Cooperative programs in the community.</B> We have developed several workplace readiness programs in our district. 
<P> <OL><LI>A cooperative program between business and health teachers trains the students for medical office positions and helps them learn medical vocabulary, lab procedures, and business office skills. The program also has an internship component in which students rotate through various medical positions.
<P> <LI>A program between a <A HREF="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/research/visible/visible_human.htm">health occupations</A> teacher and an <A HREF="http://www.nlm.nih.gov/research/visible/visible_human.htm">anatomy and physiology</A> (A&amp;P) teacher helps students learn the textbook side of A&amp;P and brings them into a hospital where they go to surgery, laboratories, rehabilitation, etc., and see the practical side of it. They also receive lectures from practicing doctors, nurses, and others.
<P> <LI>A program between the drafting machine shop, <A HREF="http://ewi.ewi.org/ewi/">welding,</A> and <A HREF="http://sashimi.wwa.com/~merbland/utility/utility.htm">electricity</A> instructors prepares selected seniors in their second year in the subject to be multi-skilled workers. This program was created to meet the needs expressed by local business and industry professionals.
<P> <LI>A program between a microbiology teacher and the local hospital enables students to study microbiology theory in high school and practice what they've learned by completing a lab internship at the hospital in various labs with mentors from the health profession.
</OL><br><I>Cathy Fisher, United Technical Center, Clarksburg, West Virginia
<P></I><B>Surviving the <A HREF="http://www.sas.upenn.edu/African_Studies/Country_Specific/W_Sahara.htm">Sahara.</A></B> I found my students had a hard time relating to the &quot;Lost in Space&quot; assignment so I substituted it with another one I found in the <I>VICA Journal</I> (April/May 1993) entitled &quot;<A HREF="http://www.goldcanyon.com/htm/desrtsur.htm">Desert Survival</A> Situation.&quot; It's the same idea, but my students know more about the deserts than the <A HREF="http://bang.lanl.gov/solarsys/homepage.htm">moon.</A>
<br><I>Loretta Hanisel, Kentucky Tech, Laurel County Campus, London, Kentucky
<P></I><B>A balancing act. </B>I've incorporated a unit on balancing work and family and another on career choices that uses the Choice computer program to increase student awareness of the interaction between their personal and work lives. They need to assess their own interests and qualities in order to make appropriate career choices. In effect, they must realize the trade-offs some decisions in life require and how they can balance the demands in their lives.
<br><I>Mary Griswold, North Linn High School, Coggon, Iowa<P>Share your favorite teaching tip with other teachers by submitting it to <A HREF="/tips/">AIT.Net Tips.</A>
<P></I>
<H3><A NAME="A6"><B>Seek a tip, share a tip</B></H3>
<P> These six teachers are seeking classroom tips--hints, strategies, resources, or projects. If you have a tip--or need one--contact the editor of <I>AIT.Net News</I> via email at <A HREF="MAILTO:ait@ait.net">ait@ait.net</A>; fax at (812) 333-4218; or snail mail at P.O. Box A, Bloomington, IN 47402-0120. 
<P> How do we get those who enroll students to understand that <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.htm">Applied Communication</A></I> is not a &quot;bonehead&quot; English class?
<br><I>Pat Deitz, Century High School, Bismarck, North Dakota
<P></I>Where could I find out about schools and programs that have on-campus, work-based learning sites? We're looking at sites and <A HREF="http://www.slu.edu/eweb/">entrepreneurships</A> on high school campuses.
<br><I>Jeanette Gehuke, Snowline Jouit Unified School District, Phelan, California
<P></I>Does anyone have a list of novels that deal with work themes and are suitable for high school juniors and seniors?
<br><I>Donna Smith, Cascade High School, Leavenworth, Washington
<P></I>What order do you recommend to start the <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c317.htm">Workplace Readiness</A></I> units?
<br><I>Sharyn K. Paige, Wayne High School, Wayne, Nebraska
<P></I>What other <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.htm">Applied Communication</A></I> teachers teach in block scheduling? This is our first year on block scheduling and my second year with AC. I'm still looking for ideas--especially on testing procedures.
<br><I>Beth Newman, Ripley High School, Ripley, Tennessee
<P></I>Does anyone have suggestions for using <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c320.htm">Attributes for Successful Employability</A></I>?
<br><I>Patricia Peschke McKinley, Clark High School, Whiting, Indiana</I></P>

