<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996 - Tips from teachers</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996</H1>
<HR>

<H1>Thank your <A HREF="/links/lstates.htm">state DOE</A>!</H1>
<P>
<H2><A HREF="/projects/default.htm">Consortium</A> investment yields savings dividend</H2>
<P> For over 35 years, AIT has pioneered the consortium process of funding curriculum projects. Educational agencies pool their financial and intellectual resources to cooperatively develop new learning materials. In return, schools in member states can buy innovative curriculum materials at greatly reduced rates.
<P> Investments by state departments of education in the <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm">Economics at Work</A></I> consortium are already paying off, with schools in 19 of the 35 member states saving more money on the materials they purchased than the state originally invested in its membership. Schools in the other 16 member states have saved money too, and their savings will soon surpass their original investment. Schools in the 15 states that did not join the consortium must pay full list price; fortunately, these states can still join the consortium and save.
<P> One outstanding savings success story began when <A HREF="http://gadoe.gac.peachnet.edu/">Georgia's Department of Education</A> joined the consortium while the course was in the planning stage. The state's far-sighted action placed its officials and teachers on the design team and ensured substantial discounts for Georgia's schools. To date, those schools have saved $151,750 on materials against the state's consortium membership fee of $23,730.
<P> Better yet, the Georgia Council on Economic Education helped introduce the course by training teachers and securing a significant grant from the Atlanta-based <A HREF="http://www.ups.com">United Parcel Service</A> for continuing assistance in training, hardware, and materials.
<P> Altogether, schools in the 35 states that formed the <I>Economics at Work</I> consortium have saved over $1.2 million! What is truly amazing is that the course is only in its first year of use. This means that it is being widely used and that schools will continue to save money for many years. 
<P> Schools using <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.htm">Applied Communication</A></I>, <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c317.htm">Workplace Readiness</A></I>, and 33 <A HREF="/catalog/default.htm">other courses</A> developed over the years through AIT's consortium process have accrued similar savings, as will consortium member schools that start using <I><A HREF="/projects/civics/">Civics at Work</A></I> when it is released next year. 
<P> Please remember to thank your state superintendent for being far-sighted, helping to create these excellent materials, and conserving your school's precious funds.
<P><I>For additional information on consortium membership in our newest consortium project, </I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm">Civics at Work</A><I>, contact John Nelson at (800) 457-4509, extension 204 (or <A HREF="MAILTO:jnelson@ait.net">jnelson@ait.net</A>), or your <A HREF="/links/lstates.htm">state department of education</A>.
<P></I>
<H3>A GROWING LIST</H3>
<P> These states have already saved more on <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm">Economics at Work</A></I> materials than they invested in consortium membership:
<br>Alabama
<br><A HREF="http://www.dpi.state.de.us/dpi/dpi/dpi.html">Delaware</A>
<br><A HREF="http://gadoe.gac.peachnet.edu/">Georgia</A>
<br><A HREF="http://www.doe.hawaii.edu/upena/">Hawaii</A>
<br>Illinois
<br><A HREF="http://www.doe.state.in.us/">Indiana</A>
<br><A HREF="http://www.state.ia.us/educate/index.html">Iowa</A>
<br>Kansas
<br><A HREF="http://www.kde.state.ky.us/">Kentucky</A>
<br>Maine
<br><A HREF="http://informns.k12.mn.us/">Minnesota</A>
<br><A HREF="http://services.dese.state.mo.us/">Missouri</A>
<br><A HREF="http://nde4.nde.state.ne.us/">Nebraska</A>
<br>Nevada
<br><A HREF="http://www.ode.ohio.gov/">Ohio</A>
<br><A HREF="http://www.state.or.us/">Oregon</A>
<br>Rhode Island
