<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996 - FastForward: Economics at Work</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996</H1>
<HR>

<P>
<B>FAST</B>FORWARD</P>

<A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/prodlogo/368slogo.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<H1><I>Economics at Work</I></H1></A>
<H2>An inside look at the 1995 AECT Crystal Award winner</H2>
<P>
As winner of the 1995 Crystal Award, AIT's <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm">Economics at Work</A></I> has been recognized by the <A HREF="http://www.aect.org/">Association for Educational Communications and Technology's</A> Division of Telecommunications as the most innovative and outstanding video-based instructional telecommunications project with a development budget of over $100,000. What's inside the 1995 Crystal Award winner? A fully interactive economics curriculum designed for today's classrooms and tomorrow's workplace.</P>
<P>
<B>Contextual economics.</B> <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm">Economics at Work</A></I> combines videodisc and barcode technology, videocassette, print, and computer software into a comprehensive, one-semester course designed around five economic activities: producing, exchanging, consuming, saving, and investing. <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm">Economics at Work</A></I> was developed by AIT, EconomicsAmerica, and a consortium of 35 state education agencies.</P>
<P>
<B>Interactive lessons.</B> All of the 27 lessons draw their content from EconomicAmerica's &quot;A Framework for Teaching Basic Economic Concepts&quot; and begin by introducing an economic event in general terms in the printed guide (&quot;Econ Briefing&quot; and &quot;Econcepts&quot;). In the 20 video lessons, the guide then presents an introduction to the interactive video segment, which is punctuated with questions and problems (&quot;Economic Puzzle Challenge&quot;) that draw in the students as active viewers and learners.</P>
<P>
This is followed by a section which connects the main themes of the lesson. Finally, the lesson presents a concluding section with summary, extension, and assessment (&quot;Quality Control&quot;) activities. (In the seven print-only lessons, &quot;Case in Point&quot; sections replace &quot;Economic Puzzle Challenge&quot; sections.)</P>
<P>
<B>Teacher support.</B> Each videodisc includes suggestions for introducing material and managing student activities and assessment prompts. The teacher guides contain a glossary of key terms, a list of additional resources, and ideas for extension activities involving the community. The laserdiscs also include a database of graphs and charts that are accessible by barcode in the teacher's guides. A classroom utilization component includes a workshop leader's handbook and a videotape that shows actual classroom use.</P>
<P>
For a closer look at the &quot;most innovative and outstanding&quot; 1995 Crystal Award winner, order your free video information kit today from <A HREF="MAILTO:ait@ait.net">AIT Customer Service</A> at (800) 457-4509.</P>

