<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996 - Meeting Needs: New resources from AIT</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996</H1>
<HR>

<P><B>MEETING</B>NEEDS</P>

<H1>New resources from AIT</H1>
<H2><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm"><I>Mathemedia</I></A> software, <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c389.htm"><I>Education Under Fire,</I></A> Workshops</H2>
<A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/prodlogo/372slogo.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0><BR>
<H3><I>MATHEMEDIA</I></H3></A>
<P>
In response to numerous requests, AIT has developed Software Templates for <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm">Mathemedia</A>, </I>the new pre-algebra <A HREF="http://www.enc.org/">mathematics</A> curriculum for grades 7-12. The templates contain application activities that require students to use formulas and spreadsheet programs. All supporting print materials are also included.</P>
<P>
Designed for Windows&#174; or Macintosh&#174; based operating systems, <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm">Mathemedia</A> </I>software utilizes your existing applications software. The Macintosh&#174; spreadsheet templates are saved as Microsoft&#174; Excel 3.0 files; supporting print materials are saved as Microsoft&#174; Word 4.0 files. The Windows&#174; spreadsheet and word processing files require Microsoft&#174; Works for Windows version 3 or greater. These can be opened with many other spreadsheet and word processing programs. Hardware requirements do not exceed those of the required application programs.</P>
<P>
The <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm">Mathemedia</A> </I>curriculum uses real-world situations to teach 12 key mathematical concepts, including graphs, decimals and exponents, logical reasoning, and probability. Each module includes three interactive video segments and a print lesson. <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm">Mathemedia </A></I>is based on the NCTM Standards, correlates to more than 30 mathematics textbooks, and fosters the SCANS competencies.</P>
<P>
If you are already using <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm">Mathemedia,</A></I> the Software Templates are available for only $49.95 plus $4.00 shipping by calling Customer Service at (800) 457-4509 and asking for Item 372-CS1 (this includes both Macintosh&#174; and Windows&#174; versions).</P>
<P>
<I>If you would like to know more about </I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm">Mathemedia,</A><I> contact <A HREF="MAILTO:ait@ait.net">Customer Service</A> and ask for the free </I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm">Mathemedia</A><I> video mailer.</I></P>
<A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c389.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/prodlogo/389slogo.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0><BR>
<H3><I>EDUCATION UNDER FIRE</I></H3></A><BR>
<P>
Collaborative schools, <A HREF="http://www.slip.net/~scmetro/childco.htm">youth</A> violence, and outcome-based <A HREF="http://www.apic.or.jp/Networks.html">education</A> are three of the vital issues discussed in <I>Education Under Fire,</I> a six-video professional development series produced by AIT and Phi Delta Kappa.</P>
<P>
Each 30-minute video program features a prominent leader in <A HREF="http://www.theworld.com/EDUCATIO/SUBJECT.HTM">education</A> considering topics that challenge opportunities for school improvement and affect the public's perception of the role of education:</P>
<P>
<B>Collaborative Schools: Sharing the Power.</B> Deborah W. Meier, president of the Center for Collaborative Education, encourages new approaches to enhance democracy and equity in public education.</P>
<P>
<B>Youth Violence: A New Public Health Issue.</B> Deborah B. Prothrow-Stith, M.D., assistant dean of government and community programs at <A HREF="http://www.harvard.edu">Harvard University</A>, regards violence as a societal &quot;disease&quot; that can be prevented through public health strategies.</P>
<P>
<B>Outcome-Based Education: Panacea or Poison?</B> William G. Spady, founder of the High Success Network, has helped educators and parents in more than 40 states and Canadian provinces implement outcome-based education.</P>
<P>
<B>Accelerated Schools: Raising the Speed Limit. </B>Henry M. Levin, director of the Center for Educational Research at <A HREF="http://www-portfolio.stanford.edu/">Stanford,</A> focuses on establishing &quot;accelerated schools&quot; that bring all students into the educational mainstream.</P>
<P>
<B>American Schools: Catching Up to the Future. </B>Willard R. Daggett, director of the <A HREF="http://www.daggett.com/">International Center for Leadership in Education,</A> encourages educational systems to provide more relevant workplace-related skills and knowledge.</P>
<P>
<B>Beyond OBE: Seeking Common Ground. </B>Robert L. Simonds is founder and president of Citizens for Excellence in Education, an organization of parents who advocate academic excellence and character education for America's children.</P>
<P>
<I>Education Under Fire</I> is available as a complete six-video set or as individual videos. For more information, contact <A HREF="MAILTO:ait@ait.net">Customer Service</A> at (800) 457-4509.</P>

<H3>PERFORMANCE SUPPORT WORKSHOPS</H3>
<P>
Gear up for the 1996-1997 school year by planning to attend AIT regional workshops on <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.htm">Applied Communication,</A> <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c317.htm">Workplace Readiness,</A> Communication 2000, <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c372.htm">Mathemedia,</A> <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c373.htm">The Road to School to Work,</A></I> and <I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c368.htm">Economics at Work.</A></I> These one- and two-day workshops will give you the confidence to utilize AIT's award-winning resources.</P>
<P>
Registration fees are $125 for one-day workshops and $225 for two-day workshops (excludes meals, lodging, or transportation). The following workshops will be held at AIT headquarters in Bloomington, Indiana:
<UL>
<LI><P><B><I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c275.htm">Applied Communication</A></I>--Introductory/Integrating Literature:</B> June 14, August 16
<LI><P><B><I><A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c317.htm">Workplace Readiness</A>: </I></B>June 13, August 8-9
