<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996 - Technology Watch: Funding the future</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996</H1>
<HR>

<H1>Funding the future</H1>
<H2>Selling your technology proposal to the school board</H2>
<P><B>(Part Two in a Series)</B></P>
<P>
According to the Public Agenda Foundation, 72% of teachers and 80% of the public believe that teaching computer skills and media technology are absolutely essential. Funding the future of technology in your school can involve many efforts--from identifying needs to finding the resources to meet them. One challenge facing all schools is convincing the school board to support a technology plan. You can improve your chance of success when you follow the strategies outlined below.</P>

<H3>Get organized</H3>
<P>
Technology moves fast. To keep on top of opportunities for educators, and garner grassroots support and commitment to technology for your school, consider forming a School/Community Technology Committee or a joint School District/School/Community Technology Committee.</P>

<H3>Develop a technology plan</H3>
<P> It's harder to argue with a well-developed plan. Be sure your plan includes a mission statement and addresses key policy issues. Create a mission statement around these three questions:</P>
<UL>
<LI><P>What education will students need to prepare them for the Information Age?</P>
<LI><P>What skills are needed to meet the demands of a rapidly changing world?</P>
<LI><P>How can technology help teachers provide a better education for their students?</P>
</UL>
<P>Develop a plan for the purchase and implementation of technology that addresses these questions, plus such policy issues as:</P>
<UL>
<LI><P>How do you ensure that all students will have equal access to technology?</P>
<LI><P>How will hardware and software be previewed, purchased, and evaluated?</P>
<LI><P>How will you train educators to use the technology and incorporate it in the curriculum?</P>
<LI><P>What <A HREF="http://www.cua.edu/www/eric_ae/intass.html">assessment</A> strategies will be used to measure learning and skills acquisition?</P>
</UL>
<P>Online examples of technology plans are available in the <A HREF="http://www2.msstate.edu/~lsa1/nctp/index.html">National Center for Technology Planning</A> World Wide Web site.</P>
<P>
<H3>Show, then tell</H3>
<P>When trying to sell the school board on the value of technology, a demonstration is worth a thousand words. Here are some ways to persuasively present the power of technology:</P>
<UL>
<LI><P>Ask educational manufacturers and software publishers if they will either loan your school or district hardware and software or come to your meeting to make a presentation for you.</P>
<LI><P>Take advantage of the free guest accounts or trial offers to show your school board what's available online.</P>
<LI><P>Obtain low-cost videos from <A HREF="http://www.gov.nb.ca/hotlist/nasa.htm">NASA</A> and the <A HREF="http://www.ed.gov/pubs/ResearchersGuide/Programs.html">National Center for Education Statistics</A>. Many technology companies offer free videos about success stories involving their products--ask your sales representatives, and be sure to contact <A HREF="MAILTO:ait@ait.net">AIT Customer Service</A> at (800) 457-4509 for free video previews of interactive courses using videodisc and software technology. </P>
<LI><P>Coordinate tours to high-tech schools. Your state <A HREF="/links/lstates.htm">Department of Education</A> can identify these schools.</P>
</UL>
<H3>Seek outside funds</H3>
<P>If you can figure out how to pay for all or part of a technology investment, it's likely you can purchase what you want for your school. Obtain grant and funding information for educational technology from local colleges and universities; technology companies; online service providers; the local business community; and federal, state and district budgets. Online information about grants and funding for educational technology include:</P>
<UL>
<LI><P>The <A HREF="http://eryx.syr.edu">Educational Resources Information Center</A> (ERIC). Ask for the AskERIC InfoGuide called &quot;Grants and Funding Sources.&quot;</P>
<LI><P>U.S. Department of Education's <A HREF="http://www.ed.gov/offices/OERI/oeribro.html">Office of Educational Research and Improvement</A> (OERI), via <B>gopher: gopher.ed.gov (port 70)</B>. </P>
<LI><P>U.S. <A HREF="http://www.nsf.gov">National Science Foundation</A>'s Science and Technology Information System. Telnet to <B>telnet stis.nsf.gov</B>, login: public; via <B>gopher: stis.nsf.gov (port 70)</B>.</P>
</UL>

<H3>Communicate, communicate, communicate</H3>
<P>Develop a method of regular communications with your school board about technology-related successes and issues. A newsletter is a great way to spread the word about your progress, projects, and successes.</P>
<P><I>Adapted from &quot;Networks of Knowledge...A Resource Guide,&quot; BellSouth TechKNOWLEDGEy '95, Community Connections</I></P>

