<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996 - Bringing a public school into the 21st century</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996</H1>
<HR>

<H1>Getting Started...</H1>
<H2>Bringing a public school into the 21st century</H2>
<P>by Mark Johnson</P>

<P>Getting a public school system up to date with new technologies that are appropriate and timely for students is often a frustrating experience. The problem is compounded by a traditionally slow reaction time to new ideas and a shortage of funds. Teachers are not unfamiliar with these barriers to modernizing their classrooms.</P>

<P> Teachers and administrators at the Ontario School System, a small rural school outside of Mansfield, Ohio, have tackled the problem through grants, board funding, and the formation of a technology foundation.</P>

<P> The local board of education has invested precious resources into a fiber optic linkup, new computers, and inservices for the staff that have run costs in excess of $100,000. Although this is an impressive figure for a small system of less than 1,900 students, it doesn't begin to meet the needs of students. Technology is expensive and ever-changing and we are like most school systems: we just don't have the financial resources to cope with these changes.</P>

<P> Another source of funding is through grant writing. Anyone that &quot;entered the arena&quot; to compete for grants knows how time-consuming this can be. We have had some success through a manipulatives and software grant from the Mildred Holdren Jennings Foundation. This grant was for the purchase of Lego Dacta sets to teach simple machines at the fourth-grade level. A logo software package called TCLogo was also purchased to give upper elementary students an introduction to computer programming.</P>

<P>We are currently teaming up with a local branch of the <A HREF="http://www.orst.edu">Ohio State University</A>, expanding this program to take advantage of recently installed linkups to the outside world. With a little luck, we will be awarded $10,000 from the Toyota Tapestry Grant to form a triad between Stingel, OSU, and the middle school. Students will be able to invent machine models available through <A HREF="http://legowww.itek.norut.no/faq/FAQ.html">Lego Dacta</A> and share ideas online with peers and adults. We keep in touch with Internet sources and the county office so that any grant or funding ideas do not go unexplored before expiration dates.</P>

<P> The technology foundation is the culmination of over two years of effort by staff and administration to implement a strategic plan developed in 1994. The foundation is a legal entity that was formed through the efforts of the committee, our curriculum director, and a local lawyer who donated his time to the legal documentation. Individuals and corporations can use the foundation to donate monies to our efforts. The foundation is also linked up with another established local foundation and enjoys tax-exempt status. Although it is a new effort, the initial reaction of the community to its formation has been positive and the balance has begun to grow.</P>

<P> We are just beginning! The task of shaping curriculum that incorporates new technologies into the everyday experiences of our students is the next step. Obviously, not every staff member is overjoyed with the changes, but the excitement is contagious and I'm sure those old attitudes will change. With a little effort, you can bring your school into the 21st century ready to meet the challenges of a changing world.</P>

<P><I>Mark Johnson is a fourth-grade teacher at Stingel Elementary School in Mansfield, Ohio.</I></P>

