<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996 - TECHNOS Press: Who will warm your bones?</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996</H1>
<HR>

<P><B>TECHNOS</B>PRESS</P>
<H1>Who will warm your bones?</H1>
<H2><I><A HREF="/technos/technos/">TECHNOS Quarterly</A></I> begins fifth year with special offer</H2>
<IMG SRC="/images/pictures/oriental.gif" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE="10">
<BR><BR>
<P><I>&quot;Now, how can two lone men need so much room? Cannot father and son sleep together? The warmth of the young one's body will comfort the old one's cough.&quot;</P>
<P>But the father always replied, &quot;I am saving my bed for my grandson. He will warm my bones in my age.&quot;</P>
<H6>Artwork by Joe Lee</H6><BR CLEAR=LEFT>

<P></I>In the pre-revolution <A HREF="http://www.kn.pacbell.com/wired/China/ChinaQuest.html">China</A> depicted in Pearl Buck's <I>The Good Earth,</I> intergenerational transfers dictated the responsibilities and benefits of status and age. Successive generations cared for those who gave them life. Wang Lung's father, for example, assumed that the warmth of his grandchildren would ease the cold and ache of his old age. </P>

<P> AIT's 1996 Distinguished Fellow Morton Marcus explores the intergenerational transfers implicit in modern American society in the Spring 1996 issue of <I><A HREF="/technos/technos/">TECHNOS: Quarterly for Education and Technology</A>.</I> In his essay, &quot;Who Will Warm Your Bones?&quot; Marcus draws a startling lesson on funding education in the 21st century: If you hope to retire well tomorrow, educate your neighbor's children today.</P>

<P> The role of economics in educational reform is also considered from numerous perspectives in the Spring 1996 issue of <I><A HREF="/technos/technos/">TECHNOS</A></I>:</P>
<UL>
<LI><P><A HREF="http://www.nobel.se/">Nobel Prize</A>-winning economist Milton Friedman advocates introducing competition to the public school system.</P>
<LI><P><A HREF="http://www.gsu.edu/">Georgia State University</A>'s Asa G. Hilliard III contends that such competition obscures the real issue: Who will pay for those who cannot pay for themselves?</P>
<LI><P>Howard D. Mehlinger, director of Indiana University's <A HREF="http://cee.indiana.edu/index2.html">Center for Excellence in Education,</A> argues that school reform will fly farther and faster if propelled by the tailwind of technology.</P>
<LI><P>William L. Lepley and A. James Jones of the <A HREF="http://ally.ios.com/~mcw39/Milt/Milt.html">Milton Hershey School</A> assert that America knows how to educate its poor children, but wonder if it's willing to foot the bill.</P>
</UL>

<P>To celebrate the beginning of the fifth year of <I><A HREF="/technos/">TECHNOS Quarterly,</A></I> TECHNOS Press is offering subscriptions to<I> <A HREF="/technos/">TECHNOS</A></I> at the 1992 rate. For a limited time, new subscribers--and current subscribers--can get an <A HREF="/ait-bin/tech_sub.htm">online discount</A> on the 1995 rate of $20 for one year ($24 for international subscriptions and $16 for library subscriptions).</P>

