<TITLE>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996 - Tune In: Mathematics Is Elementary</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>AIT.Net News, Spring 1996</H1>
<HR>

<P><B>TUNE</B>IN</P>
<H1><I>Mathematics Is Elementary</I></H1>
<H2>AIT offers ITV series for grades 2-4</H2>

<P><A HREF="http://www.best.com:80/~dillon/recycle/">Recycling</A> aluminum cans, selecting the correct change for a vending machine, and other experiences take on new meaning in <I>Mathematics Is Elementary,</I> the new ITV series from AIT and the <A HREF="http://www.wecb.org/">Wisconsin Educational Communications Board</A>.</P>

<P>Designed for grades 2-4, <I>Mathematics Is Elementary</I> brings 13 key <A HREF="http://archives.math.utk.edu/k12.html">mathematics</A> concepts to life with contextual examples from the students' own experiences. Each 15-minute program explores mathematics in real-life situations, such as finding the fractions in a divided <A HREF="http://www.ecst.csuchico.edu/~pizza/">pizza</A> and the patterns in neighborhood <A HREF="http://www.ionet.net/~usarch/ak-arch0.shtml">architecture.</A></P>

<P>Produced by General Learning Video, the <I>Mathematics Is Elementary</I> curriculum follows NCTM standards. Built-in teacher inservice is extended by an online service for professional development and peer interaction.</P>

<P>For content information and broadcast rights, contact Jan Caudill at (800) 457-4509, extension 235, or Barbara Ravellette at (800) 236-6248.</P>

<H3>Upgrade your AV roster with interactive math</H3>
<P>Be sure to include the 13 elementary mathematics programs in your AV resources for the 1996-97 school year. Now available for individual purchase, each 15-minute video helps second- through fourth-graders gain confidence in their mathematical abilities as they solve real-life problems.</P>

<P>The following programs and a comprehensive teacher's guide with activities that encourage parental involvement are available for delivery in July 1996:</P>
<OL>
<LI><P>&quot;How Many Ways?&quot; (algebra and function)</P>
<LI><P>&quot;What's Next?&quot; (patterns and relations)</P>
<LI><P>&quot;How Can I Find Out?&quot; (collecting and using data)</P>
<LI><P>&quot;How Long? How Far?&quot; (linear measurement)</P>
<LI><P>&quot;What's a Thousand?&quot; (place value)</P>
<LI><P>&quot;What Is It Worth?&quot; (operations and computations)</P>
<LI><P>&quot;What Shape Is It In?&quot; (geometry, 2-D)</P>
<LI><P>&quot;How Much? How Many?&quot; (weight measurement)</P>
<LI><P>&quot;What Size Do I Need?&quot; (geometry and measurement)</P>
<LI><P>&quot;Is It Likely?&quot; (probability and statistics)</P>
<LI><P>&quot;Is There Action in Fractions?&quot; (number sense and fractions)</P>
<LI><P>&quot;What's This When It Comes Together?&quot; (geometry, parts and shapes, 3-D)</P>
<LI><P>&quot;How Much Does It Hold?&quot; (volume measurement)</P>
</OL>
<P>For more information, contact Barbara Ravellette at (800) 236-6248.</P>

<H3>Preview via Channel One</H3>
<P>Channel One (the Classroom Channel) now offers selections from AIT's science, math, and art programs for teacher preview and purchase. After viewing the programs, teachers can purchase the aired programs and all other programs in the series. For more information, call Jan Caudill at (800) 457-4509, extension 235, or Barbara Ravellette at (800) 236-6248.</P>

<H4>Spring 1996 AIT.Net News</H4>
<HR>

