<HEAD>
<TITLE>TECHNOS Press - Interview with Gerald Bracey</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>TECHNOS Press</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Gerald Bracey on American Education</H2>

<H3 ALIGN=RIGHT>An Interview with the author of FINAL EXAM</H3>
<P>
Gerald W. Bracey is the first Distinguished Fellow of the Agency for Instructional Technology (AIT). Dr. Bracey's TECHNOS Press book is called FINAL EXAM: A Study of the Perpetual Scrutiny of American Education. It is a definitive examination of the educational reform movement in this country, and its results. FINAL EXAM provides historical perspectives on assessment, standards, outcomes, and criticism of U.S. public schools. We talked with Gerald Bracey about his book and the issues raised in it.</P>
<HR>
<P>
Choose a question from the list below to begin your version of the Bracey interview or access the <A HREF="bracey-all.htm"><B>complete Bracey interview</B></A> to read the entire exchange.
</P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/arrowr.gif"><A HREF="bracey01.htm">Dr. Bracey, why did you write this book?</A></P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/arrowr.gif"><A HREF="bracey02.htm">Is American education in bad shape--and if so, can it be fixed?</A></P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/arrowr.gif"><A HREF="bracey03.htm">If American education is not in bad shape, why are we hearing so many bad things about it these days?</A></P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/arrowr.gif"><A HREF="bracey04.htm">Are we just spinning in our tracks? Will we ever figure out what to do about our educational system?</A></P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/arrowr.gif"><A HREF="bracey05.htm">Maybe this conversation should have begun with a discussion of the purpose of public education, or learning, in the United States.</A></P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/arrowr.gif"><A HREF="bracey06.htm">What did Thomas Jefferson mean when he talked about "an aristocracy of worth and genius"?</A></P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/arrowr.gif"><A HREF="bracey07.htm">You mention in your Prologue this pendulum swing between Jefferson's aristocracy of worth and genius and the philosophy that everyone can learn. What's the significance of that swing in history?</A></P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/arrowr.gif"><A HREF="bracey08.htm">Is the notion that all children can learn a realistic one?</A></P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/arrowr.gif"><A HREF="bracey09.htm">So, is the American dream of an education for all citizens just a pipe dream?</A></P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/arrowr.gif"><A HREF="bracey10.htm">What one thing would you change in the focus of education as you've encountered it during your career?</A></P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/arrowr.gif"><A HREF="bracey11.htm">If you could build your own school and staff it with teachers, where would you start? What would be the first thing you would do?</A></P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/arrowr.gif"><A HREF="bracey12.htm">Dr. Bracey, do you have any final thoughts on this topic?</A></P>

<HR>
<P>This conversation with Gerald W. Bracey, author of FINAL EXAM, has been brought to you by TECHNOS Press of the Agency for Instructional Technology. You can order a hardback copy of FINAL EXAM for only $24.98, plus $4.00 shipping and handling. <A HREF="/ait-bin/profile.htm"><B>Register</B></A> with AIT.Net and receive an online discount on FINAL EXAM. Call AIT Customer Service at 1-800-457-4509, extension 254, to order your copy. MasterCard and VISA orders will be accepted.
</P>

<HR>
