<HEAD>
<TITLE>1996 Distinguished Fellow Book</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>

<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>TECHNOS Press</H1>
<HR>

<H2 align=center>1996 Distinguished Fellow Book by Morton Marcus</H2>

<P>TECHNOS Press is pleased to announce a new book by AIT&#146;s 1996 Distinguished Fellow, Morton Marcus, to be published in the fall of 1996.  A weekly columnist on current economic issues for 37 newspapers, Marcus is director of the Indiana Business Research Center at the Indiana University School of Business.</P>

<P>With a focus on funding for public education, this book examines current education dilemmas and intergenerational concerns, with help from everyman Septum Sixpack, his family, and friends. Incisive and entertaining, it is generously supported by data and filled with powerful, compelling arguments, as it challenges America&#146;s approach to education funding and the dreaded &#147;T&#148; word&#151;taxation. The author&#146;s candor, insights, and humor make this book a must-read for anyone interested in our financial and educational future, not just economists, tax experts, and educators.</P>

<P>For a preview, <A HREF="/journal/volume5/3marcus.htm"><B>click here</B></A>. </P>

<P>For additional information, call Amy Bond at (812)339-2203 ext.220</P>


