<HEAD>
<TITLE>Education Under Fire Presenters</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><A NAME="TOP"><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></A></TD><TD>

<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1>Education Under Fire Presenters</H1>
<HR>

<P><A NAME="MEIER"><IMG SRC="/images/pictures/389meier.gif" ALIGN=LEFT></A><B>Deborah W. Meier</B> is president of the Center for Collaborative Education, a network of nearly 40 elementary, middle, and high schools that are working on issues of school reform in New York City.  A true reformer, she encourages new approaches to enhance democracy and equity in public education.  She stresses the need to create school environments in which children can learn to see themselves as creators and possessors of &#147;wonderful ideas.&#148;  She also believes that teachers must experience the power of their own ideas and the power of joining with parents in making critical decisions that affect their schools.</P>

<P><B>Deborah Meier</B> was a founding member of the National Board for Professional Teaching Standards and the North Dakota Study Group on Evaluation, and she is currently on the boards of the Educational Alliance Fair Test, the Association of Union Democracy, and other organizations. Born in New York City, she attended Antioch College and received a master's degree in history from the University of Chicago in 1955.   Over the years, she has played many roles; among them teacher, principal, and elected school board member.  She is the author of many works, including the recent book, <I>The Power of Their Ideas</I> &copy; 1995.</P>
<HR WIDTH="50%">

<P><A NAME="LEVIN"><IMG SRC="/images/pictures/389levin.gif" ALIGN=LEFT></A></A><B>Henry M. Levin</B> is the David Jacks Professor of Higher Education and Economics at Stanford University, where he also directs the Center for Educational Research.  A specialist in the economics of education and human resources, Dr. Levin's work has dealt with educational finance, educational and workplace productivity, and investment strategies for educationally at-risk students. Much of his recent work focuses on the establishment of &#147;accelerated schools,&#148; which are designed to bring all students into the educational mainstream and to make them capable of academic success.  In 1994&#150;95 more than 700 elementary and middle schools in 37 states were involved in the accelerated schools process.</P>

<P>In 1991 the <I>New York Times</I> named Dr. Levin one of nine &#147;national standard-bearers&#148; in educational innovation. Before arriving at Stanford in 1968, he earned a Ph.D. in economics at Rutgers and served as a research economist at the Brookings Institution.  Since then he has been a visiting professor in Spain and China, served as editor of the Review of Educational Research, and published 13 books and numerous articles.</P>
<HR WIDTH="50%">

<P><A NAME="PROTHROW"><IMG SRC="/images/pictures/389proth.gif" ALIGN=LEFT></A><B>Deborah B. Prothrow-Stith, M.D.</B>, is assistant dean of government and community programs and professor of public health practice in the Department of Health Policy and Management at Harvard University's School of Public Health.  Dr. Prothrow-Stith regards violence as a societal &#147;disease&#148; that can be prevented through public health strategies.  After receiving a B.A. in mathematics from Spelman College, she earned her M.D. at Harvard Medical School in 1979. She trained in internal medicine at Boston City Hospital, where the typical &#147;stitch 'em up, send 'em out&#148; response to patients injured by violent acts that she observed there led her to examine ways of preventing violence.</P>

<P><B>Deborah B. Prothrow-Stith</B> is the author of <I>Violence Prevention Curriculum for Adolescents</I>, the first such work for schools and communities. She is coauthor of <I>Deadly Consequences</I>, the first book to present the public health perspective on violence to a mass audience, and of <I>Health Skills for Wellness</I>, a high school textbook that contains a chapter devoted exclusively to the prevention of violence.   In 1987 Dr. Prothrow-Stith became the first woman to be appointed commissioner of public health for the commonwealth of Massachusetts.  Her honors include the World Health Day Award (1993).</P>
<HR WIDTH="50%">

<P><A NAME="DAGGETT"><IMG SRC="/images/pictures/389dagge.gif" ALIGN=LEFT></A><B>Willard R. Daggett</B> is the director of the International Center for Leadership in Education.  He has established a worldwide reputation for encouraging educational systems to provide more relevant skills and knowledge for all students, especially in mathematics, science, language arts, and school-to-work programs.  Before joining the Center, Dr. Daggett held several management posts at the New York State Education Department, where he spearheaded a series of initiatives to focus the state's educational system on the skills and knowledge that students need in today's technological, information-based society.</P>

<P><B>Willard R. Daggett</B> has developed a broad, practical perspective on educational issues, having served as both a teacher and an administrator at the secondary, college, and university levels.  The states of Texas, Michigan, and North Carolina hired him to lead their school-reform efforts, and he has worked with ministries of education in several foreign countries to establish standards in mathematics, science, and language arts. He has authored 12 textbooks and numerous professional articles.</P>
<HR WIDTH="50%">

<P><A NAME="SPADY"><IMG SRC="/images/pictures/389spady.gif" ALIGN=LEFT></A><B>William G. Spady</B> has received international recognition for his work on outcome-based restructuring. In 1986 he founded the High Success Network, a consulting organization dedicated to improving educational systems. His network has helped policymakers, educators, and parents in more than 40 states and provinces in the U.S. and Canada implement the principles of outcome-based education. As a member of the staff of the American Association of School Administrators, Dr. Spady served as director of its National Center for the Improvement of Learning and cofounded the Network for Outcome-Based Schools.</P>

<P>Dr. Spady earned all of his degrees, including a doctorate in the sociology of education, at the University of Chicago. His first positions were academic appointments at Harvard University and the Ontario Institute for Studies in Education. His credits include numerous articles, lectures, frameworks, and videotapes. A major recent work, <I>Outcome-Based Education: Critical Issues and Answers</I>, was published in 1994.</P>
<HR WIDTH="50%">

<P><A NAME="SIMONDS"><IMG SRC="/images/pictures/389simon.gif" ALIGN=LEFT></A><B>Robert L. Simonds, Ph.D.</B>, is founder and president of Citizens for Excellence in Education (CEE) and of the National Association of Christian Educators (NACE). He served on President Ronald Reagan&#146;s Forum to Implement the National Commission on Excellence in Education Report: <I>A Nation at Risk</I>. He is the publisher of three journals and newsletters; and the author of several books on reforming education, strengthening families, and electing school board members.</P>

<P>Dr. Simonds has served in public schools for 34 years, first as a high school teacher, then as a principal, next as a professor at a community college, and most recently as an adjunct professor of teacher education at UCLA. Much of his travel and speaking time is devoted to CEE.</P>
<HR WIDTH="50%">

<H2>The Interviewer:</H2>
<P>Conducting each interview is <B>Dr. Phillip Harris</B>, director of the Center for Professional Development and Services for Phi Delta Kappa International. During his 30 years in the field of education&#151;as an elementary school teacher, reading clinic diagnostician, university research director, faculty member, author, and consultant&#151;he has developed expertise in methods of instruction, reading research, program evaluation, personnel evaluation, alternative assessment of students, and professional-development planning. His broad, eclectic background makes him uniquely qualified to discuss the reconceptualization of education with leading thinkers.</P>
<HR>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><BIG>Return to AIT&#146;s <A HREF="/catalog/catpages/c389.htm">Education Under Fire</A> product description page.</BIG></P>

