<HTML>
<TITLE>Respecting Diversity in the Classroom #386</TITLE>
<BODY>

<H2>Respecting Diversity in the Classroom</H2>

Professional Development, Multicultural Education, and Teaching Techniques for Preservice/Inservice Educators<P>

Discover the power of diversity as an educational resource--one that you can use to enhance your curriculum, and broaden the perspectives and enrich the lives of your students. <B>Respecting Diversity in the Classroom</B> provides insight into the nature of diversity and illustrates how to establish your own successful multicultural curriculum. Define and apply the culture of individual classrooms to the development of multicultural lessons and activities. Incorporate "thematic learning" techniques into current curricula--blending cultural messages into reading, history, geography, social studies, and mathematics lessons. Recognize the various learning styles and communications techniques of different ethnic groups, and develop methods for responding to these issues. Learn to effectively use different types of study tools to reach students and their families and to encourage multicultural understanding without racial and ethnic separatism.<P>

<B>Video Program</B><BR>
The video program develops guidelines for building a multicultural curriculum and practicing techniques for implementing multicultural materials in the classroom. "Attend" a seminar by Dr. Lucinda Lee Katz, director of the University of Chicago Laboratory Schools, where different multicultural issues are introduced and discussed. Successful teaching techniques are then illustrated with scenes from multicultural awareness programs in such diverse cities as Seattle, Minneapolis, and Chicago.  Expert commentary on multicultural awareness programs is provided by award-winning teachers and educational leaders like Historian Arthur Schlesinger, Jr., and former U.S. Assistant Secretary of Education Diane Ravitch. Dramatic reenactments of typical classroom situations then allow teachers to practice their newly acquired skills. As these scenarios illustrate, diversity is much more than race. It involves ethnicity, religion, age, gender, and socio-economic status.  The video program is divided into five sections:
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>Introduction--Defining Culture
<LI>Respecting Diversity--A Resource in Our Midst
<LI>The Multicultural Curriculum
<LI>Instructional Strategies to Fit Student Needs
<LI>Caution--Unpaved Road Ahead
</UL><P>

<B>Facilitator's Guide</B><BR>
The activities and resources included in the facilitator's guide provide the necessary tools to formulate a practical multicultural awareness program for your school or classroom. Designed to be used interactively with the video program, the facilitator's guide encourages discussion, problem solving, and skills development during pause points in the video.<P> 

<B>Respecting Diversity in the Classroom</B> was produced by Del Rey Communications, Chicago, and AIT (1996).<P>

<H3>Purchase</H3>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD>The Complete Set</TD><TD>(#386-M01)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>$295.00</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Additional Facilitator's Guides</TD><TD>(#386-FG)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>Each $8.95</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
Prices do not include shipping, handling, and insurance.<P>

Purchase <B>Respecting Diversity in the Classroom</B> (#386-M01) for $295.00 and receive one 60-minute video program and one 56-page facilitator's guide in a vinyl album.<P>

<TABLE>
<TR><TD>VIDEO</TD><TD>One 60-minute program</TD></TR>
