<HTML>
<TITLE>Looking from the Inside/Out #370</TITLE>
<BODY>

<H2>Looking from the Inside/Out</H2>

Health and Guidance for Grades 3-5, Teachers, Parents, and Caregivers<P>

<B>Give children the emotional skills they need to make healthy decisions</B><P>

It is difficult for young people to identify their feelings, other than to say they feel
good or bad. And yet, emotions are as much a part of good health as hygiene, physical fitness, and nutrition. Emotions affect a student's physical health, self-concept, behavior, and relationships. Equipped with life-coping skills, children are more likely to make healthy, responsible choices.<P>

<B>Looking from tbeInside/Out</B> strengthens existing health education instruction by:
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>helping students in grades 3, 4, and 5 acquire the knowledge, skills, and attitudes they need to understand and cope with their emotions and feelings
<LI>providing reinforcement through positive role models in contemporary
situations
<LI>providing teachers with interactive and engaging classroom activities
<LI>reinforcing the role parents play in developing positive health skills in their
young children
</UL><P>

<B>Looking from the Inside/Out</B> consists of fifteen 15-minute programs and an extensive teacher's guide that incorporates a parental component with at-home activities. The video programs feature dramatic sequences with children of various ethnic groups and races, and children with disabilities coping with their emotions. An on-camera host leads student viewers and studio children through "children-on-the-street" interviews, illustrated stories, and performed songs.<P>

The teacher's guide includes program objectives, summaries, and lesson plans. The
guide also includes a unique "community connection" that recommends activities to
involve parents and representatives from the community.<P>

<B>Looking from theInside/Out</B> continues the tradition of the phenomenally successful <A HREF="c087.html"><B>Inside/Out</B></A>. Created in 1973, <B>Inside/Out</B> has enjoyed wide use by educators as an effective resource for helping 8-10-year-olds handle their feelings. AIT, the producer of <B>Inside/Out</B>, has updated the content, format, and pedagogy of the original series to create <B>Looking from the Inside/Out</B>. &copy;1995<P>

For more information, contact your AIT sales representative.<UL>
Agency for Instructional Technology<BR>
Box A,<BR>
Bloomington, IN 47402-0120<BR>
800-457-4509 or 812-339-2203<BR>
FAX 812-333-4218</UL><P>

<B>Knowledge, Attitudes, and Life-Coping Skills provide the keys to understanding emotion</B><P>

<B>Looking from the Inside/Out</B> is designed to help students discover their emotions. Each video program provides basic knowledge about human emotions and their universality. Then <B>Looking from the Inside/Out</B> supports that knowledge by demonstrating the physical and social results of both positive and negative attitudes and habits.<P>

To help children learn how to deal with the emotions they have identified, each of the video programs concentrate on a specific life-coping skill. Four categories of skills are developed throughout the programs:
<UL TYPE=DICS>
<LI><B>Decision-Making Skills</B> - enable students to actively solve problems that may arise in social situations
<LI><B>Communication Skills</B> - help students articulate their feelings and express their needs to others in appropriate ways
<LI><B>Stress-Management Skills</B> - show students how to identify stressors, learn positive coping strategies, and build a support network
<LI><B>Goal-Setting Skills</B> - enable students to realize the importance of looking ahead and considering future goals when making decisions
</UL><P>

<TABLE BORDER>
<TR><TD><U>WORKING TITLE</U></TD><TD><U>EMOTION</U></TD><TD><U>CONTEXT</U></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>I Don't Get It</TD><TD>Confusion</TD><TD>deciding whether to participate in a gang-related activity</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>That's Me!</TD><TD>Pride</TD><TD>handling competition with siblings</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>I'll Decide</TD><TD> Independence</TD><TD>deciding about products advertised on TV</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Sticks and Stones</TD><TD>Embarrassment</TD><TD>coping with being ridiculed in school</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Oh, Yeah?</TD><TD>Anger</TD><TD>disagreeing with a friend</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Now What Do I Do?</TD><TD>Frustration</TD><TD>resolving misunderstandings with parents</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Alone in a Crowd</TD><TD>Loneliness</TD><TD>moving to a new town or school</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>A Helping Hand</TD><TD>Caring</TD><TD>helping others</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>In Harm's Way</TD><TD>Fear</TD><TD>dealing with bullies or name calling</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Learning to Say "No"</TD><TD>Pressured</TD><TD>saying no to a dare</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Saying Goodbye</TD><TD>Love</TD><TD>coping with the death of a pet or loved one</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Will He or Won't He?</TD><TD>Distrust</TD><TD>dealing with family violence</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Changes</TD><TD>Sadness</TD><TD>contending with divorce</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Worrywart</TD><TD>Worry</TD><TD>making a decision about a health-related behavior</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>I Know I Can</TD><TD>Determination</TD><TD>identifying and accomplishing a task</TD></TR>
</TABLE><P>

