<HTML>
<TITLE>Front Row Center #383</TITLE>
<BODY>

<H2>Front Row Center</H2>

Performing Arts for Grades 6-12<P>

<B>Inspire students to discover deeper appreciation for the arts</B><P>

In <B>Front Row Center</B>, students will meet famous guest artists along with lesser known performers. They will go back stage, be on stage, and sit in the audience. They will learn about stage makeup, choreographed combat scenes, dance, and music. And they will discover the courage and commitment that drive many performing artists.<P>

<B>Front Row Center</B> will help students:
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>develop an appreciation for the performing arts
<LI>explore their own creativity and interest in the arts
<LI>understand the training an artist must have
<LI>discover career opportunities in performing arts
</UL><P>

<B>Front Row Center</B> includes seventeen 15-minute videos and a teacher's guide. Each video program focuses on a different aspect of the performing arts by featuring professionals discussing and demonstrating their skills. <B>Front Row Center</B> hostess Nan Gurley actively involves the viewer in the featured art form through insightful interviews.<P>

The teacher's guide lessons are divided into two parts. A "before viewing" section prepares students and teachers for  the program by: introducing the guest artist; defining vocabulary terms; providing program descriptions; and designating learning objectives. The "after viewing" section includes discussion questions and suggested activities that reinforce what students learn from the program.<P>

<B>Front Row Center</B>was produced by WDCN-TV, Nashville, Tennessee, and made available by AIT. &copy;1995<P>

For more information, contact yourAIT sales representative.
<UL>
Agency for Instructional Technology<BR>
Box A<BR>
Bloomington, IN 47402-0120<BR>
800-457-4509 or 812-339-2203<BR>
FAX 812-333-4218
</UL><P>

<H3>Video Programs</H3>

<B>1. The Storytellers</B> - Nan Gurley and Chip Arnold demonstrate the art of storytelling by relating two stories and a part of a miracle play.<P>

<B>2. On Guard!</B> - A professional stage combat choreographer teaches three actors and Nan Gurley how to safely fight in scenes from "Romeo and Juliet" and "A Midsummer Night's Dream."<P>

<B>3. The Composers: Bela Fleck and Edgar Meyer</B> - Banjo player Bela Fleck and double bass player Edgar Meyer discuss the process of composing music, perform a couple of compositions, and improvise a piece on the spot.<P>

<B>4. Lost in the Shuffle</B> - The roots of modern dance are traced back to African tribal dance, Appalachian buck dancing, and Irish folk dancing. Tap-dancer Savion Glover, star of "Sesame Street" and "Jelly 's Last Jam," is the guest artist.<P>

<B>5.From Page to Performance: "Ain't Got Long to Stay Here"</B> - Nan Gurley talks with Barry Scott about the inspiration for his play about Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Professional actors then perform a scene from "Ain't Got Long to Stay Here."<P>

<B>6. From Man to Monster</B> - Professional makeup artist David Compton demonstrates his art as he transforms an actor into Frankenstein's monster right before our very eyes.<P>

<B>7. Best Foot Forward</B> - Choreographers Andrew Krichels and Donna Rizzo discuss the process of creating dance while members of the Tennessee Dance Theatre perform selections from an original work by two artists.<P>

<B>8. Clowning Around at the Big Apple Circus</B> - Nan Gurley goes to New York City where she goes backstage to visit and interview several professional clowns.<P>

<B>9., 10. Songs of Musical Theatre: Parts I and 2</B> - In this two part program, Nan Gurley goes to New York City where she meets several artists involved in musical theatre. She talks to Sheldon Harnick, the lyricist for the musical "Fiddler on the Roof," and Charles Strouse, the composer for the musical "Annie," and performs with Broadway actor/singer Jack Dabdoub and pianist/conductor Stan Tucker<P>

<B>11. From Page to Performance: John Lennon and Me</B> - Playwright Cherie Bennett talks about the inspiration for and process of writing her play about a terminally ill teenager. Three actresses perform different scenes from the play that takes place in Heart House, a home for terminally ill children.<P>

<B>12. On Your Toes</B> - An inside look at a rehearsal of the Nashville Ballet reveals the discipline required in this art form.<P>

<B>13. The Story Behind the Song: Tish Hinojosa</B> - Warner Brothers recording artist Hinojosa tells how her Mexican-American has influenced her life and music.<P>

<B>14. Lord What Fools These Mortals Be</B> - Three professional actors demonstrate the role of clowns and fools in Shakespeare's day using monologues and scenes from several plays.<P>

<B>15. The Songwriter: George David Weiss</B> - Nan Gurley listens as George David Weiss sings some of his famous songs and talks about his song writing experience.<P>

<B>16. The Maestro</B> - Rod McGaha plays the trumpet, leads professional jazz players in a musical number, and teaches high school jazz band members how to interpret music.<P>

<B>17. Backstage</B> - A backstage visit to the Nashville Academy Theatre - the oldest theatre for young audiences in the country - reveals the teamwork It takes to produce a musical.<P>

<CENTER>
