<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIT Executive Director - Dr. Michael F. Sullivan</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0></A>
<H1>AIT Board of Directors</H1>
<HR>


<IMG SRC="sullivan.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT ALIGN=BOTTOM VSPACE="22" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE="10">
<BR>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER><I>Dr. Michael F. Sullivan</I></H2>
<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Executive Director<BR>Agency for Instructional Technology</H3>

<HR>
<P>
Michael Sullivan is executive director and chief operating officer of the Agency for Instructional Technology, AIT.</P>
<P>
He oversees the activities of the nonprofit U.S.-Canadian education organization, which develops, produces, acquires, and distributes instructional technology materials.  Under his direction, AIT publishes TECHNOS, a quarterly journal that reflects the Agency's leadership in the rapidly changing field of educational technology.</P>
<P>
Dr. Sullivan joined AIT in July 1990, having served as director of strategic planning and development at UNISYS Corporation in Bluebell, Pennsylavnia, since 1988.  Previous to this employment with UNISYS, he was assistant state superintendent for instructional technology in Maryland. There he directed the selection, production, and distribution of all instructional materials to schools, established the Maryland Educational Technology Network, and directed the state education foundation.</P>
<P>
A graduate of Bowling Green (Ohio) State University, Dr. Sullivan earned his bachelor's degree in English and speech in 1969.  He earned his master's degree in curriculum development at Wright State University in Dayton in 1971.  His doctorate in instructional technology was earned in 1976 at Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University in Blacksburg.  He began his career in education in Ohio schools as a teacher of English and speech, moving to the position of federal project director in Wayne County (West Virginia) schools.</P>
<P>
Dr. Sullivan is co-author of <I>Maryland EducationTechnology Network Resource Book</I> for the Maryland State Department of Education.  His writings have been published in <I>Executive Educator</I> <I>The American School Board Journal, CURRENT,</I>and <I>Eduational Leadership</I>.</P>
<P>
He was one of two Americans invited in 1992 to serve as a juror for the coveted Jopan prize, International Educational Program Contest, sponsored by NHK-Japan Broadcasting Corporation.  In addition he served as a reader/reviewer for the New American Schools Development Corporation national design competition for innovative projects.</P>
<P>
Mike Sullivan lives in Bloomington, Indiana.</P>

Mike Sullivan may be reached via e-mail at <A HREF="MAILTO:sullivan@ait.net">sullivan@ait.net</A>.

