<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>TECHNOS Press - Interview with Gerald Bracey</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>TECHNOS Press</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Gerald Bracey on American Education</H2>
<H3 ALIGN=RIGHT>An Interview with the author of FINAL EXAM</H3>

<P>
Gerald W. Bracey is the first Distinguished Fellow of the Agency for Instructional Technology (AIT). Dr. Bracey's TECHNOS Press book is called FINAL EXAM: A Study of the Perpetual Scrutiny of American Education. It is a definitive examination of the educational reform movement in this country, and its results. FINAL EXAM provides historical perspectives on assessment, standards, outcomes, and criticism of U.S. public schools. We talked with Gerald Bracey about his book and the issues raised in it.</P>
<HR>
<P>Choose a question from the list below to begin your version of the Bracey interview or access the <A HREF="bracey-all.htm"><B>complete Bracey interview</B></A> to read the entire exchange.</P>

<P><IMG SRC="/images/arrowd.gif">Dr. Bracey, why did you write this book?</P>
<P>
<B>BRACEY:</B> I think the book stemmed out of my desire to know how we got where we are today. We are, as a nation, very ahistorical. We tend not to look into the history of things, and I thought it would be useful to look into the history of education, particularly the history of education criticism, and see what people had said about schools from time immemorial. I also thought it would be useful, since there is so much emphasis on standards, assessments, and outcomes, to research the histories of those three areas, too.</P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/images/arrowd.gif">Is American education in bad shape--and if so, can it be fixed?</P>
<P>
<B>BRACEY:</B> First off, I really don't think it's meaningful to speak of American education. And the reason I say that is that the performance of different schools and different school districts is so great around the country. The chief defining quality of American education is not quality or lack of quality, but inequality. Inequality is huge around different areas. For example, in the most recent international study of mathematics skills, Taiwan and Korea as countries had the highest scores. Asian kids in American schools outscored them. Hungary as a nation finished third. White kids in American schools tied Hungary for third place. White kids and Asian kids together make up over 70 percent of the school population. So a large proportion of our kids are world class. They're scoring up there with the best nations.</P>
<P>
<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="/images/arrowd.gif"></TD><TD>If American education is not in bad shape, why are we hearing so many bad things about it these days?</TD></TD></TABLE></P>
<P>
<B>BRACEY:</B> Different groups have been bashing schools for different reasons. Let's start with the politicians. Ronald Reagan came in on an education agenda that was dedicated to vouchers, privatization, and school prayer and tax credits. George Bush extended Reagan's agenda. I am convinced that part of their strategy for trying to soften up the American public to permit the transfer of public funds to private schools was to constantly portray the American public schools as abject failures.</P>
<P>
When we turn to the universities, we find a different reason for school bashing. The universities have, unfortunately, invested far too heavily in school failure. Shortly after the first "Bracey Report on the Condition of Public Education" came out, David Clark, who had been dean of the School of Education when I was on the faculty at Indiana University, wrote me a nice letter, but he said in passing in part, "the American common school is an endangered species. The wimps in education"--by which he meant his fellow professors--"will not defend it. They're afraid of losing their money or access to the corridors of power."</P>
<P>
At the most recent "Phi Delta Kappan" editorial board meeting, Susan Furman, a policy analyst from Rutgers University, said, "If you want money, you've got to say the schools are lousy. So what else is new?"</P>
<P>
Business and industry have in their self-interest to portray schools as deficient in order to get the schools to do for free what business and industry ought to be spending money on: in on-the-job training.</P>
<P>
And finally the media have been bashing schools for a variety of reasons. In the first place, the media accentuate the negative. Good news really is no news in many quarters. In addition, media by and large tend to print what people in places of authority tell them to print. Content analyses show that 70 to 90 percent of what journalists write is what people tell them to write. And in the last 15 years, the people who have been in positions of power have been telling media to write negative stuff. There is, I must say, something unique in the conversations that I have with media representatives. I find that these people have made up their minds about the condition of public education, and they don't detach their investigative reporting from their personal views.</P>
<P>
<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="/images/arrowd.gif"></TD><TD>Are we just spinning in our tracks? Will we ever figure out what to do about our educational system?</TD></TR></TABLE></P>
<P>
<B>BRACEY:</B> I don't think we're spinning in our tracks. Sometimes it seems that way. One of the things I've noticed is that each new round of reform acts likes electro-convulsive shock, inducing immediate amnesia for the previous rounds of reform. I recall that Ted Bell, Secretary of Education during the Reagan years, in his book "The Thirteenth Man," when he reflects on the impact of "A Nation at Risk," he gets very nostalgic and asks how can we get back to a past when we were a nation of learners?</P>
<P>
Well, my research has shown that we have never been a nation of learners. I came across a very scandalous survey by "The New York Times" showing that kids knew nothing about American history, knew nothing about American geography. The "Times" was scandalized, and put this on page one with a big headline right next to the other big headline of the day which was, "Patton Attacks at El Guettar," this having taken place in 1943. What made this so incredibly scandalous was that these were not high school students who were so ignorant about history and geography; they were college students. And in 1943, you only had about 15 to 20 percent of all high school graduates going on to college. They were an elite.</P>
<P>
In one book on the history of literacy in this country, the writers looked at all of the what are called "then-and-now studies." This is when, for example, students in Indiana in 1974 were given a 1946 version of a test--1946 becomes "then"; 1974 becomes "now." By and large, in then-and-now studies, kids now do better than kids then, no matter how "now" is defined. I think what we have here is an evolutionary process where we really are getting better and better.</P>
<P>
<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="/images/arrowd.gif"></TD><TD>Maybe this conversation should have begun with a discussion of the purpose of public education, or learning, in the United States.</TD></TR></TABLE></P>
<P>
<B>BRACEY:</B> I see two purposes of public education. And I see one purpose that public education is currently pursuing, which I think it should not. I do not think that education should prepare students for the world of work. Much work is boring, demeaning, even dangerous, and schools have no business getting kids ready for that. Most work is an ugly fact of life, and we have to acknowledge that, but schools shouldn't have any part in it.</P>
<P>
The word "school," by the way, comes from the Greek word "schole," which means "holiday" or "leisure time." Schools were intended to be holidays from the grim world of work which most of us face once we get out of school. And I think they should continue being that.</P>
<P>
That said, then: the purpose of schools should be, I think first of all, to prepare citizens for democracy. Thomas Jefferson, who was our first educator of any import, saw schools as the means of protecting us from our government. Jefferson said that all governments tend to degenerate and become corrupt, and the means of absolutely protecting the nation from this was to improve the minds of its citizens through schools. The second purpose I see is to prepare people to have a rich and meaningful life when they're not at work. We need to have people who can deal with leisure. They must be able to have an interesting life of the mind when they are away from work.</P>
<P>
<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="/images/arrowd.gif"></TD><TD>What did Thomas Jefferson mean when he talked about "an aristocracy of worth and genius"?</TD></TR></TABLE></P>
<P>
<B>BRACEY:</B> I think by "an aristocracy of worth and genius," Jefferson meant to contrast the kinds of aristocracy he wanted to produce in this nation with the aristocracies in Europe. The aristocracies in Europe were based entirely on birth and blood; there was no room in or out of them. Jefferson saw the schools as a great sorting machine by which you would get the brightest kids each year and give them more education and thus in the end have an aristocracy. These would be our leaders, and that would be the aristocracy of worth and genius, not an aristocracy of birth.</P>
<P>
<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="/images/arrowd.gif"></TD><TD>You mention in your Prologue this pendulum swing between Jefferson's aristocracy of worth and genius and the philosophy that everyone can learn. What's the significance of that swing in history?</TD></TR></TABLE></P>
<P>
<B>BRACEY:</B> I'm not sure that it has a significance beyond its historical existence. I believe in part it reflects the swing back and forth between a meritocratic thinking about education in which we encourage the best and brightest to come forth and be schooled, versus an egalitarian philosophy and approach to education in which we see it as imperative to provide the same education to all children in order to permit all children to have a chance to succeed in life.</P>
<P>
<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="/images/arrowd.gif"></TD><TD>Is the notion that all children can learn a realistic one?</TD></TR></TABLE></P>
<P>
<B>BRACEY:</B> Well, the notion that all children can learn is basically a meaningless one, until you try to specify what they can learn. And then I think we are in for some disappointment. Because while I do think that many children in schools could learn a great deal more than they are learning today, it is the case that some children cannot learn. We have studied several effective remedial reading programs like Reading Recovery and Success for All. The children who move through those programs are, for the most part, ably assisted. They do learn to read, but some do not.</P>
<P>
<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="/images/arrowd.gif"></TD><TD>So, is the American dream of an education for all citizens just a pipe dream?</TD></TR></TABLE></P>
<P>
<B>BRACEY:</B> I wouldn't say it's a pipe dream. And it's certainly something that we ought to strive for because, as we have seen, education has become even more important for individual success. Schools have very little to do with our international competitiveness as a nation, and education is no longer a guarantee that you will get a good job. But what seems to be guaranteed now is, if you don't have an education, you will not get a good job. So we must strive to educate everyone. At the same time, I think we absolutely have to realize that if we were to educate everyone, the country would fall apart. It would fall apart because educated people are allergic to sweat. They won't do the dirty work. They won't clean out the cesspools. They won't sweep the streets. They won't cut branches down that are on the electric wires. We absolutely positively have to have a group of undereducated, unskilled people to do all these dirty jobs that "the comfortable classes," as John Kenneth Galbraith calls them, will not do.</P>
<P>
<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="/images/arrowd.gif"></TD><TD>What one thing would you change in the focus of education as you've encountered it during your career?</TD></TR></TABLE></P>
<P>
<B>BRACEY:</B> I think what led us more astray than anything that comes immediately to mind was an emphasis on the kinds of skills that could be assessed using multiple choice examinations. That drew us away from the old goals of developing a "disciplined mind," as they referred to it, and more to looking at atomistic, concrete, decontextualized skills--because those are the only kinds that you can assess with multiple choice questions. The desire for this kind of assessment was driven only really from a concern for efficiency. How fast could we get this assessment done? How cheaply could we get it done? And that became an overwhelming consideration once the electromagnetic/electromechanical means of scoring tests were developed.</P>
<P>
<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="/images/arrowd.gif"></TD><TD>If you could build your own school and staff it with teachers, where would you start? What would be the first thing you would do?</TD></TR></TABLE></P>
<P>
<B>BRACEY:</B> The kinds of teachers I would want are the kinds who can lead children. Educate comes from the Latin "educare," which means "to lead out." And there are teachers I have seen who are able to lead children towards educative experiences. They have some warmth. They are good people at leading seminars. They seem to have an insight into the thinking process. They also, by and large, like children. And I would start by finding those kinds of teachers because I think no matter what kind of structure you have for the school, if you have a structure at all, no matter what kind of technology you enrich the school with, at heart it's the teacher/learner interaction and the learner/learner interactions that are critical to the educational process.</P>
<P>
<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="/images/arrowd.gif"></TD><TD>Dr. Bracey, do you have any final thoughts on this topic?</TD></TR></TABLE></P>
<P>
<B>BRACEY:</B> I just hope that if people do read this book, they come away from it with a new sense of what American education has been about. Historically, no matter how good American schools have been, they've never been good enough--they've always been carped at and criticized. But you take where we were a century ago and look where we are now--it's quite an amazing process. A century ago we were a nation of 50 million people. There were only about 200,000 students in secondary school. There were some 3 million students who were of the age to be in secondary school but who were not. We now graduate about 83 percent of our students on time. More come back for degrees. More take GEDs.</P>
<P>
If you look at test scores of a variety of kinds, you find that achievement test scores are at all-time highs. You find that many of the national assessment trends are at all-time highs. You find the proportion of students scoring above 650 on the SAT mathematics is at an all-time high. The data show that, as we have gotten education to more and more people, it has not, so far as I can tell, been bought at the cost of quality. And I would hope people would come to realize what an amazing experience the American public schools' provision of education has been.</P>
<HR>
<P>
This conversation with Gerald W. Bracey, author of FINAL EXAM, has been brought to you by TECHNOS Press of the Agency for Instructional Technology. You can order a hardback copy of FINAL EXAM for only $24.98, plus $4.00 shipping and handling. <A HREF="/ait-bin/profile.htm"><B>Register</B></A> with AIT.Net and receive an online discount on FINAL EXAM. Call AIT Customer Service at 1-800-457-4509, extension 254, to order your copy. MasterCard and VISA orders will be accepted.</P>

<HR>
