by Carol A. Risher</P>
<P>
Copyright Law Providing Access to Information<BR>
Charles Schneebeck</P>
<P>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/HBotterbusch.htm">Position Statement of the Association for Educational Communications and Technology</A><BR>
by Hope Roland Botterbusch</P>
<P>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/MMosley.htm">Multimedia Development and Copyright Issues in the Maricopa Community Colleges</A><BR>
by Mary Lou Mosley</P>
<P>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/KHowat.htm">New Media Centers Program: Forum for Research and Development of Multimedia Technologies in Education</A><BR>
by Kevin J. Howat</P>
<P>
During the National Conference on Educational Fair Access and the New Media, participants met in small sessions where working committees discussed possible guidelines governing three difficult copyright issues that particularly affect the handling of new electronic and digitized media: the quantity and sources of excerpted materials; the presentation, utilization, and duplication of copyrighted materials; and the retention, access, and storage of multimedia materials. On the final morning, participants met in general session to hear committee reports. A summary of each report follows.</P>
<P>
<B>REPORTS OF THE WORKING COMMITTEES</B><BR>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/JSichel.htm">Committee on the Quantity and Sources of Excerpted Materials</A><BR>
by Jan Sichel</P>
<P>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/LLivingston.htm">Committee on the Presentation, Utilization, and Duplication of Copyrighted Materials</A><BR>
by Lisa Livingston</P>
<P>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/CRace.htm">Committee on the Retention, Access, and Storage of Multimedia Materials</A><BR>
by Carol A. Race</P>
<P>
<B>GENERAL DISCUSSION, JUNE 17, 1994</B><BR>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/IBender.htm">Ivan R. Bender, Chairperson</A></P>
<P>
<B>APPENDICES</B><BR>
