<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - Introduction to Conference Proceedings</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Introduction</H2>
<P>
<I>By <A HREF="/ait/board/sullivan.htm">Michael F. Sulltvan</A></I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>I</BIG></BIG>n a small midwestern city, a first-grade teacher sought a theme to unify her students' work, something that would engage their imaginations and interests. She found what she wanted in a favorite children's picture book, <I>Clifford the Big Red Dog</I>, by Norman Bridwell. Each year, she read the story aloud, and the children drew pictures to illustrate it. She typed the text into a classroom computer, using a program that permitted the students to interact with the words and answer questions. ("Find the word that means a color, and type it.") She recorded her reading of this story and its sequels on audiotape, so that beginning readers could practice listening to the words as their eyes followed the texts. She helped the children create a large papier-mach&#233; model of Clifford, which became the basis for activities in math and measurement. She gave out small felt cut-outs representing a big red dog to each child who read the original book, or any of the sequels, alone. The children glued or sewed these onto a bandolier, similar to ones the Boy and Girl Scouts use to display their badges. At each year's fair at the school, her class mounted a display of the Clifford pictures they had painted, and they proudly wore their Clifford badges.</P>
<P>
Good teaching? Undoubtedly.</P>
<P>
Violation of copyright law? Quite possibly.</P>
<P>
A biochemist at a California university is reading proofs for a scholarly book he has written in collaboration with a colleague in a New York laboratory. Just as he is about to send the proofs back to his publisher, he reads an article, just out, that forces him to reconsider his conclusion. He quickly scans the article into his computer and uploads it for immediate sending to his New York colleague over the Internet. He also sends electronic copies to three other colleagues around the world who are familiar with his work, asking each of his correspondents to consider how his book's conclusion should be modified.</P>
<P>
Does current copyright law require this biochemist to get permission from the author or publisher of the article before converting it to digital form and disseminating it over the Internet?</P>
<P>
Simultaneous revolutions in education and technology are forcing a reexamination of the criteria of "fair use," embodied in the 1976 Copyright Revision Act. A "literature based" reading program, encouraged for K-12 language arts instruction, requires providing students with a great variety of copyrighted print materials. Limited textbook and library budgets undoubtedly send many teachers to the copy machine. As students are encouraged to put together portfolios for assessment purposes, what criteria govern what they are allowed to include? Is a student violating fair-use guidelines when his study of <I>Raisin in the Sun</I> inspires him to direct the production of one scene from the play and to include a videotape of the production in his portfolio? What if the videotape  is shown at a school fair? Suppose his teacher takes it to a professional conference, where she plays it as part of a presentation on portfolio assessment? Should she, or her student, have arranged for performance rights?</P>
<P>
The concept of fair use was introduced in Title 17 of the U.S. Copyright Law, section 107, "Limitations on Exclusive Rights: Fair Use" (see appendix). The paragraph lists certain limited circumstances in which copyrighted material can be used without permission from the copyright holder, for news reporting, criticism, research, and teaching. The tests for determining fair use fall short today when questions arise from other applications made possible by new media and technological developments. The line between teaching and performance, and between education and commerce, has become very difficult to map. A teacher may hold up a book before his class to show an illustration or chart, but can the same teacher hold up the book before a television camera in order to broadcast the illustration through a closed-circuit network to a distant learning site? Does a student have the right to put together a multimedia term "paper" that combines material from a variety of sources, including text, graphics, sound, and video?</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>Simultaneous revolutions in education and technology are forcing a reexamination of the criteria of 'fair use,' embodied in the 1976 Copyright Revision Act.</BIG></BIG></P>
<P>
Copyright experts, representatives of educational institutions, and producers of copyrighted material debated questions such as these at the Educational Fair Access and the New Media National Conference, convened at American University in Washington, D.C., June 15-17, 1994. The idea for the conference was born in 1992, when the Consortium of College and University Media Centers (CCUMC) recognized the potential of computerbased technology in educational settings and the need to accommodate instructors and students when they request that a copy of an excerpt be made. At the same time, CCUMC understood the concerns of copyright owners. Fact-finding meetings with copyright experts and concerned government agencies affirmed the need to clarify the issues presented and to provide a vehicle for their open discussion. Thus the mission was defined.</P>
<P>
Other interested parties had also begun to express concern about the vagueness of current fair-use guidelines and the difficulty of applying them to educational uses of new media. The Agency for Instructional Technology (AIT), as a nonprofit producer of innovative, media-based materials for classroom use, recognizes the great need for new guidelines for the use of multimedia technologies in the information industries, especially as they are used by learners and facilitators of learning. Further, AIT holds that convention and the law in our society should allow learners to have "fair access," which the Agency defines as the right to incorporate copyrighted electronic materials into student-produced works or exhibitions of learning.</P>
<P>
Together, CCUMC and AIT planned and sponsored the conference to foster a collaborative, working environment for representatives of the various affected interest groups. The sponsors hoped that participants would come away with a greater understanding of the issues for teachers and learners as well as for copyright holders and with a commitment to the development of new guidelines, even though there remained considerable disagreement about what revised guidelines should say.</P>
<P>
This volume contains papers by the major presenters at the conference, who together represent the full continuum of perspectives on a difficult issue. From the attack of instructional technology director Fred Hofstetter on what he feels are unnecessarily restrictive interpretations of copyright and fair-use guidelines and his call for their thoroughgoing overhaul to Time Warner counsel Bernard Sorkin's thesis that any loosening of current copyright protection is "both unnecessary and undesirable," the essays present the spectrum of the opinions in the field.</P>
<P>
Robert Wedgeworth, representing the situation of librarians, reviews the 1976 Copyright Revision Act, describes the strain that new multimedia uses have put on existing guidelines, and sketches out the kind of new framework that needs to be developed. Acting Register of Copyrights Barbara Ringer discusses the development of the current fair-use guidelines and the role the U.S. Copyright Office might play in revising them. Bruce Lehman, assistant secretary of commerce and commissioner of patents and trademarks in the U.S. Department of Commerce, describes the likely actions of interest groups in shaping new fair-use guidelines and lays out the role of his office in dealing with new technologies, especially in resolving intellectual property issues in connection with the establishment of the national information infrastructure.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>The tests for determining fair use fall short today when questions arise from other applications made possible by new media and technological developments.</BIG></BIG></P>
<P>
Michael Ribaudo writes of the quandary of an academic administrator concerned with both faculty members' access to multimedia materials and their rights to materials they have developed. Jon Baumgarten relates his experience as an attorney dealing with copyright issues in an academic setting. Educational use, he says, "is not ipso facto fair use." Bill Mullin, president of a company providing music for media productions, discusses the role of music in multimedia productions and procedures for obtaining performance permissions. Speaking on behalf of producers of educational video programs, Charles Benton relates his experience with the uses and abuses of copyright law and fair-use guidelines by the educational establishment and tells of an attempt to create a commercially viable clearinghouse for licensing off-air copies. President of a large consortium of higher education institutions and associated corporations, Robert Heterick argues that a recent initiative by research libraries and universities to clarify intellectual property rights in an electronic environment deserves support, as long as there is a recognition of the very real differences between print-and the traditions of ownership that have grown up around it-and the new electronic media.</P>
<P>
Speaking for American publishers, Carol Risher says that many of them are ready to explore new-media possibilities for the dissemination of copyrighted works and to work with educators to discuss pilot projects and experimental cooperation. Charles Schneebeck, director of computing services at a California university campus, describes two current activities and one proposal that seek to ensure fair and efficient access to information and at the same time preserve the rights of creators of works. He, like Heterick, points out that information in new, digitized formats requires policies that are quite different from those that were developed to govern print. Hope Botterbusch, representing the Association for Educational Communications and Technology, presents its position statement on fair-use guidelines. Mary Lou Mosley, associate dean of an Arizona community college, enumerates some of the promises and problems that new media and attendant copyright concerns have brought to the faculty. Finally, Kevin Howat describes a promising collaboration between software and hardware providers, publishers, multimedia developers, legal experts, governmental agencies, and educators that provides equipment, design, training, and technical advice to community and education users.</P>
<P>
In addition to the papers presented at the conference, this publication includes reports of the working committees; a summary of the open discussion on the last day; relevant sections of the 1976 Copyright Law; fair-use guidelines for books, music, and off-air videotaping; addresses of participants; and a list of suggested readings.</P>
<P>
We hope this collection will become a useful source of information and opinion to all those engaged in the debate about new media and fair access for education. If the lively discussion at the recent conference was any indication, it will not be easy to decide how much use the first-grade teacher can make of Clifford before she is guilty of copyright infringement. Nor is there any consensus about the actions of the university professor. Everyone involved agrees, however, that such issues must be aired and debated. Ultimately it should be possible to preserve the interests of Clifford's author and publisher, the teacher who uses him creatively, and the children whose learning depends on their fair access to him. <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>
<P>
<A HREF="/ait/board/sullivan.htm">Michael F. Sullivan</A> is Executive Director of the Agency for Instructional Technology.</P>
<HR>
