<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - A New Framework for Educational Uses of Copyrighted Works</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>A New Framework for Educational Uses of Copyrighted Works</H2>
<P>
<I>By Robert Wedgeworth</I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>T</BIG></BIG>hank you for the honor of opening this important and timely conference on fair access and the new media.</P>
<P>
It is important in that it addresses issues very much at the heart of the educational enterprise, namely, the environment in which we use the existing knowledge base and add to it. The conference is timely in that almost eighteen years since the enactment of a new copyright law in the United States, there are signs of great apprehension over its application to an increasingly electronic information world.</P>
<P>
Although estimates vary considerably as to when most of the much-heralded promise of the information superhighway and the National Information Infrastructure will appear, it is still a much different world than that which shaped the current copyright law.</P>
<P>
There are, of course, both promises and perils predicted for the new information environment. One of my favorites is the <I>Chicago Tribune</I>'s Mike Royko's description of his experience on the Internet. He describes it like being on a highway in a blizzard with no windshield wipers and all road signs are upside down and backwards.</P>
<P>
And, of course, there are many positive assumptions as to how potential users will behave. Several weeks ago Richard Frank, president of Walt Disney Studios, highlighted some of the insensitivity to consumer convenience by replicating a computer program for ordering pizza. Selecting the size, toppings, and method of payment took more than three minutes. He then picked up the phone and ordered a pizza in seventeen seconds.</P>
<P>
Since the major driving forces of the new information environment anticipate consumer services and products, the educational world will need to be very aggressive in order to keep its interests visible.</P>
<P>
Media educators have been at the front of innovation in education since the end of World War II. However, it may be useful to look at the university library as an illustrative example of factors that influence higher education. Libraries tend to reflect the dominant mode of production and use of educational information.</P>
<P>
As early as 1962 in an exhibit at the Seattle World's Fair, the U.S. library community demonstrated its concept of the library of the 21st century. That exhibit ran from April to October in Seattle and then moved to New York City, where it ran for two similar six-month periods. The exhibit included a traditional collection of books for adults and children. However, it featured several new technologies that were not commonly known to the public at the time. There was a UNIVAC Solid State 90 computer programmed to retrieve three types of information: bibliographies of the great authors of the western world, quotations from those authors on common subjects, and gazetteer information on more than ninety countries.</P>
<P>
Photocopying on plain paper was demonstrated in a machine designed to copy from books. Several stand-alone teaching machines, crude predecessors of today's computer based models, were used to demonstrate repetitive instruction. Finally, we improvised to illustrate a satellite network by connecting pins in a globe with thread. As of 1962 to 1964, these were essential elements of the library of the 21st century.</P>
<P>
Currently, a number of projects are experimenting with components of the library of the future driven primarily by changing technologies and changing economics. In 1994 we still see the continuation of collections of books, journals, manuscripts, and other materials, but in the future they may be stored in electronic formats for retrieval on demand. In addition, many more types of information sources are likely to appear for the first time in an electronic format. These specific changes recognize the increasing costs of books and journal subscriptions and the additional costs of building and maintaining physical spaces to house them. Since 1986 journal prices alone have increased by 108 percent while library budgets increased 92 percent in the same period.</P>
<P>
Information management systems for the storage, retrieval, display, and manipulation of local and remote information sources interconnect libraries from coast to coast and will continue to be developed for more and more specialized constituencies. While early computer-based information sources targeted scientific, legal, and financial communities, more recently the advent of audio and full-motion video capabilities to computing systems have encouraged the arts and humanities to develop networked information sources. Satellite communications envisioned in 1962 now connect the nation's and the world's great library collections, making them accessible to users across the world.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>These issues and their complexity point inevitably to the creation of collective copyright management systems that balance the interests of users and owners under broad-based agreements.</BIG></BIG></P>
<P>
The more recent developments in library capabilities have been the cause for alarm among some in the author and publisher communities. The principal fear is that, as intellectual properties increasingly become accessible in electronic formats, there will be a tendency toward greater frequency of infringing activities. On the other hand, educators recognize that a huge market exists that cannot be served without more effective delivery and access mechanisms.</P>
<P>
A recent task-force report of the Association of American Universities (AAU) presidents recognizes the enormous changes in the information environment and their copyright implications. Entitled "Intellectual Property Rights in an Electronic Environment," the report addresses the universities' interests as copyrighted materials users, creators, and publishers. Some of the concerns prompting the report include
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>expanded modes of library acquisitions with restrictive contracts or licenses that erode fair use
<LI>restrictive licenses on CD-ROM products, computer software, and on-line services
<LI>limitations on network applications and interactive uses that enhance, alter, or create new materials for classroom use
<LI>questions of university ownership interest in copyrighted materials created by faculty
<LI>changing patterns of faculty transfer of copyright ownership.
</UL></P>
<P>
The AAU recommends (1) creation of model policies that address issues of use and ownership of copyrighted materials; (2) development of a national consensus on fair use in an electronic environment; and (3) study of the feasibility of strengthening university and society-based electronic publishing outlets as means of moderating increased costs of academic information. Model policies are intended to guide practices in ways that will encourage fair use while discouraging abuses or potential infringing activities.</P>
<P>
While the AAU focus on copyright is welcome and will raise new levels of interest within the academic community, it does not address a fundamental problem that hinders the widespread use of copyrighted multimedia materials in an electronic environment.</P>
<P>
Several recent reports address different aspects of this barrier. Problems of inducing voluntary copyright registration are studied in the ACCORD report issued by the Library of Congress. In addition, the American Research Libraries/CAUSE/EDUCOM March 1992 report pinpoints the need for a copyright management system capable of handling the enormous growth and complexity of use stimulated by new information technologies. The report cites three points as motivating factors for supporting this recommendation: ease of access; limited skill required; and social, economic, and political issues.</P>
<P>
The report assumes that the current copyright law is a workable legal framework but that it needs a mechanism for managing the complex technical and legal issues in the electronic domain. The report concludes that the current system for accessing copyrighted works is unmanageable. The features of the system it proposes are open access; security and accuracy for storage and transit; definitions of compensable uses; and advantages of using the system that will accrue to users, creators, brokers, and repackagers.</P>
<P>
These issues and their complexity point inevitably to the creation of collective copyright management systems that balance the interests of users and owners under broadbased agreements. However, in all of the complex economic, social, and political issues affecting the future of copyright, we must not forget that the ultimate purpose is not just to compensate copyright owners or to encourage and support users. Ultimately, we are connecting future generations through the transmission of the culture. Perhaps this is the most important responsibility each generation exercises.  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>

<H3>References</H3>
<P>
Wedgeworth, Robert, and Barbara Ringer. <I>The Library of Congress Advisory Committee on Copyright Registration and Deposit: Report of the Co-Chairs.</I> Washington, DC: Library of Congress, 1993.</P>
<P>
Association of American Universities. <I>Reports of the AAU Task Forces.</I> Washington, DC: Association of Research Libraries, 1994.</P>
<HR WIDTH="75%">
<P>
<B>Robert Wedgeworth</B>, university librarian at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, oversees the largest public university research library in the United States. He is the former dean of the School of Library Service at Columbia University (1985-92) and, prior to that (1972-85), executive director of the American Library Association (ALA). During his tenure, Wedgeworth transformed the ALA into a technologically advanced association with major marketing and publication programs. He was prominently involved in copyright matters during the 1970s and 1980s and served on President Ford's National Commission on New Technological Uses of Copyrighted Works (1975-78). In his more than 30 years as a librarian, library educator, and association executive, he has created and edited two major reference works, the <I>ALA Yearbook</I>, 1976-1985, and the <I>ALA World Encyclopedia of Library and Information Services, Second Edition</I>. In addition, Wedgeworth has written numerous articles on international librarianship, international book trade, copyright management, information policy, and information technology. In 1991, he was elected president of the International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions, an organization headquartered in the Netherlands that represents over 1,300 library associations and institutions in more than 135 countries.</P>

<HR>
