<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - Register of Copyright Perpective</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Register of Copyright Perspective</H2>
<P>
<I>by Barbara Ringer</I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>T</BIG></BIG>he passing of the 1976 Copyright Law jarred thousands of librarians and educators in general into an awareness of legal realities. Their initial fears were calmed, however, when they found out that the new law did not appreciably change library operations or decision making. Accommodations had been worked out. People had reached some understanding of their mutual problems.</P>
<P>
But the problems were different then from what they are today. The recent series of lawsuits by the Association of American Publishers, with their unsatisfactory out-of-court settlements, and the campaign to eliminate the fair-use provisions of the copyright law now have librarians practically as well as ideologically on the defensive. Librarians also fear that price discrimination by publishers may be creating a defective licensing environment. For their part, publishers look with suspicion on efforts by the Library of Congress to bring storage-and-retrieval techniques to bear on prices.</P>
<P>
You may wonder why I left the private practice of copyright law to return to the U.S. Copyright Office after thirteen and a half years. It was the result of a crisis in the Library of Congress. Legislation had been introduced in Congress to, in effect, eliminate the main incentive to registration of copyrights still very much a live issue in Congress and elsewhere. The Library of Congress was concerned not only about its own collection but also about the future of the Copyright Office.</P>
<P>
Some of you may have heard of a committee called ACCORD, which is a very nice name for a very contentious committee. It was divided down the middle on whether to keep section 412 of the 1976 Copyright Law; this section is the issue of the day in certain quarters. Eventually there was an understanding among committee members. I think they came out of that exercise, as I certainly did, with a lot more understanding of the whole problem as it now exists.</P>
<P>
What I discovered is that the whole copyright situation had changed since the time I had retired. I had tried to keep my hand in it by reading and so forth, but reading newsletters doesn't really tell you what is going on. The whole technological climate had changed. What astonished me more than anything else was that there was an enormous impasse between publishers and eleemosynary users of all sorts, copyright users such as teachers and librarians. They were not only not talking to each other; they were not even talking among themselves, and that's why I welcome this sort of conference. We need lots more of this sort of thing.</P>
<P>
What will happen with ACCORD and the challenge to the Library of Congress and the Copyright Office remains to be seen. What we did discover was that the Copyright Office itself had to become a lot more user friendly and to encourage registration rather than to try to serve as a sort of gatekeeper for the courts. What I see as the future of the Copyright Office and the copyright system is to provide the informational infrastructure for a copyright management system that will make the process extremely efficient and extremely usable, something on-line and free to everybody that provides a complete, accurate, and dependable record of copyright information, including not only bibliographic information but also ownership information, licensing information, even pricing information. And we're working in that direction.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>We are operating on the premise that we are not going to change the copyright law. I think we can work out at least short-range solutions that will enable us to go forward without meddling with established law.</BIG></BIG></P>
<P>
There are two initiatives that I would like to tell you about. But first I should note that we are operating on the premise that we are not going to change the copyright law. I think we can work out at least short-range solutions that will enable us to go forward without meddling with established law. You can really open a Pandora's box if you get into section 108, for example. There have been dozens of amendments to the copyright law, and it has not been improved by the process. Down the road, long after I'm gone from the scene, there will probably be another general revision of the copyright law. The last one was in 1976; the one before that was in 1909.</P>
<P>
The first of the initiatives comes out of the Patent Office, from Bruce Lehman, my old pal from the days when we were working on revising the copyright law; he is now commissioner of patents and trademarks and assistant secretary of commerce. Bruce is not only a visionary but also a doer and shaker with respect to copyright. You may wonder why this initiative is coming out of the Patent Office, but that fact does reveal something that people are beginning to realize: that the concept of intellectual property is changing. Copyright used to be for literary property and patents were for industrial property and trademarks were somewhere in between. The portmanteau phrase now is <I>intellectual property</I>, and I am pleased with that. You can't really talk about software, for instance, solely in copyright or patent terms. You have to think of them both. The U.S. Constitution linked them in 1790, and maybe we're coming back to that point again in our history.</P>
<P>
The Patent Office, which is swimming in money because it is fee driven, unlike the Copyright Office, is going forward with a report, a very challenging and stimulating report, that addresses the problems we are here to talk about today. It is based on hearings and a lot of study within the Patent Office. I think it deserves our careful consideration. It's called a preliminary draft of the report of the working group on intellectual property rights, and when it is released it will be distributed fairly widely. There will be hearings on it. It has administration backing, and I urge you to take careful account of it.</P>
<P>
The report calls for amendments in the copyright law. The two that I focus on as most important involve the distribution right. The law speaks of transmission of performances and displays. What we are now concerned about is network transmissions that might be downloaded and manipulated at various places. The present law doesn't quite fit. It could be made to fit, but it probably would be better, as the report suggests, to try to make clear that the transmission right is a distribution right when it involves hard copy that you are putting on the network, visual images that are the full text of copies of works. This would be a new right that would be added to the law. It would affect teachers, scholars, librarians-the whole educational and eleemosynary community.</P>
<P>
There are other more technical proposed amendments, but the one that you are mainly interested in is fair use. This is very controversial. What I interpret the proposal as saying is basically, let's beef up copyright; let's give copyright owners substantially more protection across the board in areas where there are big gaps, like the performance of records. At the same time, revisit the whole fair-use provision and possibly expand sections 107 and 108 to accommodate what is going on in the real world. This may be a good idea, but it will not be easy to accomplish. It will be like moving a mountain. I went through such processes during the 1976 revision, and I know exactly what I am talking about.</P>
<P>
The other initiative comes out of the Library of Congress, which has been frustrated by lack of money and lack of infrastructure to go forward with it. The basic plan, as just approved, is to have a series of meetings at the Library of Congress to address problems with respect to the information superhighway, not just the intellectual property problems but also the whole technical infrastructure funding and reorganization that would be necessary in institutions like the Library of Congress. One of the main things on the agenda will be a working party on copyright in a very broad sense.</P>
<P>
Eric Schwartz, policy planning advisor in the Copyright Office, has put forward a proposal-which the librarian of Congress has accepted-to do a test project that would be tied in with another test project we have going for electronic delivery of copyright applications. (The whole copyright process would be done electronically. We are pretty far along with that project now; I think we're actually going to start the test this year.) According to Eric's proposal, we would first define the works desired by the Library of Congress for the project, and we're thinking only of printed material, although I know that many people think we should go beyond that. We need to start small. For published, printed material, we would work out a system under which we have copyright permission and would be paying royalties for putting it on line. Then we would define the community of users, and we're now thinking seriously about confining the first test to nonprofit educational institutions, for classroom use only. We would try to determine the number of students who would participate and receive the materials, then define the intended uses. We would use dedicated lines that wouldn't be open to the public in general. Whatever you call it, performance or display or whatever, would be permitted within defined limits, a certain amount of reproduction so that the students could do what students do with such things.</P>
<P>
We would identify the copyright owners of all the works included and try to find some kind of umbrella monitoring system. It is useless to talk in terms of one-on-one licensing. You just cannot do it. People will not use the material or will start using it clandestinely. We need an umbrella organization like ASCAP-not the clammy hand of government, not compulsory licensing, but some way that users could call up something, get permission to use it, and then pay for it without going through gyrations. This must be built into budgets. We cannot go forward into the next century trying to rely on the totally bankrupt notion of fair use to cover everything you want to do.</P>
<P>
Finally, and this is the bottom line, we would try to negotiate a single license with appropriate representatives for a limited time, and maybe some part of the licensing fees could come back into the system to try to make it run.</P>
<P>
I urge and implore you to be involved in this system. If you resist it-or, even worse, do not talk about it-you're going to be bounced one way or the other anyhow. We must sit down and talk together; I see this happening today, and I'm very grateful to be here to see it.  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>
<HR WIDTH="75%">
<P>
<B>Barbara Ringer</B> returned to the U.S. Copyright Office as acting register of copyrights in November 1993, having served as register from 1973 to 1980, when she retired from the office. Ringer began her career in 1949 as a GS-5 copyright examiner after earning her law degree from Columbia University's Law School. She held various posts with the Copyright Office, from head of the Renewals and Assignments Section, to assistant chief, to chief of the Examining Division. In addition, she was director of the Copyright Division of the United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization in Paris (1972-73). Ringer played a major role in the revision of the 1976 Copyright Law and active roles in the 1971 revisions of the Bern Convention and the Universal Copyright Convention. Beginning in 1980, she served in the law firm of Spencer & Kaye in Washington, D.C., in her specialty of copyright law. Ringer is the author of numerous studies, bibliographies, and articles in legal and professional journals and is a teacher and lecturer in her area of expertise.</P>

<HR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/BLehman.htm">Next Article</A></P>
