<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - Department of Commerce and Patent and Trademark Office Perspective</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Department of Commerce and Patent and Trademark Office Perspective</H2>
<P>
<I>By Bruce A. Lehman</I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>I</BIG></BIG>'d like to start by explaining why I'm on this program. There is some confusion about my role. I am commissioner of patents and trademarks but also assistant secretary of commerce, and in the latter capacity I am an advisor on intellectual property issues to the Clinton administration. It's in this capacity that I'm here today.</P>
<P>
Secretary of Commerce Ron Brown heads the National Information Infrastructure Task Force. That is the administration's primary mechanism for carrying out its promise to promote the rapid construction of the electronic superhighway. In keeping with our role as new Democrats, we're not going to pump a huge amount of money into big public works projects, partly because we don't have the money but also because the job is already being done, and in many ways quite well, by the private sector: fiber-optic cable, satellite distribution systems, cable systems, and so forth. So we already have or are building the main features of an electronic information infrastructure.</P>
<P>
The real issue for the administration is whether the full benefits of this infrastructure are going to reach the American people, and sooner rather than later. Will it have minimal benefits or maximum benefits? Will it have a minor effect on the economy, or is it going to stimulate major economic growth? Will it stimulate exports? Will it put the United States in a more competitive position internationally?</P>
<P>
The way that we make certain that the full potential of the NII, the national information infrastructure, is realized is by tuning the dials of public policy in Washington. A major part of this effort is improving and accelerating the building of the physical infrastructure. My colleague Larry Irving, who is assistant secretary for telecommunications policy in the Department of Commerce, is leading that part of the task force. He is working on bills that are already pending on Capitol Hill to try to accelerate deregulation and competition in constructing the highway.</P>
<P>
Also in the Commerce Department, Arati Prabhakar, who is director of the National Institute of Standards and Technology, is working on the issue of applications for the highway. The federal government is the biggest user, and Prabhakar is working on trying to harmonize and standardize government applications so that they will provide a road map for everyone else. If we, who use the NII in government, come up with standards, that will make it easier for all the disparate elements of the private sector to work together.</P>
<P>
We also have an Information Policy Committee headed by Sally Katzen, deputy director of the Office of Management and Budget. It has three parts. One part is concerned with privacy and security, an important area in these days of electronic data. Another is examining how we will treat government information. Work produced by the government is not copyrightable, mainly because we want to make it widely available to the public.  The committee is busy finding out how the information infrastructure can make it even more accessible to the public.</P>
<P>
The third part of the information committee is the intellectual property rights working group, which I have been assigned to chair.  It consists of people from just about all the federal agencies. Since last fall have been attempting to define the intellectual property issues and to come up with a series of recommendations. Our opening shot was a series of public hearings where about 60 witnesses testified. We have also brought in experts and consultants from time to time and talked with them.</P>
<P>
The overall NII Task Force, by the way, consists entirely of executive branch officials. Our advisory council, however, consists of about 30 nongovernmental officials from both the not-for-profit and the profit-making sectors. The co-chairs are Ed McCracken, president of Silicon Graphics, and Delano Lewis, chief executive of National Public Radio. The committee's role is to look at what we're doing and represent the community that is concerned with this project.</P>
<P>
We are now reaching a critical point. We are about to release our preliminary report. There is a good reason why we call it preliminary. We want to get feedback from as many people as possible; the information infrastructure is too important to let it be dominated by special interests. When our report is released we will seek comments that will be on the Internet. Those who wish may download the report or access it from the Internet, and we will accept comments in writing from the Internet. Those comments will be available for public inspection in our office. We will have public hearings in addition so that people can come and explain their views. Eventually we will issue a final report. Only then will we make serious recommendations for changes in statutory law.</P>
<P>
I'd like to say a few words about the philosophy of this emerging report. Fortunately we have some successful examples in history to look at. The whole evolution of the 1976 Copyright Law, which many of us worked on, and the things that happened subsequently, the amendments-all of that gives us a good history. I think basically the Copyright Law has worked very well in an era of changing technologies over the past twenty years. We don't want to completely rewrite the whole law. We would be working for the next hundred years. It took twenty years to do the 1976 law.</P>
<P>
The place to start is to decide how the existing law is going to cover the information infrastructure, then write an analysis that will serve as a guidepost for people wanting to use the infrastructure. We have precedent for that. The Commission on New Technological Uses (CONTU) of copyrighted works that was set up in the 1970s issued a report in 1978 that ultimately became the legislation on computer software copyright in 1980. Now the computer software copyright amendments were probably about five sentences long-very modest amendments to the law. But those statutory changes built on a scholarly and extensive analysis of how the existing law of copyright should apply to the new age of computer software. And so the CONTU report provides a basis for people to work on, and it has worked quite well. The proof is that even though there is a lot of anxiety in this field and people are talking about litigation, there is more litigation in real estate in one year in Washington, D.C., than there is in the area of copyright, and certainly computer software copyright, in the whole United States. That is proof of the efficacy of these processes that we evolved over the past twenty years.</P>
<P>
Some fairly modest statutory changes may be recommended in the preliminary report. But by and large the report will be an explanation of how the existing copyright law will function in the context of the digitized world of the information superhighway. This question not only has important domestic implications but also is critical to world commerce in intellectual property, to freedom of information and exchange of information on a global basis. I hope it will be the basis for an emerging global understanding of how the intellectual property law will work.</P>
<P>
I know that the present group has a particular interest in fair access and fair use. And I know that those attending this conference include people in the academic and library communities and people in the proprietary publishing community. One thing we realized early on when we got into our analysis of how the existing law would work is the very fine work that was done in the 1970s to provide a statutory foundation for the previously existing traditional doctrine of fair use and then to flesh that out with guidelines and understandings that an elementary school teacher could apply. That work was going to come under considerable strain in the digital superhighway context and those guidelines simply would not apply. Guidelines on photocopying don't have any relevance to the downloading of a copyrighted work by a PC in an elementary school and the use of that work in the elementary school, if one wants to make copies or use it in various ways and share it within that environment. We don't have guidelines on that right now. If people are to feel secure in using the information superhighway and if proprietors of copyrighted information are to feel secure in putting their vehicles onto the highway, they must have some sense that products won't be stolen. And the users need assurance that they won't be sued if they use the superhighway.</P>
<P>
This gets back to the point I made about the superhighway benefits coming sooner rather than later. If we do not move quickly to define the scope of fair use in this area, there will be a chilling effect. Publishers will be unlikely to want to use the superhighway to distribute their products, and users will be afraid to use it because of the legal liability. Those who work for school systems know that one of the most flourishing areas of law these days is advising school boards on potential liabilities. So it is important to have a new round of discussions about the scope of fair use in the digital context.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>If we do not move quickly to define the scope of fair use in this area, there will be a chilling effect. Publishers will be unlikely to want to use the superhighway to distribute their products, and users will be afraid to use it because of the legal liability.</BIG></BIG></P>
<P>
One of the things we will be doing as a working group of the National Information Infrastructure Task Force is convening a conference at which we will attempt to determine what the issues are and how to come up with a common understanding of what the scope of fair use is in the digital environment. For example, in the existing guidelines, we have section 108 for library photocopying, but we have a separate section 107 for educational fair use. I don't imagine at this point that there will be any statutory changes in section 107. I think 107 probably can work well in the digital context, but we do need to understand how it applies. This is the kind of issue we will be looking at in this conference.</P>
<P>
As for our report, we encourage everyone to read it carefully and to give us their reactions. We in the administration are concerned about improving access for all of our citizens to all of the benefits of our society. We have not forgotten our responsibility to make certain that the nation's resources are available fairly to everybody, and one of the hallmarks of the national information infrastructure project is to attempt to ensure wide access.</P>
<P>
I'd also like to say a word about the copyright management system at the Library of Congress, which Barbara Ringer also spoke about and which is discussed in our report. It is a perfect example of the tremendous central role that the Library of Congress can play in the national information infrastructure, to provide a standardized mechanism for keeping control of copyrights so that they can work in the digitized system. We applaud that work.</P>
<P>
You may recall that the Clinton campaign in 1992 was summed up in the phrase "It's the economy, stupid." Someone has now coined a phrase in the context of the national information infrastructure: "It's the content, stupid." That's what we're all concerned about: the content and the rules of the road for the content in the NII. I look forward to working with all of you in the coming months so that our nation will continue to occupy a leadership position on the emerging superhighway.  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>
<HR WDITH="75%">
<P>
<B>Bruce A. Lehman</B> is assistant secretary of commerce and commissioner of patents and trademarks in the U.S. Department of Commerce. Previously he was with the law firm of Swidler & Berlin in Washington, D.C. (1983-93). He served for nine years prior to that as counsel to the Committee on the Judiciary of the U.S. House of Representatives and chief counsel to the Subcommittee on Courts, Civil Liberties, and the Administration of Justice. Lehman served as the committee's principal legal advisor in the drafting of the 1976 Copyright Law and the 1980 Software Amendments. He has served as a member of the Advisory Committee on Intellectual Property of the U.S. Department of State and has been a member of the American delegations to diplomatic meetings and conferences in the field of intellectual property, including the diplomatic conference to revise the Paris Convention and meetings of the executive committees of the World Intellectual Property Organization and the Universal Copyright Convention. A graduate of the University of Wisconsin (1969) and its law school (1970), Lehman is a member of the bar of the District of Columbia.</P>

