<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - Copyright Issues from the Perspective of an Academic Administrator</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Copyright Issues from the Perspective of an Academic Administrator</H2>
<P>
<I>By Michael Ribaudo</I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>I</BIG></BIG>ssues of copyright pose an almost schizophrenic dilemma for those of us involved in academic administration in higher education.  We know that exposure to multimedia-based course materials can be tremendously beneficial to the learning process.  On the other hand, we find ourselves supporting individual faculty members and faculty development teams with released time, equipment, and programming support.  We expect a return on our investment that will yield multimedia applications rich in primary and secondary source materials from which our students can profit significantly.  And while we would hope for an ideal world where our faculty authors could operate without the restrictions imposed by intellectual property concerns, we recognize the legitimacy of the claims of copyright holders who expect to see their rights of ownership honored.</P>
<P>
As administrators, we often feel like laymen, neither conversant in the intricacies of copyright law nor as experienced as authors with the frustrations of navigating the system.  We are told of the barriers that copyright regulations present to the creation and dissemination of media-rich instructional software.  We are barraged by the accounts of individual faculty members and by what we read in the press to such an extent that at times we have difficulty knowing which end is up.</P>
<P>
And, if anything, advances in technology and the dramatic growth of media-rich materials now sitting on file servers and widely available over the Internet make the situation even more confusing.  From my desktop machine today, using Internet navigation tools such as Mosaic, I can browse through hundreds of virtual museums all over the world and call up to my display high-resolution images of paintings, photographs, movie clips, animations.  In most cases, the servers on which these digital data reside contain no caveats or cautions regarding ownership or what I can do or should not be doing with these files if I choose to have them forwarded to me.  In the area of World Wide Web servers alone, it seems that hundreds of new resources are announced each month, and more and more colleges and universities are deploying the networks and work stations that are making access by faculty to these resources more and mores ubiquitous.</P>
<P>
Media consumers need to work hand in hand with media owners to grapple with these issues and to look toward advancing technologies not as the source of new problems in the area of intellectual property concerns but rather as a means to new solutions.  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>
<HR WIDTH="75%">

<P>
<B>Michael Ribaudo</B> is university dean for instructional technology and government and industry partnerships at City University of New York (CUNY).  He is responsible for coordinating the research and instructional computing activities at the 21 unit colleges of the CUNY system.  Prior to assuming his current role in 1985, he was an associate dean for academic affairs at CUNY charged with coordinating a systemwide testing program and directing research on the effectiveness of the universitys basic-skills instructional efforts.  Ribaudo is a founder and former director of the New York State Education and Research Network, the regional high-speed telecommunications network linked to NSFnet.  He also served on the executive committee of the Apple university Consortium and has consulted widely with vendors and universities on the uses of computers in the classroom.  A director of the National Testing Network in Writing, he recently completed the direction of a major project to assess the effectiveness of the use of computers in college-level writing programs.
</P>

<HR>
