<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - Corporate Perspective</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Corporate Perspective</H2>
<P>
<I>By Jon A. Baumgarten</I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>I</BIG></BIG> was pleased to be invited to participate in this conference, which I think will illuminate important developments and concerns in law, technology, and education. It's interesting to be following Dean Michael Ribaudo of the City University of New York, since I did my undergraduate work at what was then City College of New York. (But I obtained my law degree from New York University [NYU], and, when my clients found NYU photocopying, that didn't stop me from taking the appropriate legal action.)</P>
<P>
I must immediately make a disclosure that I hope will not unduly disappoint the organizers of and participants in this conference. Though I am and have long been copyright counsel to the Association of American Publishers, I am not here as a formal representative of the AAP; nor do I have any authority whatsoever to negotiate or agree to specific guidelines on behalf of the association or its members. You're most fortunate today to have with you Carol Risher, the vice president for copyright and new technology for the association. I think that I speak for both Carol and myself when I say that our purpose here is principally to learn about the use of technology in an educational context, to participate in discussions about these developments, and to share publishers' concerns. We're just beginning to understand what the new role of publishers, the new role of librarians, and the new role of educators is in this exciting, emerging environment.</P>
<P>
Having made this disclosure, let me share with you a few of my personal general observations about fair use. First, in my view-and, I suggest, in the view of the United States Supreme Court, the appellate courts, and trial courts as well as the Congress- the doctrine of fair use is a limited, albeit very important, defense to copyright infringement. It is not, as some commentators would have it, a broad-based fundamental right of unauthorized use or a pillar of users' rights on a par with the exclusive rights accorded to copyright owners under the copyright laws.</P>
<P>
Second, a related concept: although the application of fair use can and undoubtedly will be affected by developments in technology, it remains a limited privilege for occasional and essential supplemental activity. The doctrine is not and should not be a basis for regularized or systematic exploitation of others' property without permission. I recall during the case I mentioned earlier against NYU the great public anguish expressed by educators that we were pursuing such a case. Nonetheless, a lot of educators came to us privately and applauded the bringing of the lawsuit. And when we began to think about it, we realized that the condemnation was coming mainly from undergraduate faculty members and that the praise was coming more quietly but equally powerfully from graduate faculty. A large part of the difference, we realized and had confirmed to us, was that graduate faculty members, who wrote the books, were seeing their royalties disappear as their undergraduate colleagues picked bits and pieces from their books and put them in homemade, unauthorized anthologies, leaving their books to go out of print.  Authorization for the use of other people's property, as Luddite as it may seem to some, is still a matter of fundamental importance to publishers, authors, and to the societal interest in the creation of quality educational materials.</P>
<P>
Third, I think it is clear that educators, school administrators, and publishers share the objective that Commissioner Lehman mentioned, and that Barbara Ringer and Bob Wedgeworth reflected as well, of a common commitment to the importance of educating schoolchildren and students at all levels of achievement in this country. Having a thriving educational environment is a national imperative. And the fair-use doctrine undoubtedly has a role here, though its parameters are yet to be determined. But just as publishers must and will come to understand the legitimate needs of educators in the technological age, educators must understand that educational use is not ipso facto fair use. Court decisions have restated and emphasized this point, not just in recent cases but as long ago as the early 1900s, long before photocopying was thought of.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>Authorization for the use of other people's property, as Luddite as it may seem to some, is still a matter of fundamental importance to publishers, authors, and to the societal interest in the creation of quality educational materials.</BIG></BIG></P>
<P>
Educational needs in this country have been and will continue to be served by a dedicated, risk-taking, and profit-seeking private publishing community willing to invest its resources, time, effort, and money in creating, developing, and disseminating educational materials. As new technologies change the nature of the educational marketplace, publishers will seek new ways of serving these needs with innovative materials designed to capture the attention and the imagination of students and to enable educators to work their skills and their incomparable magic in the classroom. Education and publishing form a cooperative, not an antithetical, environment. The usurpation of this market through an unbridled rush to capitalize on the promise of technology without regard for the interests of those-authors and publishers-who make possible the works that the technology uses will in the end be counterproductive and will destroy the cooperative environment.</P>
<P>
If this conference is a first step taken in a cooperative spirit, to be complemented shortly by other steps forward, then it is certainly worthwhile. But if this conference and others like it are simply additional steps in pressing the notion that technology is wonderful, we must use it, and everything else be cast aside, then I suggest that not much is going to be accomplished. I hope the first picture that I portrayed is the one that develops, and I look forward to participating with you. Thank you.  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>
<HR WIDTH="75%">
<P>
A partner in the law firm Proskauer, Rose, Goetz, and Mendelsohn in its Washington, D.C., office, <B>Jon A. Baumgarten</B> is a graduate of the New York University School of Law and a member of the bar since 1968. He is a former general counsel of the U.S. Copyright Office (1976-79), where he was instrumental in the formulation of the 1976 Copyright Law and was responsible for the preparation of Copyright Office regulations and practices under the new law. Baumgarten is the author of <I>U.S.-U.S.S.R. Copyright Relations Under the Universal Copyright Convention</I> and is a member of the National Advisory Committee to the U.S. Copyright Office and the International Copyright Panel of the Advisory Committee to the Department of State on International Intellectual Property. Presently his practice emphasizes domestic and international copyright, trademark, licensing, contract, litigation, and related matters pertaining to the publishing, computer, motion picture, music and recording, communications, and arts communities.</P>

<HR>
