<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - Getting Your Music's Worth Beyond Fair Use</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Getting Your Music's Worth Beyond Fair Use</H2>
<P>
<I>By Bill Mullin</I></P>

<BIG><BIG>F</BIG></BIG>eelings are often remembered long after intellectual details have faded. In the words of Thomas Fuller, "Seeing is believing, feeling's the truth." Educational media programs, while designed to convey the range from concrete information to abstract concepts, are not wholly effective as strictly factual presentations. The more compelling and engaging programs are emotional in content to some degree, even when conveying clear-cut information. Students' developed affinities toward a topic can have a great deal to do with what they retain about it. The feeling people have about learning a subject has a lot to do with how they integrate it into their collective and sometimes tacit understanding of it. One of the most effective tools for creating an appropriate feeling in your message is music.<P>
<P>
<B>M<SMALL>USIC'S</SMALL> R<SMALL>OLE IN</SMALL> M<SMALL>EDIA</SMALL> P<SMALL>RODUCTIONS</SMALL></B><BR>
Music can play a number of roles in your script. It can attract attention. It can set up, emphasize, or punctuate points of interest. It can create tension and release for problem/solution deliveries. Are you attempting some finality, or do you want to suggest that there's more to come? Sometimes music is simply a bridge from one topic to another. It acts as a nice buffer between statements. In this respect, it's the equivalent of "white space" in print. The audience can relax, breathe, and prepare for more.</P>
<P>
There are times when no music at all is best. This "effective silence" technique can act as a point of punctuation or lend gravity to a point, cueing the listener to give serious attention.</P>
<P>
<B>H<SMALL>OW TO</SMALL> F<SMALL>IND</SMALL> A<SMALL>PPROPRIATE</SMALL> M<SMALL>USIC</SMALL></B><BR>
There are educational situations where a fair use of copyright material may be valid. However, there are other cases where the program may be considered as enhancing the academic worth of the school or instructor and so gaining a "commercial advantage."</P>
<P>
So, where do you find music that complements the environment you're creating? With sufficient time and budget, you can have original music scored. With this option, you may be licensing the use of a composed piece (on an exclusive or nonexclusive basis) or you may create a "work-for-hire" agreement, where you own the song upon payment. These terms should be clearly established with the music provider.</P>
<P>
You can also opt for tracking down the licensing of a popular song. This process may involve several levels of permissions to use. The record label, which owns the recording, and the composer and publisher, who own the composition, need to approve the use. If you can only get the license for the song, or the recording use is expensive, you may want to record your own version.</P>
<P>
When original or popular music is not required to be your theme, or the process is too cumbersome and expensive, your best resource is a production music library. There is a wealth of preproduced stock music of every kind on compact disc, designed specifically for media production, at very reasonable rates. Best of all, long past are the days of the canned, postwar, newsreel/documentary sound that once was available on vinyl records. The difference between the quality of production music and the output of a major record label is virtually nonexistent.</P>
<P>
There are many advantages of using a production music library:
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>The library includes good music recordings and quality performances that are not otherwise available. 
<LI>Library compositions are designed for media use and blend well with narration.
<LI>The music is less expensive than original or licensed pop music.
<LI>It's relatively easy to get clearance from one source.
<LI>Library music is available for immediate use.
</UL></P>
<P>
<B>M<SMALL>USIC AT</SMALL> W<SMALL>ORK</SMALL></B><BR>
Your audience today, whether in the classroom or across a satellite network, is sophisticated about media. The viewer will accept a diversity of styles and moods that work with the message. This cultural mingling is present everywhere, from motion pictures to local advertising. The styles of symphonic orchestration coexist with cutting-edge rock, and the textural effects of new age or world-beat music are often superimposed on music that is eclectic, electric, acoustic, and even opera. General acceptance of this mixture allows a lot of liberty in this global village and provides a broad palette of choices as we move from project to project or from scene to scene within a project.</P>
<P>
How does music work with your message? The obvious consideration is tempo and rhythm. Your audience will readily identify with the pace of a piece, as their heartbeats respond to its rhythm. The level of activity is important, too. Do you want to imply busyness or sparseness? What style appeals to your audience's lifestyle? Styles can invoke geographic images, time periods, or states of being such as action or reflection. Some copywriters report that they often select the appropriate music first and then use it as a source of inspiration for the copy.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>When original or popular music is not required to be your theme, or the process is too cumbersome and expensive, your best resource is a production music library.</BIG></BIG></P>
<P>
<B>C<SMALL>OPYRIGHT</SMALL> A<SMALL>WARENESS</SMALL></B><BR>
It is essential to be aware of how music, an intellectual property, is acquired. There are basically three rights to be concerned with when using music. One is the <I>synchronization right</I>. This gives you permission to apply the music to visuals or spoken word. The <I>mechanical right</I> gives you permission to reproduce copies. These two rights are granted by the music library. The <I>performance right</I> provides permission for public performances of the music in your production. ASCAP and BMI are organizations governing performance rights to which most composers assign clearance and fee-collection duties. It is often best for the instructional media presentation to secure the performance rights directly from the music library, too. Doing so eliminates the concern for ASCAP/BMI clearances. Music libraries will cooperate for most forums that are not wide-broadcast exposures, such as radio and television.</P>
<P>
<B>L<SMALL>ICENSING</SMALL> O<SMALL>PTIONS</SMALL></B><BR>
Libraries usually offer at least one of three basic licenses or purchase options for the synchronization and mechanical rights. The "per-use" license may be the oldest established type. With this, you can obtain a set of discs, usually by paying a nominal access fee to have them on hand, and remit a license payment when you use particular songs found on the CDs. This option has traditionally been called "needle-drop." Costs vary from $25 to $75 per song for each application. The advantage of a per-use approach is that you have about the lowest initial outlay and only pay for what you use.</P>
<P>
If you are using a large quantity of music, an "annual blanket" or "lifetime license" may be your best choice. The annual plan gives you a quantity of music with rights to apply any of it to unlimited productions within a year. The library asks that you log what you use, reporting it at a certain time. Depending on the amount of music you get, an annual fee can run from $800 to $5,000.</P>
<P>
The lifetime license (sometimes called a <I>buy-out</I>) is long term. You pay one time for use of a set of music.  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>
<HR WIDTH="75%">
<P>
<B>Bill Mullin</B> is president of Signature Music, Inc., a worldwide publisher and producer of music for media, located in Buchanan, Michigan. Signature has been serving the broadcast, industrial, and educational markets for ten years with the Signature Music Library, containing a wide range of song styles. Applications where songs have been licensed range from motion pictures, such as Warner Brothers' <I>Pelican Brief</I>, to local school media centers, such as that in De Kalb County, Georgia. Mullin graduated from Ball State University with a degree in telecommunications. He has worked in radio and television production; has owned and operated a recording studio; has sold, designed, and installed professional audio equipment; and has managed the marketing of microphones for Electro-Voice.</P>

