<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - Association for Information Media and Equipment Perspective</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Association for Information Media and Equipment Perspective</H2>
<P>
<I>By Charles Benton</I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>T</BIG></BIG>hanks to the organizers of this conference for bringing us together to consider new fair-use guidelines for the new media in education. The subject needs to be addressed by all the affected parties. I am here to offer my experience and judgment and also to try to represent the views of my beleaguered colleagues in the audiovisual business. But most important, I am here to listen, to learn, and to get involved however I can to be of help in our collective struggle for progress on this issue.</P>
<P>
The Association for Information Media and Equipment (AIME) represents approximately 100 agencies interested in copyright law. Educational media copyright owners are represented as regular members; the National Association of Regional Media Centers and major school district and museum audiovisual and instructional technology directors are represented as associate members. AIME was formed in the early 1980s for people who were interested in copyright issues and how they related to fair use in education. AIME formed the Copyright Information Center, including the AIME copyright hotline, which services AIME members. We also produced a widely used video, hosted by Bill Kurtis, which is currently being revised to reflect the new technologies. AIME also writes articles, provides information on copyright issues, and sponsors workshops at many state and national educational conferences. AIME is here today because its members support the need for developing guidelines for fair use of the new media in education that are clear and usable.</P>
<P>
Perhaps some personal background would also be useful. This is my 41st year in the educational media business-15 years with Encyclopaedia Britannica Films and 26 years with Public Media Inc. (PMI) and Films Incorporated. We call ourselves a video publisher-distributor-licensor. Between 1978 and 1982 I served as chairman of the National Commission on Libraries and Information Science, and in 1979 I chaired the first White House Conference on Library and Information Services. As one of the legacies of the Encyclopaedia Britannica, the Benton Foundation was created in 1981, and you'll notice that, on your list of participants, I am identified as its president. Two months ago, at the request of the Clinton administration, we hosted in Washington, D.C., a public interest summit for the national information infrastructure, which over 650 people from the nonprofit sector attended. Vice President Gore was the keynote luncheon speaker. Therefore, I bring to our discussion not only a business but also a public policy and public interest perspective.</P>
<P>
I think perhaps it was this "multiple hats" perspective that led PMI to start the Television Licensing Center (TLC) in 1980, just one year after Representative Bob Kastenmeier developed his fair-use guidelines for off-air videotaping-the educational fair access and new media guidelines of 15 years ago.</P>
<P>
Improving accessibility for all educators was a goal of PMI when we developed the TLC in 1980 with PBS to license the off-air taping of "Cosmos." We can draw upon the experience of the Center. It allowed educators to tape off air and pay a fee to retain programs on tape. At that time videos were high priced, and this gave teachers the opportunity to use videos at a much lower price. It was the only attempt in the industry to improve accessibility through establishing a commercially viable clearinghouse for the long-term licensing of off-air copies.</P>
<P>
Through the early and mid '80s, the Licensing Center continued to serve a useful function with BBC, Annenberg, and other major PBS programming. But then it died. What happened? I think our experience is instructive.</P>
<P>
While all this was happening, the home video business was exploding. After settling the Beta-VHS format war in the early '80s, more and more new programs came into the market at increasingly low prices. Of course, Hollywood led the way with its feature films. Public libraries (Rochester, New York, was the first) began circulating videos "for home use only," without acquiring public performance rights from the nontheatrical distributors. Home video distributors and institutional catalog companies started to push into the educational market, using the face-to-face teaching classroom exemption as the rationale for ignoring and bypassing public performance rights. School boards and administrators began asking why there should be such a large price differential between videos for home use and videos for education. Many of the major film libraries and media centers began to atrophy as prices fell and decentralization of educational media decision making accelerated. Meanwhile, Cable in the Classroom and Whittle Communications grew with their political and business agendas only partially focused on meeting real educational needs. And PBS was rediscovering its original educational mission, most recently affirmed by Ervin Duggan, its new president, in his May 25, 1994, report to PBS member stations, discussed at the annual meeting in Orlando.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>AIME is here today because its members support the need for developing guidelines for fair use of the new media in education that are clear and usable.</BIG></BIG></P>
<P>
You may ask, what does all this have to do with the Copyright Law and the new media? What I am trying to communicate is the climate in the audiovisual sector-the "old" new media, if you will-of the educational media business where misrepresentations or ignorance of the law have led to the devaluation of public performance rights. The overall impact of this has been devastating to the audiovisual business.</P>
<P>
Furthermore, there is only so much time for media use in the classroom, and if that time is being taken up by "free" media whatever the source, through cable or PBS or fair use or otherwise then one must consider point 4 of Section 107 of the 1976 Copyright Law: "the effect of the use upon the potential market for or value of the copyrighted work."</P>
<P>
Consider how many of the established educational audiovisual producers are still producing original programs for the classroom-almost none. TV entertainment or programming produced for the general audience and somehow adapted for educational use is now more the rule than the exception.</P>
<P>
As we're struggling with fair-use guidelines for the new computer-based multimedia programs for education, which are proliferating, we need to bear in mind both the intended and unintended consequences of the new media guidelines for video 15 years ago, and do better this time around.  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>
<HR WIDTH="75%">
<P>
<B>Charles Benton</B> is chairman of Public Media Inc. and president of the Benton Foundation. A 1953 graduate of Yale University, he served in various capacities at Encyclopaedia Britannica Films, Inc. (1953-66), becoming president of Encyclopaedia Britannica Educational Corporation in 1966. Benton, who resides in Evanston, Illinois, was awarded an honorary doctorate of law from John Marshall Law School in Chicago in 1984. He represented the State of Illinois as its delegate to the White House Conference on Small Business in 1986. He is a member of the Council of Foundations' Steering Committee on Film, TV, and Video Affinity and is a delegate at large to the White House Conference on Library and Information Services. Benton serves as president of Debate America and on the boards of numerous political, educational, library, and communication organizations. The author of <I>Television in Urban Education</I>, he has also written chapters, articles, and speeches about his many personal and professional interests.</P>

<HR>
