<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - Managing Intellectual Property on the Net</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Managing Intellectual Property on the Net</H2>
<P>
<I>By Robert C. Heterick, Jr.</I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>T</BIG></BIG>he nation's capital has been much taken with discussion of the Internet, a national information infrastructure (NII)-"information superhighways"-and even a global information infrastructure. Competition for the protocols that will undergird the NII has been waged between those who favor a de jure approach and those who follow a de facto strategy. It would appear that the de facto approach to the Internet protocols has won out by sheer force of arms, or at least by having something that works and is used, in contradistinction to the laboriously crafted and mostly ignored International Standards Organization protocols.</P>
<P>
There may be a lesson here in approaching the issue of copyright and fair use in the networked world. The Association of Research Libraries (ARL) and the Association of American Universities (AAU) project, "Intellectual Property Rights in an Electronic Environment," attempts an extrapolation of intellectual property from the print to the networked world based upon laboriously crafted legal and political precedent. But the networked world isn't anything like the print world, and it certainly isn't a simple extrapolation of it. Without some better understanding and resolution of intellectual property issues there isn't likely to be much scholarly information on the information superhighway.</P>
<P>
We all know the general outline of the problem. Colleges and universities have, certainly since the 1970s and 1980s, paid a fair amount of attention to patent policy. Striking it rich in biotechnology has been on the wish list of every research university development officer. Copyright policy, on the other hand, has not captured the attention of institutional administrators, who have generally seen it as part of the faculty role in research output-something with little or no market value. What has generally been overlooked is the role of faculty members as consumers in their teaching and scholarship roles.</P>
<P>
The impact of faculty as consumers of scholarly information certainly hasn't been lost on our institutional libraries, which have contended with double-digit inflation in science, technology, and medicine serials for most of the last decade. Nor has it been lost on print publishers, many of which find packaging faculty scholarly output to be quite profitable. At the same time, abuse of intellectual property rights has been downright painful for some, particularly software publishers.</P>
<P>
Lost revenues by software copyright holders alone are estimated to be in the hundreds of millions of dollars annually. As a consequence, we have witnessed an increasing effort on the part of owners of intellectual property to seek the stronger protection of patent. As we are all painfully aware, the Patent Office has not been prepared to deal with software as "invention" and has awarded several highly questionable patents for processes that most have considered prior art. In fact, the Patent Office has recently moved to overturn one patent granted within the past year and is considering similar action on at least one other patent recently granted.</P>
<P>
One would have to conclude that copyright in the networked world is not working very well, for either consumers or owners of scholarship. As we deal more and more with networked, multimedia forms of scholarship, we can only expect the situation to worsen.</P>
<P>
The AAU/ARL report calls for several activities on the part of our colleges and universities. All are long overdue. The report encourages the academic community to come to consensus on what should constitute fair-use rights in an electronic environment. It calls for a study on creating and strengthening competitive university and society-based electronic publishing outlets. And it calls upon institutions to volunteer to create model policies for institutions as copyright users and as creators of copyrightable materials.</P>
<P>
All this is good, but we need more, I think. And what we need isn't likely to come from our historic community of scholars but is much more likely to arise from the networking community much as the Internet protocols did-by experiment, by consensus on what works, and by common agreement on what is useful.</P>
<P>
The print paradigm is one that invests heavily in up-front effort because it was expensive to typeset, to have reasonable press runs, to maintain inventories, to misestimate the number that will be sold, and to distribute artifacts of tangible weight and dimension. Much as most of our financial activities were preaudited before computers, our print media has been pre-everything for similar reasons. In the electronic age it is not even clear that editorial judgment should be exercised before "publication." It may be the case that some of the ideas that are needed to make copyright work in the information age are already being tried on the Internet and bulletin board systems.</P>
<P>
There is already a fair amount of research being done on how to transfer copyright royalties on the net. There are likely more folks than we know experimenting with embedding copyright indicators in message headers or checksums. I'm sure some folks are experimenting with "knowbots" or agents that carry and disseminate information about copyright. A number of perceptive students of the Internet and copyright have already made the observation that the time-value of information might be recognized in an electronic environment by decreasing royalties over the life of copyright for ephemeral scholarly materials.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>Copyright in the networked world is not working very well, for either consumers or owners of scholarship. As we deal more and more with networked, multimedia forms of scholarship, we can only expect the situation to worsen.</BIG></BIG></P>
<P>
So, by all means, let's pursue the AAU/ARL agenda. But let's also try to understand in what ways the electronic environment is different from print. Digital information is nonexcludable (copying is almost free) and nondiminishable (copying is almost perfect). These are not characteristics of the print world. Derivative works and the bundling of public with private goods by value adders will be characteristic of the networked world. Neither form is particularly commonplace in the print world.</P>
<P>
While the rationale behind fair use can be found directly in the Constitution, it can also be seen as a subsidy. Unlike most federally directed subsidies, this one does not direct federal funds to consumers or their agents, but rather imposes an almost unenforceable burden of unknown magnitude on copyright owners. There is no clear or compelling evidence that fair use will work in the networked world. This is not to say that there shouldn't be federal subsidies or investment strategies to ensure the rapid dissemination and easy use of "invention," only to say that contract is likely to be the sine qua non of the networked world. And just as the competitive base of the NII will drive out cross subsidies, contract is likely to drive out fair use.</P>
<P>
If we can't extrapolate from the print to the networked world, how should we approach the issue of copyright and fair use? I believe that we must create reasonable scenarios of what we expect the networked world to become and reason back from them. And as we have done with Internet protocols, we need to experiment and come to community consensus on what works and satisfies the needs of both copyright consumers and owners as well as the federal interest in rapid dissemination and use of the knowledge that supports a robust economy.</P>
<P>
Can the existing copyright and fair-use provisions be fine-tuned to cover intellectual property in the networked world? I doubt it. Wrong choices, no matter how well intentioned, can stifle the growth of scholarly information on the networks of the future. Wrong choices will ensure an entertainment-based rather than knowledge-based networked world and we will have missed another opportunity and encouraged the creation of another "vast wasteland."</P>
<P>
The stakes are high. I think Abraham Lincoln captured it well in another context when he observed, "The dogmas of the quiet past are inadequate for the stormy present and future. As our circumstances are new, we must think anew, and act anew."  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>
<HR WIDTH="75%">
<P>
<B>Robert C. Heterick, Jr.</B>, is president of EDUCOM, a Washington, D.C. based consortium of 600 higher education institutions and 100 corporate associates dedicated to the transformation of higher education through the effective and efficient application of information technology. Heterick is also vice president emeritus of Virginia Polytechnic Institute (Virginia Tech), where, in addition to his responsibilities for computing, telecommunications, and libraries, he spent more than 30 years teaching and researching strategic planning for information technology. He holds bachelor's, master's, and doctoral degrees in engineering from Virginia Tech and is the author of books and journal articles, as well as research and consulting studies for universities, state and federal agencies, the National Academy of Sciences, and many of the major information technology and library organizations. Heterick serves on the Federal Networking Council Advisory Committee and is chairman of the board of the Blacksburg (Virginia) Electronic Village, a joint venture of Virginia Tech, the Town of Blacksburg, and the Bell Atlantic Company.</P>

<HR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/CRisher.htm">Next Article</A></P>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/">Back to Table of Contents</A></P>
