<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - Use of Copyrighted Works in Multimedia: A Publisher's Perspective</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Use of Copyrighted Works in Multimedia: A Publisher's Perspective</H2>
<P>
<I>By Carol A. Risher</I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>T</BIG></BIG>he use of copyrighted materials in multimedia works is really no different from other uses of copyrighted materials-a marketplace develops to respond to needs. I would like to go through a few real-life experiences to demonstrate how that occurs.</P>
<P>
<B>I<SMALL>NTERNATIONAL</SMALL> C<SMALL>OPYRIGHT</SMALL> I<SMALL>NFORMATION</SMALL> C<SMALL>ENTER</SMALL></B><BR>
In 1971, when the international copyright conventions (Bern and Universal) were modified to provide compulsory licensing for publishers in developing countries to get the rights to reprint or translate works published in developed countries, there was tremendous concern that the publishers in developing countries wouldn't be able to find the copyright holders to try to negotiate licenses. So each of the countries created an "International Copyright Information Center" whose purpose was to help publishers in the developing countries find the copyright holders for the purpose of negotiating reprint and translation licenses. When I joined the Association of American Publishers (AAP) in 1977, I was named, among several titles, director of the United States office of the UNESCO-sponsored International Copyright Information Center (INCINC). We were still getting a few requests a year in 1977, but today most people in the developing countries know how to contact copyright holders and their need for INCINC assistance has declined. It's a service we still offer, particularly to the East European countries and those that have not used our services before, but there isn't the same fierce problem of finding copyright holders of copyrighted works.</P>
<P>
<B>P<SMALL>UBLIC</SMALL> B<SMALL>ROADCASTING</SMALL> E<SMALL>XPEDITING</SMALL> C<SMALL>ENTER</SMALL></B><BR>
In 1978, when the 1976 U.S. Copyright Law became effective, another title was added to my list. I became director of the Public Broadcasting Expediting Center. Section 118 of the Copyright Law deals with public broadcasting uses of copyrighted works, and no compulsory license was put in for the use of literary materials--materials in books such as poems and short stories. Instead there was an antitrust exemption in the act that allowed publishers to sit down with the public broadcasting entities and negotiate a kind of model licensing plan. One of the concerns expressed by the public broadcasting entities during the negotiation was how they would find the copyright holders and what to do if the publishers did not respond to their permission requests. What if the process took too long? And so AAP set up the Public Broadcasting Expediting Center and said that if any public broadcasting entity or anyone producing for such an entity was having problems locating a copyright holder or had sent a request to a copyright holder and it was not being handled in a timely fashion, that person could call the Center and it would expedite the matter. In the early days there were a few calls a month; these eventually dropped to a few calls a year, and last year we had no calls at all. The public broadcasting entities learned how to find copyright holders, and publishers simply responded to the needs of the marketplace. There was no longer any need for the AAP to expedite requests.</P>
<P>
<B>O<SMALL>PTICAL</SMALL> D<SMALL>ISK</SMALL> P<SMALL>ROJECT</SMALL></B><BR>
In the early 1980s the Library of Congress came forward with an idea to create an optical disk project. The Library of Congress, of course, has a lot of useful material in its stacks, and officials there thought if the information could be digitized and stored on an optical disk, it could be made available to users with terminals. The AAP offered to help the Library. We asked officials there to identify the list of materials they wanted to put in the system. These officials gave us a list of 74 publishers of potentially usable materials. We wrote letters to all of these publishers noting that since they were the copyright holders, the Library of Congress would be writing directly to them to request permissions, but AAP would like to facilitate the pilot project. We noted that there was much for all participants in the projects to learn, including whether users would want to read the information on screen or automatically print out everything. No one knew how users would react or how the system would work. Individual publishers weren't even sure whether each use (browsing, on-screen reading, downloading, printing) would involve separate accounting. The publishers and the Library of Congress developed a very effective and useful tool by dialoguing. The Library of Congress received permissions for, I think, all 74 serial publications to be digitized over a two-year period, stored on an optical disk, and used. At the same time, the Library of Congress convened two working groups: one comprising proprietors and the Library, the other comprising librarians and the Library. Sometimes the two groups met together. The theory behind these advisory groups was, let's identify what your concerns are. Let's realize what it is that's driving your decisions. Let's talk to each other, but let's also talk among ourselves. It's the spirit that has permeated everyone's remarks this morning-the importance of talking to one another.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>The publishing community is interested in working with users in doing experiments, pilot projects, and models so that together we can envision a new environment</BIG></BIG></P>
<P>
<B>C<SMALL>OPYRIGHT</SMALL> C<SMALL>LEARANCE</SMALL> C<SMALL>ENTER</SMALL></B><BR>
In the private sector, the Copyright Clearance Center (CCC) has received from many publishers the right to license the photocopying of materials from publishers that are participating in the system. The CCC system is voluntary; publishers choose to participate. The publishers set the fees for copying; CCC goes to for-profit corporations and says, we are here to offer you a license; these are all of the publishers whose works are in our system, and if you take the license, this is what you can do. One after another the corporations have said they were interested in "electrocopying." They explained that they have big computers and databases and would like to scan material, store it in the database, and provide access by their researchers at their desks rather than having them go to the corporate library. CCC told the corporations that they did not have that right from the publishers but would see what they could do to talk to the publishers. They came to AAP, and we created a special task force to deal with these requests. What we found is that if you tell copyright holders that people want to scan your material and stick it in their database, they all say, "Wait a minute! What does this mean?" But when the CCC came with specifics noting a particular campus that would like to create a totally digital library to serve one of its disciplines and had identified the list of materials it would like to have in digital form, the publishers responded differently. It was a manageable list-only one of a publisher's 40 journals, only three of another publisher's many books. They were all willing to participate in a pilot project because it presented an opportunity to address concerns and interests such as system security, whether onscreen resolution would be good enough to communicate the very complex x-ray and high-level graphics in some books, and whether the electrocopying would undermine or support the total dissemination goal.</P>
<P>
Then another project was brought to the group by CCC that needed other materials. And similarly, one by one, up to 15 projects were developed. AAP members individually gave approval, through the CCC as middleman, to participate in these projects because everybody had something to gain by working with the community, by dialoguing, by addressing the very complex technological and other issues that we all faced.</P>

<BIG><BIG>There will be multiple avenues to support the needs of multimedia users and developers-the private sector will respond to the needs of the marketplace.</BIG></BIG>
<P>
<B>A<SMALL>CADEMIC</SMALL> P<SMALL>ERMISSION</SMALL> S<SMALL>ERVICE</SMALL></B><BR>
AAP is probably best known for the Kinko's litigation, in which AAP coordinated a lawsuit against the chain for its infringing photocopying. As a result of this lawsuit and the determination by the courts that making course packs is an infringement and that anyone who does so must get permission for everything, the CCC developed a new Academic Permission Service (APS) to facilitate the needs of both publishers and the marketplace. Publishers put their materials in the APS system, and CCC licenses those who make course packs. This is a relatively new service; it is another example of the marketplace responding to need. In the two years of APS's existence, the number of permission requests that CCC has been able to handle has doubled each semester. If you need to get a permission, this service is one way to do it. The other, of course, is to go directly to the copyright holder.</P>
<P>
<B>E<SMALL>LECTRONIC</SMALL> R<SMALL>ESERVE</SMALL> R<SMALL>OOMS</SMALL></B><BR>
AAP members are also talking with people in the library world who are creating "electronic reserve rooms." Scanning technology makes it possible to scan, store, and print on demand. AAP representatives are attending meetings hosted by the Association of Research Libraries and the National Association of College Stores to discuss this topic. We have talked individually with officials at various campuses about how they can create electronic reserve collections that will work for all players, recognizing copyright and supporting the educational needs.</P>
<P>
<B>X<SMALL>EROX'S</SMALL> G<SMALL>LYPH</SMALL></B><BR>
There's another new project that's just in the talking stage. I've received two phone calls from officials of the Xerox Corporation. They have developed something called the Glyph, which makes it possible to put all the necessary copyright information-who is the copyright holder, what is the fee for printing, what is the fee for scanning, whom do you contact, what is the address-in a tiny microscopic dot that can be embedded in a small line or border on a page. Thus the publisher can provide all the necessary information on the printed page. And the Glyph reader works just like the barcode scanner at a supermarket: when a page is put on a Xerox machine or any other copier that has such a reader, the copyright information can be tracked and recorded. Eventually, a billing and payment mechanism can be established. Obviously the technology is there, and Xerox would like to work with publishers on trying it out.</P>
<P>
<B>T<SMALL>HE</SMALL> R<SMALL>OLE OF THE</SMALL> M<SMALL>ARKETPLACE</SMALL></B><BR>
We are living in a very exciting transition period. We're watching technologies grow. We're trying different things. We're experimenting, and publishers want to work with all of the user communities to understand their needs and their wants and to consider the things publishers can develop to meet those needs. The publishing community is interested in working with users in doing experiments, pilot projects, and models so that  together we can envision a new environment. When Barbara Ringer spoke earlier about the project at the Library of Congress to create a database of copyright holders, it reminded me of a report the AAP received in February from the Japanese Ministry of International Trade and Industry, which has designed and was asking for worldwide comment on a global database of copyrighted works. It envisions a voluntary system. Everybody who holds copyright in animation, video, graphics, music, or text can voluntarily register with this Japanese database and set their own fees. And there are incentives to encourage registration. But the impetus behind the project is that the Japanese government wants everyone to have a central place to go to find out who holds copyrights. This morning you heard that the U.S. government is looking at this kind of project too, and what I've said to you today is that there are also projects in the private sector. There will be multiple avenues to support the needs of multimedia users and developers-the private sector will respond to the needs of the marketplace. <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>
<HR WIDTH="75%">
<P>
<B>Carol A. Risher</B> is vice president for copyright and new technology for the Association of American Publishers (AAP), in the Washington, D.C., office. She represents this country's publishing industry on the International Publishers Copyright Council and the U.S. State Department Advisory Committee on International Intellectual Property and is currently responsible for copyright enforcement efforts in ten countries and the United States. Risher has lectured at national and international meetings on copyright and new technology and has testified before Congress and executive branch agencies on new technology issues of concern to the publishing industry. In addition to her work at AAP, she served as executive director of the International Intellectual Property Alliance (1984-91), on the board of the National Information Standards Organization (1989-90), and on the Library of Congress Optical Disk Advisory Board (1986-91). She is also an instructor at the Howard University Press Book Publishing Institute.</P>

<HR>
