<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - Position Statement of the Association for Educational Communications and Technology</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Position Statement of the Association for Educational Communications and Technology</H2>
<P>
<I>By Hope Roland Botterbusch</I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>T</BIG></BIG>he Association for Educational Communications and Technology (AECT) is a leading international, professional association dedicated to the improvement of instruction through the utilization of media and technology. The Association provides a forum for the exchange of information among such professionals as audiovisual media specialists, library and information specialists, microcomputer specialists, educational administrators, researchers, teachers and professors, television producers and directors, and instructional technologists.</P>
<P>
The mission of AECT is to provide leadership in educational communications and technology by linking professionals holding a common interest in the use of educational technology and its application to the learning process.</P>
<P>
The charge of AECT's Copyright Committee is to keep members informed of current copyright issues, develop and review positions on copyright, develop and review copyright materials published by AECT, and monitor changes to the Copyright Law of 1976 and related legislation. This charge has been delegated to a committee comprised of K12, college, and university educators and scholars, all of whom hold some expertise in the area of copyright. All but one of these committee members offer informed opinions but do not dispense legal advice. The one committee member who is able to dispense legal advice regarding copyright is a renowned copyright attorney who is an integral part of these proceedings today.</P>
<P>
The Copyright Committee's newest and most exciting charge, and the reason I am here today, is to communicate AECT's position on educational fair access for the use of copyrighted works in multimedia programs produced by faculty and students for educational purposes.</P>
<P>
<B>P<SMALL>OSITION</SMALL> S<SMALL>TATEMENT ON</SMALL> F<SMALL>AIR</SMALL> A<SMALL>CCESS OF</SMALL> C<SMALL>OPYRIGHTED</SMALL> W<SMALL>ORKS IN</SMALL> M<SMALL>ULTIMEDIA</SMALL> P<SMALL>ROGRAMS</SMALL></B><BR>
First, AECT vigorously promotes the adherence to the Copyright Law of the United States of America contained in Title 17 of the United States Code and, in particular, to Section 107 Limitations on Exclusive Rights: Fair Use.</P>
<P>
Second, AECT has promulgated and subscribes to a code of ethics that is intended to aid its members individually and collectively in maintaining a high level of professional conduct. AECT's Code of Ethics includes a statement on copyright that reads:
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>In fulfilling obligations to the profession, members shall inform users of the stipulations and interpretations of the copyright law and other laws affecting the profession and encourage compliance.</I></BLOCKQUOTE></P>
<P>
Third, AECT recognizes that the standards of the House Subcommittee on Courts, Civil Liberties, and Administration of Justice Negotiating Committee-specifically, the "Fair-Use Guidelines for Off-Air Videotaping"-reflect the negotiating committee's consensus as to the application of fair use and carry the weight of law.</P>
<P>
In light of the three points above, AECT recommends adoption of a set of proposed criteria regarding fair access for the use of copyrighted works in multimedia programs produced by faculty and students for educational purposes.</P>

<BIG><BIG>Because of the unique nature of multimedia development, AECT recommends a review of the appropriateness of the '10/10 guidelines'.</BIG></BIG>
<P>
<B>R<SMALL>ECOMMENDED</SMALL> G<SMALL>UIDELINES</SMALL></B><BR>
The following criteria should be included in "The Fair-Use Guidelines for Multimedia Programs." The guidelines should
<OL TYPE="1">
<LI>encompass grades pre-school, K-12, vocational, college and university education;
<LI>be for the purpose of scholarship, research, criticism, comment, news reporting, teaching, or learning;
<LI>include student use to demonstrate competencies;
<LI>include faculty use for scholarly research and instruction;
<LI>provide for the use of out-of-print materials;
<LI>provide for the use of copyrighted materials when the copyright owner cannot be located from which to obtain permission;
<LI>define "fair use" in terms of the portion used in relation to the whole work; and,
most important
<LI> define <I>multimedia</I>.
</OL></P>
<P>
<B>T<SMALL>OPICS</SMALL> N<SMALL>EEDING</SMALL> D<SMALL>ISCUSSION</SMALL></B><BR>
First, a discussion of what constitutes multimedia is needed. The AECT Copyright Committee has developed a working definition of <I>multimedia</I> as material taken from various audio, visual, and textual mediums that is combined by means of an electronic device.</P>
<P>
Second, to define fair use, a discussion of what is commonly known as the "10/10 guideline" is in order. Reference to such a guideline may be found in the records of discussions of the Congressional Committees prior to the adoption of the Copyright Law of 1976. The "10/10 guideline" may be summarized to state that
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>ten percent of a work may be copied for educational purposes as long as that ten percent constitutes ten percent or less of the educator's or student's original finished work and that the ten percent copied is not the essence of the work.</I></BLOCKQUOTE>
Because of the unique nature of multimedia development, AECT recommends a review of the appropriateness of the "10/10 guidelines."</P>
<P>
Third, a discussion is in order for extending the meaning of the term <I>instructional setting</I> to the library media center because face-to-face instruction takes place there.</P>
<P>
Finally, AECT believes the fair-use guidelines currently in place should be used as a basis for developing fair-use guidelines for multimedia. Those guidelines that apply are found in the Copyright Law of the United States of America, Title 17 of the United States Code Section 107, "Limitations on Exclusive Rights: Fair Use," and Section 110, "Limitations on Exclusive Rights: Exemptions of Certain Performances and Displays."</P>
<P>
<B>C<SMALL>ONCLUSION</SMALL></B><BR>
AECT has members who individually hold copyrights to their creative works. In addition, AECT has members who desire, in an educational setting, to utilize copyrighted works for valid instructional and educational purposes. Thus we strive to maintain a balanced perspective as to the extent and limitations of fair use. We sincerely feel that there is a need to provide fair-use access to copyrighted materials to be used in multimedia programs in an educational setting, while protecting the intellectual property rights of the authors.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>AECT believes the fair-use guidelines currently in place should be used as a basis for developing fair-use guidelines for multimedia.</BIG></BIG></P>

<H3>AECT C<SMALL>ODE OF</SMALL> E<SMALL>THICS</SMALL></H3>
<P>
<I>Preamble</I>
<OL TYPE="1">
<LI>The Code of Ethics contained herein shall be considered to be principles of ethics. These principles are intended to aid members individually and collectively in maintaining a high level of professional conduct.
<LI>The Professional Ethics Committee will build documentation of opinion (interpretive briefs or ramifications of intent) relating to specific ethical statements enumerated herein.
<LI>Opinions may be generated in response to specific cases brought before the Professional Ethics Committee.
<LI>Amplification and/or clarification of the ethical principles may be generated by the Committee in response to a request submitted by a member.
</OL></P>
<P>
<I>Section 1-Commitment to the Individual</I></P>
<P>
In fulfilling obligations to the individual, the members:
<OL TYPE="1">
<LI>Shall encourage independent action in an individual's pursuit of learning and shall provide access to varying points of view.
<LI>Shall protect the individual rights of access to materials of varying points of view.
<LI>Shall guarantee to each individual the opportunity to participate in any appropriate program.
<LI>Shall conduct professional business so as to protect the privacy and maintain the personal integrity of the individual.
<LI>Shall follow sound professional procedures for evaluation and selection of materials and equipment.
<LI>Shall make reasonable effort to protect the individual from conditions harmful to health and safety.
<LI>Shall promote current and sound professional practices in the use of technology in education.
<LI>Shall in the design and selection of any educational program or media seek to avoid content that reinforces or promotes gender, ethnic, racial, or religious stereotypes. Shall seek to encourage the development of programs and media that emphasize the diversity of our society as a multicultural community.
</OL></P>
<P>
Section 2-Commitment to Society</P>
<P>
In fulfilling obligations to society, the member:
<OL TYPE="1">
<LI>Shall honestly represent the institution or organization with which that person is affiliated, and shall take adequate precautions to distinguish between personal and institutional or organizational views.
<LI>Shall represent accurately and truthfully the facts concerning educational matters in direct and indirect public expressions.
<LI>Shall not use institutional or Associational privileges for private gain.
<LI>Shall accept no gratuities, gifts, or favors that might impair or appear to impair professional judgment, or offer any favor, service, or thing of value to obtain special advantage.
<LI>Shall engage in fair and equitable practices with those rendering service to the profession.
</OL></P>
<P>
Section 3-Commitment to the Profession</P>
<P>
In fulfilling obligations to the profession, the member:
<OL TYPE="1">
<LI>Shall accord just and equitable treatment to all members of the profession in terms of professional rights and responsibilities.
<LI>Shall not use coercive means to promise special treatment in order to influence professional decisions of colleagues.
<LI>Shall avoid commercial exploitation of that person's membership in the Association.
<LI>Shall strive continually to improve professional knowledge and skill and to make available to patrons and colleagues the benefit of that person's professional attainments.
<LI>Shall present honestly personal professional qualifications and the professional qualifications and evaluations of colleagues.
<LI>Shall conduct professional business through proper channels.
<LI>Shall delegate assigned tasks only to qualified personnel. Qualified personnel are those who have appropriate training or credentials and/or who can demonstrate competency in performing the task.
<LI>Shall inform users of the stipulations and interpretations of the copyright law and other laws affecting the profession and encourage compliance.
<LI>Shall observe all laws relating to or affecting the profession; shall report, without hesitation, illegal or unethical conduct of fellow members of the profession to the AECT Professional Ethics Committee; shall participate in professional inquiry when requested by the Association.  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></OL></P>
<HR WIDTH="75%">
<P>
An educational copyright specialist who earned her master of science degree in library science from Wayne State University, <B>Hope Roland Botterbusch</B> is the executive director of Manatee Educational Television in Bradenton, Florida. Previously, Botterbusch was the district copyright contact for the School Board of Pinellas County in Clearwater, where she wrote the county's district copyright guidelines. She has been the chairperson of the Copyright Committee of the Association for Educational Communications and Technology since 1990, having served on the committee since 1988. Botterbusch's career spans twenty years, during which she has been a school library media specialist, a classroom teacher, a district audiovisual and instructional television supervisor, a corporate trainer, an adjunct university professor, and an educational consultant. She is coordinator of the column "Copyright and You" in Tech Trends magazine and a frequent speaker at local and national professional conferences. Botterbusch has numerous educational honors, the most recent being the 1994 Industry-Education Utilization Award from the National Association for Industry-Education Cooperation.</P>

<HR>
