<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - Multimedia Development and Copyright Issues in the Maricopa Community Colleges</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Multimedia Development and Copyright Issues in the Maricopa Community Colleges</H2>
<P>
<I>By Mary Lou Mosley</I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>T</BIG></BIG>he Maricopa County Community College District (MCCCD) in Phoenix, Arizona, consists of ten community colleges and centers and serves approximately 90,000 students. MCCCD has been a leader among community colleges in the integration of technology into instruction, including providing many computer labs for students, giving every faculty member an office computer and software, supporting faculty development of instructional materials that supplement classroom instruction, and exploring new technologies and new types of classrooms. MCCCD is also an active member of the League for Innovation in the Community Colleges, and several of our colleges have active partnerships with computer companies. Glendale Community College is an IBM demonstration center for multimedia instructional development and Paradise Valley Community College focuses on multimedia instructional development for Apple as a member of the Apple Community College Alliance.</P>
<P>
Community college students represent a variety of needs, experiences, and learning styles. They range in age from 17 to 80-plus, with many of them falling into the category of adults returning to education. They attend school for a variety of reasons, including the intent to transfer to a four-year institution, to update or improve job-related skills, to obtain retraining, to develop skills in order to get a job, and to enhance personal growth and interests. Many of them bring work and life experiences with them that need to be taken into account when teaching. Finally, many community college students learn in different ways, with different learning styles, than the student who graduates from high school and goes directly to college. Our instructional materials must address the needs and motivations of the adult learners who do better if they can control the pace of their learning, interact, respond, and get information in ways that are alternatives to the traditional lecture. For these reasons, multimedia and computer-based instructional materials are very successful with the community college student.</P>
<P>
<B>D<SMALL>EVELOPMENT OF</SMALL> M<SMALL>ULTIMEDIA</SMALL> I<SMALL>NSTRUCTION</SMALL></B><BR>
MCCCD faculty members have been very active in developing alternative methods of instruction that rely on various technologies, such as computers, video, distance learning, audio and video conferencing, and multimedia. The computer-based materials have been developed on Macintosh, NeXt, DOS, and VAX platforms. These materials are designed for multiple uses, including classroom presentation, review and reinforcement of instruction, exploration beyond the classroom, and independent learning. In addition to classrooms, students use these materials in computer labs and content-specific labs such as biology, chemistry, math, and English; in learning centers; and in libraries and the Information Commons. In some cases, students take the materials home. Although the faculty members often develop the materials to use with their own students only, colleagues soon ask if they also can use the materials with their classes.</P>
<P>
The faculty-developed instructional multimedia materials range from simple one-concept or one-skill stacks to complex modules that include detailed color illustrations, still photographs, video, music, and interaction with other resources or media. Many multimedia modules are being created that access videodiscs or CD-ROMs and incorporate QuickTime clips. Music or sound is another key aspect of the modules. The modules are created in a variety of authoring programs and languages including HyperCard, SuperCard, ToolBook, Director, Authorware, Course Builder, and many others. Students also are developing multimedia materials for class projects, and faculty are using commercial multimedia instructional programs, such as the ABC News Interactive series, <I>BioSci II</I>, or Mozart's <I>Magic Flute</I>.</P>
<P>
Several of the colleges are producing their own videodiscs and CDs based on video they have shot themselves because of the lack of clear guidelines and the complexity of the process for getting permission for using commercial clips. Faculty members also are relying on royalty-free music clips or on colleagues to compose and play music for their instructional modules. Others are drawing their own pictures and graphics, pixel by pixel, since finding the copyright owner is so difficult. Yet the question still arises whether they are actually copying or making a derivative work when they create their illustrations and pictures for their programs.</P>
<P>
<B>C<SMALL>OPYRIGHT</SMALL> I<SMALL>SSUES AND</SMALL> C<SMALL>ONCERNS</SMALL></B><BR>
As faculty members have developed multimedia materials, they have raised issues and concerns about copyright, in terms of both what they want to incorporate in their materials and the protection they have after developing them. Many of their concerns about using parts of others' copyrighted work are the same as those being addressed at this conference. A number of other situations and questions about faculty developers' rights and responsibilities have arisen as they become more involved in developing multimedia instructional modules. Some examples include
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>creating a QuickTime clip from a small segment of a videodisc
<LI>scanning in a photograph of the "Mona Lisa" to use in a HyperCard stack
<LI>using popular music as introductory background by accessing the CD
<LI>typing the dialog from a videodisc so that students can read while the videodisc is playing
<LI>drawing graphics and pictures in a paint program that are based on a textbook illustration but are common knowledge
<LI>changing a scanned/digitized copyrighted image to meet their own needs
<LI>digitizing a speech recorded off TV to include in a module
<LI>adapting others' multimedia programs to fit their own situation
<LI>demonstrating a multimedia module at workshops and conferences and sharing it with colleagues at the home college or at other colleges
<LI> deciding where to give credit for using another person's work, as in a clip in a videodisc or CD that they are developing.
</UL></P>
<P>
Our faculty members are willing to ask for permission to use others' work and to pay royalties, but they have had great difficulties accomplishing that. For example, an anthropology instructor has developed multimedia materials that would be enhanced if he could use several illustrations from a book. When he contacted the publisher, he was told that no one really knew who owned the copyright to the illustrations, so no one could help him. In another case, a faculty member wanted to use some music clips and contacted ASCAP, which gave him incorrect and misleading information. A member of the psychology department wanted to use some video clips from a series that the college owned and was given verbal permission to do so. When she put her request for permission in writing, however, she was told that written permission would not be granted.</P>
<P>
Faculty members want clear guidelines and answers to questions so they can develop instructional materials to use with their students and still adhere to the Copyright Law. Essentially, our faculty is asking for the following actions:
<OL TYPE="1">
<LI>Development of guidelines for using parts of others' work, whether print, audio, video, still images, graphics, or scripts, in instructional multimedia materials that they are developing to use with their students. The guidelines should also address-or a process should be established-that will enable faculty members to share these materials with colleagues who want to use them with their students.
<LI>Expansion of the definition of face-to-face teaching to include labs, networks, libraries, learning centers, and so forth, because much of the teaching and learning in community colleges, especially with multimedia materials, occurs outside traditional classrooms. The key factor should be that the materials are in support of instruction, not where or how they are used.
<LI>Establishment of a clearinghouse for getting permission and paying royalties to use parts of others' work in their own multimedia instructional materials.
</OL></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>Multimedia development and such new technologies as scanners and digitizers are not covered in any of the copyright materials, the guidelines, or the law.</BIG></BIG></P>
<P>
Our faculty members are very frustrated because they do not have a clear or easy way to get permission or pay royalties to use nonprint materials. They are driven by their desire to help students learn, and developing multimedia instructional materials is one very important and successful method at the community college level for improving the teaching and learning process. Thus our teachers feel that they have only two viable options: violating the letter of the law or not using the materials. In both cases, the creator of the original material is injured. Establishing guidelines for fair use, a process for getting permission, and a clearinghouse will help the creator, the teacher developing materials, and, most important, the students.</P>
<P>
Much confusion and uncertainty about what faculty can and cannot do will be eliminated by establishing guidelines. We have heard conflicting opinions from attorneys who specialize in copyright and educational institutions. For example, during a recent teleconference, three attorneys said that the Kastenmeier guidelines for off-air taping were more restrictive than the actual Copyright Law and did not need to be followed by faculty members. Publishers and producers tell us unofficially that we can use parts of their materials in our multimedia modules because we are an educational institution, but they will not give us written permission.</P>
<P>
Faculty members are willing to follow guidelines and get permission to use others' work if a process is established. Getting permission to use parts of print materials through a clearinghouse, through our campus bookstore, and through specialized publishers has greatly changed the way our teachers view copyright. No longer do they see it as an impediment to their teaching. Our teaching professionals are looking for a similar process or clearinghouse that will enable them to develop multimedia materials in accordance with the Copyright Law.</P>
<P>
<B>MCCCD I<SMALL>NTELLECTUAL</SMALL> R<SMALL>IGHTS</SMALL> C<SMALL>OMMITTEE</SMALL></B><BR>
Three years ago, MCCCD established a committee to look at intellectual rights, in terms of both how we are using and developing instructional materials and how our faculty developers can protect their own materials. The committee consisted of our legal counsel, an instructional administrator, and faculty developers. The MCCCD Governing Board had passed a policy requiring employees to adhere to the Copyright Law. However, no guidelines or training had been developed to help employees understand their rights and responsibilities under the law.</P>
<P>
The Intellectual Rights Committee reviewed a number of materials on copyright, both print and video, to find information we could give faculty and staff. We were concerned because the materials were negative in approach and tone, emphasizing what could not be done. We wanted to be positive so that faculty would be willing to comply with the Copyright Law. We also were frustrated because the materials dealt with print and video, but had little or no information or guidelines for the newer technologies, such as multimedia and distance learning.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>Establishing guidelines for fair use, a process for getting permission, and a clearinghouse will help the creator, the teacher developing materials, and, most important, the students.</BIG></BIG></P>
<P>
As a result of our decision to take the positive approach about the rights faculty had under the Copyright Law, we had to develop our own videotape. The emphasis was on what could be done legally under the law and how to get permission to use copyrighted work. The videotape covers print, off-air broadcasts, and computer software. The narrator is a member of the faculty talking to other members about successes in legally using copyrighted materials. Every college in the district has a copy of the videotape and supporting materials. We also put guidelines, information about getting permission, and MCCCD copyright policies on a computer file server that could be accessed by anyone in MCCCD.</P>
<P>
At the same time that we were creating the videotape, significant changes were taking place in the area of print materials. Our college bookstore company, Follett, was offering to put together anthologies of articles for faculty, including the service of getting permission from copyright owners. The bookstore then would sell the anthologies to students. Several book publishers were willing to offer a similar service to faculty. No longer do faculty members have to make their own copies of articles, essays, short stories, and so forth-often without permission. Getting permission also is becoming easier for print materials. Many publishers have departments and procedures set up to handle requests and are more willing to grant permission. A similar change in ease of getting permission or paying royalties has occurred with using videos in the library and on videoconferencing networks.</P>
<P>
Multimedia development and such new technologies as scanners and digitizers, however, are not covered in any of the copyright materials, the guidelines, or the law. We surveyed members of our faculty about their concerns as developers, and we consistently heard pleas for guidelines, a procedure for requesting permission and paying royalties that would be successful, and a clearinghouse for handling requests, much like what is available for print materials. The Intellectual Rights Committee invited Ivan Bender to work with us and our faculty for two days this spring to provide more information about copyright and multimedia development as well as to identify gray areas. We also wanted to demonstrate what we are doing at the community college level and how our teaching methods, facilities, and student needs may differ from those at a four-year university. Bringing the community college experiences and concerns to this task force should strengthen the results.  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>
<HR WIDTH="75%">
<P>
As associate dean of instruction at Paradise Valley Community College in the Maricopa County Community College District (MCCCD) in Phoenix, Arizona, <B>Mary Lou Mosley</B> has responsibility for the coordination of summer school, MCCCD's videoconferencing network classes, and the Apple Community College Alliance project. She also manages the Macintosh computer labs and teaches computer skills to students and supports faculty doing multimedia development work on the Macintosh. Under her direction, the district developed an ESL software project and a multimedia demonstration center for faculty. Mosley has worked with MCCCD's Intellectual Rights Committee, serving as its chairperson for two years. She holds both a bachelor of arts in history and a master of arts in library media from the University of Colorado as well as a Ph.D. in educational technology from Arizona State University. Since 1978, she has been a librarian, a high school library media specialist, and an instructional designer.</P>

<HR>
