<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - New Media Centers Program</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>New Media Centers Program:<BR>
Forum for Research and Development of Multimedia Technologies in Education</H2>
<P>
<I>By Kevin J. Howat</I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>H</BIG></BIG>eadquartered in San Francisco, New Media Centers (NMC) is a not-for-profit organization that helps create model learning centers in institutions of higher education worldwide. The program helps educators better understand, utilize, and integrate digital technology into their classrooms and surrounding communities.</P>
<P>
New media offer educators innumerable opportunities for exploration and innovation; they also pose many challenges. New Media Centers helps educators meet those challenges by acting as a clearinghouse for faculty and students to exchange ideas and know-how with industry experts on topics ranging from optimal system configurations to curriculum development. The program also coordinates collaborative projects between centers and a broad range of interested parties, including technology industry leaders, publishers, creative professionals, multimedia developers, legal experts, legislators, government regulators, and nongovernmental organizations. Through outreach programs, centers provide training and workshops on new media for such community members as K-12 teachers and local business executives. To ensure that each center is equipped with state-of-the-art tools and equipment, the program's technology members offer the centers advantageous pricing on complete hardware and software configurations for professional-quality new-media development. The goal of the program is to create 100 New Media Centers worldwide by 1996.</P>
<P>
New Media Centers' broad-based constituency forms the foremost body of expertise on ground-breaking technical, developmental, social, and ethical issues surrounding new media today. As the world continues its transition from a manufacturing-based to an information-based economy, the program will play an increasingly critical role in developing innovative ways that digital technology can create new educational and economic opportunities.</P>
<P>
<B>B<SMALL>ACKGROUND</SMALL></B><BR>
In early 1993, a group of technology companies formed a consortium to explore new ways of fostering use of interactive media in education. The goal was to find approaches that could prosper even in times of economic uncertainty, maintain currency in the face of rapid technological change, and extend the benefits of interactive media to a far broader audience.</P>
<P>
The result was the formation of the New Media Centers program. Based on a long-term partnership among a group of key industry players and a diverse group of colleges and universities, this program is dedicated to providing access to state-of-the-art new media technologies not only to faculty, staff, and students at the host institutions but also to the business, creative, and educational communities they serve. The founding companies include Adobe Systems Incorporated, Apple Computer, Inc., FWB Inc., Macromedia, Prentice-Hall, Sony, and SuperMac Technology, Inc. Since inception, Kodak and Clement Mok Designs have joined the program as corporate sponsors.</P>
<P>
A request for proposals for the program was announced at the 1993 EDUCOM conference in Cincinnati. Executives from the sponsoring companies addressed an audience of over 200 representatives from the press and academic communities. They were joined by Senator J. Robert Kerrey of Nebraska, sponsor of the Electronic Libraries Act of 1993, the goals of which are synergistic with those of the New Media Centers program.</P>
<P>
Clearly the program tapped into a strong vein of interest on campuses across the continent. The New Media Centers office received over 700 requests for the request for proposals package. Over 140 institutions submitted detailed proposals that included major financial and other resource commitments for the 15 sites planned for the first year of the program. Based on this overwhelming response, the consortium's board expanded the number of sites to be created in the first year of the program to 22.</P>
<P>
The schools selected to host the initial set of New Media Centers include Stanford University, California Polytechnic at Pomona, California State University at Long Beach, Georgia Institute of Technology, University of Hawaii at Manoa, Lewis-Clark State College, University of Michigan, University of Minnesota, University of Nebraska, Princeton University, University of New Mexico, Cornell University, Hostos Community College of the City University of New York system, New York University, Elizabeth City State University, Ohio State University, Pennsylvania State University, Houston Community College, Bennington College, Virginia Tech, University of Wisconsin, and University of Calgary.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>Students can gain new insights into their academic studies from new-media course materials. Through hands-on experience with professional tools, they can master skills that can be hard to acquire in traditional academic settings but that can be vital in the job market.</BIG></BIG></P>
<P>
<B>Partnership Between Industry and Academe</B><BR>
The program is unique, requiring mutual commitments from both corporate and academic partners. The requirements for the corporate partners include
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>guaranteeing extended, preferential pricing for an entire complementary range of media-related hardware and software, as well as for upgrades;
<LI>establishing a close working relationship between industry and academic partners, including a two-way exchange of support, information, and resources;
<LI>providing New Media Center sites access to the consortium's industry contacts, technology developments, and emerging new media solutions;
<LI>involving the New Media Centers in the advance testing and use of prototype new media products;
<LI>steering debate over practical ways to deal with intellectual property issues, distribution, and royalties in the context of new media;
<LI>sharing expertise in the process of turning prototypes developed at New Media Centers into viable products for the academic or commercial marketplace;
<LI>financing the introduction of the program; and
<LI>communicating New Media Centers achievements to other academic institutions, to the technology and publishing communities, and to the business world.
</UL>
For participating educational institutions, the requirements of the program include
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>allocation of financial resources, a facility, and staffing to create, equip, and maintain the center;
<LI>a commitment to train faculty and students, introduce interactive media into a range of academic disciplines, and develop media-based curriculum materials;
<LI>opening New Media Centers to community access, via workshops and seminars on using interactive media for alumni, business professionals, K-12 teachers, parents, and others; and
<LI>showcasing new-media technologies developed by the corporate partners in the New Media Centers program.
</UL></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>Intrigued by the educational benefits and economic potential of multimedia, many leading publishing houses have begun to extend the reach of their product lines by adding new-media enhancement to their textbooks.</BIG></BIG></P>
<P>
<B>D<SMALL>IFFERENCES</SMALL> B<SMALL>ETWEEN</SMALL> NMC <SMALL>AND</SMALL> E<SMALL>XISTING</SMALL> I<SMALL>NITIATIVES</SMALL></B><BR>
Compared with the ad hoc undertakings that typify many of the first-generation multimedia ventures on campuses, the New Media Centers program represents an effective model for deploying new-media technologies in education. The New Media Centers initiative differs on several counts.
<OL TYPE=DISC>
<LI><I>Practical and stable economic model.</I> Because they don't rely on donations, seed programs, or one-time grants, the New Media Centers are less subject to the vagaries of corporate largesse. Participating universities have financial responsibility for their New Media Centers. But in exchange, each center has a unique guarantee: deep, long-term preferential pricing from a group of companies that together offer complete solutions for interactive media technologies.</P>
<P>
There are several benefits to this strategy for participating educational institutions. First, it provides the best possible pricing on the products that are essential for professional quality work in multimedia. Second, it greatly simplifies purchasing negotiations. Third, because the preferential pricing guarantee extends over time, universities can more readily afford to upgrade their media technology and keep their New Media Centers on the leading edge. As a result, universities can build a more complete base for interactive media computing (in contrast to the piecemeal assemblages of equipment and endless purchase-price negotiations) more economically and more conveniently than before.</P>
<P>
Other aspects of the New Media Centers program hold promise as revenue producers for participating universities. Workshops and seminars for nonuniversity audiences could generate a return on the initial investment. And new-media-based curriculum materials, created by faculty and students and disseminated to other campuses or in the commercial marketplace, could produce a stream of royalties.</P>

<LI><P><I>Powerful?  model for integrating interactive media into academia.</I> While there are pockets of achievement, interactive media have not made sweeping inroads on most campuses. Few schools offer degree programs in multimedia applications, interactive telecommunications, and the like. Only a handful of academic disciplines use interactive media in teaching. Many faculty, staff members, and students are not aware of what they can do with interactive media. Many find that the facilities for using them are still relatively inaccessible or incomplete.</P>
<P>
The underlying economics of the program plays an important role in making new media available to academic endeavor. The financial commitment by universities and the preferential pricing by vendors make inviting, well-equipped facilities practical for the first time.</P>
<P>
The New Media Centers are inclusive in scope, another departure from many existing multimedia projects. By charter, they serve the varied interests of the whole academic community, not just a few departments. Conceivably, professors and students of forensic anthropology, journalism, linguistics, business management, constitutional law, and other disciplines can all use the centers to learn new-media technologies and use them to enhance the curriculum for their own academic fields.</P>
<P>
Each participating campus is free to interpret the overall training and support goals of the program in its own way. Some might focus on basic skills for working with interactive media: searching multimedia databases, combining different data types, and annotating them to compose something new-a new kind of term paper or scholarly article, dynamic course materials, and the like. On a more conceptual level, some might explore issues in repurposing content from one medium to another, in terms of legal constraints or instructional design. Others might teach particular software packages or specific techniques for interactive presentations, graphic design, desktop publishing, or desktop video production.</P>
<P>
For faculty, the New Media Centers program provides abundant resources for acquiring the skills of interactive media plus the collaborative assistance needed to integrate new media into their teaching. Students also benefit in several ways. They can gain new insights into their academic studies from new-media course materials. Through hands-on experience with professional tools, they can master skills beyond those associated with specific disciplines, skills that can be hard to acquire in traditional academic settings but that can be vital in the job market.</P>

<LI><P><I>Effective model for extending the benefits of new media beyond the campus.</I> The centers are an ideal resource not only for matriculated students, faculty, and staff but also for nonacademic "students"-from artists and business professionals to alumni and publishers. According to <I>Digital Media</I> (September 20, 1993), "The growing need for focused education in multimedia technologies transcends the university setting; professionals in the industry [need] a chance to brush up in a specific technology area or forge new relationships with others who share their interests." By leveraging their investment in new-media technology and the relationships they forge with industry partners in the NMC consortium, the New Media Centers are well positioned to serve the needs of this broad community.</P>
<P>
Extension programs could offer workshops for business executives who want a basic introduction to the techniques of interactive multimedia for presentations or corporate training programs. They could also offer seminars on the impact of new media in publishing, telecommunications, or entertainment and hands-on classes on various multimedia tools. These activities not only could communicate the value of new media to a broader audience but also could generate an income that would help the New Media Centers be self-sustaining.</P>
<P>
The New Media Centers can also serve to link participating universities and their media-based endeavors with the large, active community of developers who have been attracted to interactive media. This connection could prove useful to both universities and developers. For instance, developers may be helpful in suggesting creative ways of resolving technical challenges that the New Media Centers may encounter and offer their talents as teaching resources. In addition, the centers could host developers through artist-in-residence programs and provide venues for beta testing their prerelease software and hardware, which would provide the technology partners with a larger pool of solid, quality-assurance resources.</P>

<LI><P><I>"Laboratory" for new approaches to creating and disseminating media-based publications.</I> As print becomes just one of many media used to teach and learn, the textbook publishing industry is in the throes of change. Intrigued by the educational benefits and economic potential of multimedia, many leading publishing houses have begun to extend the reach of their product lines by adding new-media enhancement to their textbooks. Some have begun to distribute traditional textbooks electronically to campus bookstores for on-demand printing. Others offer custom publishing services to professors, creating tailor-made anthologies consisting of excerpts and graphical material selected from the texts they publish. Still others provide software tools with their texts so educators can create study aids and presentation materials that dovetail with assigned textbooks.</P>
<P>
The New Media Centers offer a proving ground for even more fundamental changes. Program members-be they scholars, authors, editors, publishers, librarians, distributors at campus bookstores or copy shops, software developers, or hardware vendors- have a congenial forum to develop and refine approaches to multimedia production, publication, and distribution. Consortium members hope a broad range of publishers will look to New Media Centers as laboratories where, together with educators, they can work to forge guidelines on such crucial matters as
<UL TYPE=DISC>
<LI>repurposing existing content for deployment in different media;
<LI>pricing and distribution of new-media productions through new channels and developing new methods of tracking these transactions;
<LI>extending copyright protection to electronically distributed multimedia; and
<LI>marketing university-created new-media products.
</UL></P>
<P>
As <I>Digital Media</I> observed, "It is only in understanding all the dimensions of distribution, production, and funding across all the industries touched by multimedia that we will move successfully into the new world. . .this technology will create."  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>
</OL>
<HR WIDTH="75%">
<P>
<B>Kevin J. Howat</B> is director of strategic relations and marketing programs at Macromedia, the leading independent software company supplying products and services to multimedia developers, publishers, and enthusiasts. Howat directs Macromedia's business development efforts, establishing and managing strategic alliances. He also heads the company's new Multimedia Source & Center programs group, which provides professional services and support to Macromedia's customers and industry partners. Before entering the computer industry, Howat spent thirteen years in publishing with Wadsworth and Addison-Wesley in a variety of positions, including sales, acquisitions, and editorial management. While there, he acquired rights to over 75 new properties, establishing many best-selling titles in key markets. His first foray into the software business was with The Learning Company, where he designed and managed the development of educational software products for children, including "OutNumbered!" the 1990 recipient of the Software Publishers Association's Elementary Education Award. Howat holds a bachelor's degree from Franklin and Marshall College, where he graduated cum laude with honors in literature.</P>

<HR>
