<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - Committee on the Quantity and Sources of Excerpted Materials</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Committee on the Quantity and Sources of Excerpted Materials</H2>
<P>
<I>Report by Jan Sichel</I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>T</BIG></BIG>he committee comprised sixteen participants. Five represented trade interests: the Association of American Publishers, the Picture Agency Council of America, a music company, the Goals of America and Artists' Rights Foundation, and the Global Village Schools Initiative. Five represented professional associations: the National Association of Secondary Schools, the Association for Supervision and Curriculum Development, the National Council of Teachers of Mathematics, the Association of American Colleges and Universities, and the Association of Educational Communication and Technology (AECT). Six were media directors and specialists representing various universities. The group lacked representatives of software publishers, the telecommunications industry, and students.</P>
<P>
The committee first discussed abuses of copyrighted materials, particularly by students who seem to have the idea that anything in the commercial world is accessible to them to take and use as they choose. Clearer and more definitive guidelines might help librarians, media specialists, teachers, and administrators provide a better model of correct use. The members emphasized the ethical importance of having faculty members model respect for law, regulation, and fair use.</P>
<P>
Participants pointed out that the international community is guilty of greater abuses against American copyright than are academics. Ignorance of fair-use criteria is probably a greater cause of abuse than real intent to flout regulations. In some cases, observance of fair use of copyrighted materials may conflict with freedom of speech.</P>
<P>
The committee spent considerable time trying to define the term <I>multimedia</I>, finally arriving at the following working definition:
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>Multimedia is a work that combines audio, text, and/or visual materials by means of a computer or similar device.</I></BLOCKQUOTE></P>
<P>
Members of the committee from the academic community differed with those from industry and professional organizations. Some agreed with AECT's recommendation to apply the current print guidelines' ten percent rule with the additional limitation that the resulting work may contain no more than ten percent of such excerpted audio and visual material. Others argued for a fifty percent rule in which fifty percent of a work could be made up of a combination of excerpts, as long as each excerpt was no more than ten percent of an original work.</P>
<P>
Trade associations, particularly the Picture Agency Council of America, suggested the possibility of site licenses for still photographs in which universities could take responsibility for a licensing process.</P>
<P>
A representative of the Association of American Publishers said the group might be willing to pursue pilot projects in developing materials.</P>
<P>
Although the committee concluded in some frustration at being unable to reach any closure in the short time available, members felt that if they continued to work together, eventually it would be possible to write fair-use guidelines that would be acceptable to everyone.  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>
<P>
<B>Jan Sichel</B> is President of the Consortium of College and University Media Centers.</P>

<HR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/LLivingston.htm">Next Article</A></P>
