<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - Committee on the Presentation, Utilization, and Duplication of Copyrighted Materials</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Committee on the Presentation, Utilization, and Duplication of Copyrighted Materials</H2>
<P>
<I>Report by Lisa Livingston</I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>T</BIG></BIG>he committee comprised several people from the educational community, media managers, instructional technology people, and computer people. Proprietary interests were also present. The committee decided that digitalization was the key to <I>multimedia</I>, defining the term as follows:
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>Multimedia is a medium or any combination of media that is or are driven, accessed, or manipulated by a computer.</I></BLOCKQUOTE></P>
<P>
Members argued that while electronic technology is central to multimedia today, future means of communication are likely to be portable, and multimedia may move into nonelectronic technologies.</P>
<P>
The committee discussed the issue of fair-use environments for the presentation of copyrighted multimedia materials. The members reviewed common learning environments that extend the concept of "face-to-face instruction." Self-paced learning programs, networks involving one or more academic institutions, and learning at home all create difficulties for fair-use regulation and possible threats to the profits of the proprietors.</P>
<P>
Spontaneity is important in the student's navigation through a multimedia program, whether it's on a network or whether it is an individual unit. Spontaneity is also important for the student developing a digital term paper, for example, or doing a digital assignment at home.</P>
<P>
The committee concurred that the definition of the term <I>learning environment</I> needed to be expanded.</P>
<P>
In considering issues of utilization, the committee members again discussed self education and home uses of materials. One issue is the distinction between education and entertainment. In a film class, for example, a teacher or student might have reasons to put together a multimedia presentation with clips of many films in them, but films are highly protected and producers demand that their profits be protected. The committee felt that there may be a significant difference between students developing a multimedia production that includes film clips and teachers doing the same thing. All agreed that if a faculty member developed some sort of media production and then tried to sell it, use rights had to be arranged. Many participants thought, however, that faculty members who spent a lot of time developing multimedia presentations for their own classes should be able to use film clips and that they should be able to incorporate some of these clips in their own term "papers" as well. It was suggested that it might be possible for limited-use rights to be acquired by an educational institution that would extend to such teacher and student uses.</P>
<P>
Duplication is an issue closely related to utilization. Committee members debated the effects of having one media presentation used again and again for some kind of campus multimedia teaching program. Vendors were concerned about loss of profits, if duplication of such frequently used programs were permitted. It was suggested that some academic uses required multiple copies of materials. Vendors might find it profitable to make an arrangement with academic institutions to provide for these uses.</P>
<P>
The committee concluded its deliberations by discussing the rapidly changing marketplace and by emphasizing the importance of vendors and users working together to find a way of meeting their respective needs.</P>
<P>
Further discussion dealt with the difficulty of obtaining copyright release, or of even tracking down the copyright holder. The concept of <I>intellectual value</I> as something separate from monetary value came up. There was debate about the need for a clearinghouse as a way to provide convenient access to copyrighted material but also to get players to work together.</P>
<P>
One committee member suggested that there be something created called an <I>educational domain</I>, which is somewhere in between public domain and public performance. Another member suggested the need for a "school/home site license" for institutions where students may need to take mulltimedia materials home for study.  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B>Lisa Livingston</B> is Chairperson of the Copyright Task Force of the Consortium of College and University Media Centers.</P>

<HR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/CRace.htm">Next Article</A></P>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/">Back to Table of Contents</A></P>
