<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - Committee on the Retention, Access, and Storage of Multimedia Materials</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2>Committee on the Retention, Access, and Storage of Multimedia Materials</H2>
<P>
<I>Report by Carol A. Race</I></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>T</BIG></BIG>he committee comprised nine people, including three producers, two media directors, a few academics, and a representative of computer services. The committee adopted the definition of the term multimedia of the New Media Centers, which reads as follows:
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>Multimedia is a strategy for fostering interactive media through fusion of technologies and solutions for uniting text, illustrations, photographs, sound, voice, animations, and video in a dynamic new form.</I></BLOCKQUOTE></P>
<P>
Members felt that interactivity was the key characteristic of multimedia.</P>
<P>
Members first discussed the issue of retention. They agreed that short-term retention is covered by fair-use guidelines and that even long-term retention is usually permitted as long as it causes no economic loss to the copyright holder.</P>
<P>
Participants pointed out the need to attach credits citing the copyright holder to all multimedia materials in such a way that they would be embedded in any fragments or parts of a work that were included in another work. It was suggested that evolving technologies may soon solve this problem.</P>
<P>
As far as access is concerned, committee members agreed that the current fair-use guidelines cover most instances where access is desirable, as long as such access does not cause economic harm to the copyright holder. There was a need for an exemption to cover presentation of a product developed by a member of the faculty at conferences of education professionals.</P>
<P>
Committee members representing higher education argued against an arbitrary numerical quantification of amounts of material excerpted from copyrighted materials or forming part of a teacher- or student-created work. Representatives from the K-12 teaching environment, however, argued that guidelines such as the "10/10 percent" upheld by the AECT were necessary.</P>
<P>
Rosemary Talab, from AECT, called attention to a 1992 publication of the Office of Technology Assessment (OTA) called <I>Finding a Balance: Computer Software, Intellectual Property, and the Challenge of Technological Change.</I> (She was a reviewer and had contributed to a section that dealt with mixed media.) She called for a new OTA report on the issues discussed at the present conference and said there is particularly a need for investigation and report on digitized media.</P>
<P>
Conference chairperson, Ivan Bender, announced that the sponsors of the conference intend to present the recommendations of the conference participants to such primary government agencies as the Patent and Trademark Office and the Copyright Office.  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B>Carol A. Race</B> is a member of the Copyright Task Force of the Consortium of College and University Media Centers.</P>

<HR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/IBender.htm">Next Article</A></P>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="/technos/proceed/">Back to Table of Contents</A></P>
<HR>
<A HREF="/ait/aitcopy.htm">&copy; AIT </A>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
</HTML>
