<DOCHDR>
http://www.ait.org:80/technos/proceed/IBender.htm 206.106.95.11 19970113045028 text/html 32153
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Mon, 13 Jan 1997 05:46:01 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
Last-Modified: Fri, 14 Jun 1996 20:58:20 GMT
Content-Length: 31952
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>What's Fair - General Discussion</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A HREF="/technos/atechnos.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/technos/tpress.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER=0 HSPACE=0></A>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>What's Fair?</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>General Discussion</H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
J<SMALL>UNE</SMALL> 17, 1994<BR>
I<SMALL>VAN</SMALL> R. B<SMALL>ENDER</SMALL>, C<SMALL>HAIRPERSON</SMALL></P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>C</BIG></BIG>hairperson Bender began the discussion by commending conference participants on the presentations and committee work done the previous day. He thanked the committee chairpersons for their reports and recognized the first speaker.</P>
<P>
<B>C<SMALL>HILDREN'S</SMALL> U<SMALL>SE OF</SMALL> S<SMALL>OFTWARE AND</SMALL> M<SMALL>ULTIMEDIA AT</SMALL> H<SMALL>OME</SMALL></B><BR>
Ken Komoski, representing the Educational Products Information Exchange and the Learning and Information Network for Community Telecomputing (LINCT), reinforced the need for having the Office of Technology Assessment (OTA) look into the issues discussed at the conference. He urged participants to talk to their members of Congress and to request a new report on the important issues raised at this conference and also suggested talking to Kathleen Fulton, who is the senior analyst at OTA.</P>
<P>
As a representative of LINCT, Komoski explained that there needs to be a realization that media will not just be going to the homes of individual students on the school bus, but also on "the computer bus. . .going home on a community telecomputing network." There will soon be a need not just for a school-based site license, which participants have discussed, but for a "community-based site license with particular attention being paid to this as a way of getting to the growing numbers of electric access have-nots." He pointed out that many parents spend "$350 to $1,250 a year on software that their kids use for ten or more hours each week at home, but that poor kids and struggling middle-class kids get only an hour or two a week of computer use in schools."</P>
<P>
Chairperson Bender asked whether fair-use guidelines would extend to the child who took a multimedia program home for his own use and then put it on the Internet where any subscribers could access it. Komoski responded that no one could answer that question, but it needed to be addressed, as the "floodgates" of potentially "42 million K-12 youngsters" with access to networks were on the verge of being opened. Bender commented that the prospect of such numbers is a quantum leap beyond the previously discussed ideas of broadening the face-to-face teaching restrictions on fair use.</P>
<P>
Komoski agreed, clarifying his remarks by adding that he was thinking particularly of computer software with high instructional value. In lower-income families, children have access to such products for limited and scheduled hours at school. The children of higher income families, who have bought such programs, have virtually unlimited opportunities to explore the software and learn from it. He reiterated his concern that society was increasingly divided between technological haves and have-nots, and there needed to be a concerted attempt to deal with the problem.</P>
<P>
<B>A<SMALL>CADEMIC</SMALL> D<SMALL>OMAIN</SMALL></B><BR>
Gregg Mathis of Carnegie Mellon University raised the issue of defining academic domain. He takes academic domain to be between fair-use situations and the public domain. He argued that products have an economic life span, during which creators are entitled to full economic benefits and fair-use restrictions should apply. After such a period, however, the concept of academic domain might come into play. In this period, the product might be made available for free use by the academic community.</P>
<P>
Carol Risher, of the Association of American Publishers, responded that the marketplace already has such a sequence in place. She gave examples of earlier versions of several software programs that were sold for nominal prices to homes and schools when new, revised editions were released. She also pointed out that a similar "after-market" exists for computer hardware, as offices update their equipment and donate or sell the old hardware to schools. She protested, "Schools are seen in fact as the next market after the prime commercial area, and I don't think you have to impose on copyright proprietors and vendors and creators something that they are now doing anyway." She said she was "not wild about an educational domain."</P>
<P>
<B>N<SMALL>EED FOR</SMALL> F<SMALL>AIR</SMALL>-U<SMALL>SE</SMALL> G<SMALL>UIDELINES</SMALL></B><BR>
James Schmidt, university librarian at San Jose State University, argued that seeking new guidelines may not be necessary or advisable. Because guidelines do not have the force of law, they are subject to litigation whenever some party or interest feels that its needs are not accommodated. As a result, guidelines are likely to be continuously evolving though case-by-case accretion.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>There will soon be a need for a community-based site license with particular attention being paid to this as a way of getting to the growing numbers of electric access have-nots.</BIG></BIG> - <I>Ken Komoski</I></P>
<P>
Schmidt spoke of a case under adjudication involving the uploading of copyrighted material to a computer network bulletin board service. He did not know whether fair use claims formed any part of the defense, but he pointed out that one of the things computers "do very well is to count things and keep track of where they come from." Anonymity is very difficult.
Chairperson Bender then made four points:
<OL TYPE="1">
<LI>The prevailing viewpoint of conference participants is that most educators, those at the K-12 level as well as those in higher education, would prefer more specific guidelines to help them define and interpret fair use.
<LI>The problem with any guidelines covering new media is that they can quickly become outmoded.
<LI>The preamble to the existing fair-use guidelines, which appear as Section 107 of the U.S. Copyright Law, "reflect the viewpoint that the guidelines are not necessarily carved in granite, so to speak, and can be looked at again by the parties."
<LI>Some educational organizations regard fair-use guidelines as a "safe harbor." As long as they stay within the confines of the guidelines they are secure from concerns about copyright infringement. But even if they stray beyond them, they may not be sued because the guidelines "are minimum rather than maximum."
</OL></P>
<P>
<B>T<SMALL>HE</SMALL> H<SMALL>OME</SMALL> "A<SMALL>FTER</SMALL> M<SMALL>ARKET</SMALL>"</B><BR>
Ken Komoski, responding to Carol Risher's comments about the "after-market" of educational and home sales, said, "The educational market is being transformed by the home market right now. Sales of computer software, including CD-ROM and multimedia, to homes will far outstrip all sales to schools within the next two years. As we speak, they're going neck and neck. The home market for these products increased by 69 percent, I believe, last year, and probably will hit that or better again this year." He then reiterated his concern that these sales will go largely to higher income families, further dividing the haves from the have-nots. That's why, he said, "Fair use to low-income kids and adults is very important, and that's why we need to have community telecomputing cooperatives paying a community-wide site license and working with schools to be able to get good software on their networks and into the homes, hands, heads of low-income families."</P>
<P>
Komoski further spoke of the BET Program-Businesses for Equity in Telecomputing-that encourages agencies that are considering giving computers to schools also to make them available to families. The families would sign up for training at community centers and earn a computer as they learned to use it. He mentioned the Buddy Program in Indiana, which also works to get computers into homes.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>An academic domain could be between fair-use situations and the public domain, where a product might be made available for free use by the academic community.</BIG></BIG> - <I>Gregg Mathis</I></P>
<P>
<B>N<SMALL>EEDS OF THE</SMALL> D<SMALL>ISABLED</SMALL></B><BR>
Cindy King of Gallaudet University spoke on behalf of the needs of disabled populations. She said that current copyright law leaves unclear whether she has the right to transcribe audio tracks into texts that are accessible to deaf populations. Blind users could make use of texts converted to speech, but no one knows whether the conversion is permitted under copyright law. Most multimedia developers have a written text. Ideally this text, digitized, should be available to the disabled population for conversion into accessible forms, but the accessibility becomes a problem because everybody else would want it. In England there have been experiments with making text fields available to blind populations for conversion to speech in ways that ensure that publishers do not lose their rights and that copying does not become universal.</P>
<P>
<B>M<SMALL>ARKETPLACE</SMALL> N<SMALL>EEDS</SMALL> C<SMALL>ONVEYED</SMALL> T<SMALL>HROUGH</SMALL> P<SMALL>ERMISSIONS</SMALL> R<SMALL>EQUESTS</SMALL></B><BR>
Carol Race, from Northeast Missouri State University, also representing CCUMC, observed that the process of requesting permissions from publishers and copyright holders is a form of communication between these groups and the marketplace. As a result of this communication, publishers are learning of new needs and problems of their buyers and are led to begin wrestling with some of the emerging problems, such as using materials on distance learning networks.</P>
<P>
<B>P<SMALL>RODUCER'S</SMALL> P<SMALL>ERSPECTIVE</SMALL></B><BR>
Charles Benton of Public Media Inc. challenged remarks in Fred Hofstetter's presentation about the Howard Community College Faculty Copyright Manual. The frequency-of use proviso, requiring that off-air taped material can be repeated once for teaching reinforcement and then, after 45 days, must be erased, is constantly being violated, resulting in "the erosion of public performance rights that we've seen." According to Benton, repeated showings of broadcasts in classes deprives program-rights holders of profits and cuts severely into the after-market. "The fact is if people were living up to this guideline there might still be a market here, and some of the companies that have gone out of business would not have gone out of business."</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>The prevailing viewpoint of conference participants is that most educators those at the K-12 level as well as those in higher education, would prefer more specific guidelines to help them define and interpret fair use.</BIG></BIG> - <I>Ivan Bender</I></P>
<P>
Benton also spoke about the 10/10 rule relating to use of excerpts, arguing that sometimes a very brief amount of footage is "the essence of the film" and using such an excerpt is prohibited by fair use, even if it is less than ten percent of the original production and constitutes less than ten percent of the new production under development. As examples, he cited the footage showing the Tacoma Bridge collapse and a clip showing the metamorphosis of a butterfly from Encyclopedia Britannica films.</P>
<P>
Benton supported the idea of having OTA issue a report on fair-use issues and suggested that Senator Kerrey, who sponsored the Electronic Education Act, might request such a study. With the National Information Infrastructure Task Force sponsoring a conference in 1994, progress will be made, probably incrementally, case by case. He said it may be premature to search for new guidelines right now, but it would be good if the conference established an ongoing steering committee to continue to work on the issues raised.</P>
<P>
The most constructive thing to do right now, according to Benton, is to "focus on setting up models." He said, "CCUMC could apply research on where things are working and where you do have a public/private sector cooperation that is making progress and that is helping to make definitions. Let's attack this problem inductively from the ground up as opposed to deductively, from the guidelines down."</P>
<P>
Ivan Bender, conference chairperson, responded that in his experience in visiting campuses and discussing fair use, most people are very eager to know just what they can and cannot do. The actions of the Maricopa County Community School District, where volunteers give their time to an intellectual property rights committee to police copyright at their own campuses, are exemplary, and Professor Hofstetter's views may be those of a small minority only. Bender doubted that many of the participants thought that the time was premature for new guidelines, but he commended the idea of an ongoing committee to work on guidelines.</P>
<P>
Mike Wood, director of the Media Resources Center at Wichita State University, engaged Benton in further discussion regarding the Tacoma Bridge footage example as demonstrated by Fred Hofstetter. Wood asked about the conditions under which he would be permitted to use the bridge footage and an Ella Fitzgerald Memorex clip in the classroom. Assume that he had purchased both pieces and had shown them both, in their entirety, to his physics class; and assume, to make a point, that he wished to juxtapose two short segments. Could he use capture-and-edit technology to "clip" the two pieces, or must he show them on two projectors, side by side? What intellectual or economic damage would be done to the filmmaker or the distributor in this instance? Carol Race and Carol Risher explained that the clips that Wood had acquired were on a commercial videodisc and later issued on a CD-ROM created by John Wiley and Sons. Benton replied, "Whoever is the copyright owner of those two clips ought to have a say in how they are used to get a fair return on those investments."</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>Blind users could make use of texts converted to speech, but no one knows whether the conversion is permitted under copyright law.</BIG></BIG> - <I>Cindy King</I></P>
<P>
At a later point in the discussion, Race returned to this question, saying that when the clips are on a laserdisc using CAV technology, which is marketed for its random access capability, "If they didn't want clips to be able to be used independently, they wouldn't put them down in a CAV random-access disk. That's what they're there for and that's what they encourage educators to do."</P>
<P>
Bender added, "Those are very valuable clips and very valuable property. They shouldn't just be repurposed because they meet needs that are not foreseen by the publisher without some permission and without some relationship between the publisher and the user."</P>
<P>
<B>F<SMALL>AIR</SMALL> U<SMALL>SE OF</SMALL> F<SMALL>ILM</SMALL> C<SMALL>LIPS IN</SMALL> M<SMALL>EDIA</SMALL> S<SMALL>TUDIES</SMALL></B><BR>
Charles Benton said that he had recently had several discussions about the use of film clips of Hollywood movies for film studies. "I have actually been trying for decades to beat some sense into the heads of the Hollywood studios to allow access to clips for film studies for 'media literacy,' which we really need, and, unfortunately, the publishing community has been stymied because it's very difficult to get clearance for these clips from the Hollywood studios and/or commercial television just to study the media." He added, "Hollywood goes berserk with the idea" of picking up clips from feature films and defining the practice as fair use. He hoped that continuing pressure might bring about some progress on this issue. He argued, "We should be able to study the literature of our timefeature filmsso that kids can develop some standards, some critical thinking, around films and television as they are with literature, which of course is traditional and entrenched."</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>The process of requesting permissions from publishers and copyright holders is a form of communication between these groups and the marketplace.</BIG></BIG> - <I>Carol Race</I></P>
<P>
<B>A<SMALL>N</SMALL> E<SMALL>XISTING</SMALL> OTA R<SMALL>EPORT</SMALL></B><BR>
James Schmidt announced that in 1986 or 1987, Representative Kastenmeier's subcommittee requested a study by OTA. A report was issued by the Library of Congress Network Advisory Committee under a title on the order of "Intellectual Property Rights in the Electronic Age." Robert Cost was the analyst. Although the Internet has expanded since the time the report was written, the participant said that Cost had been aware of the emerging network environment.</P>
<P>
The same participant also identified himself as a person responsible for a media center operation with television distribution responsibilities. He said, "The current guidelines are an administrative headache, a nuisance, a piece of overhead that I wish we could do without, and if I can figure out a way to do that, I will."</P>
<P>
<B>E<SMALL>DUCATION AND THE</SMALL> M<SMALL>ARKETPLACE</SMALL></B><BR>
Lynne Crandall, media consultant at the Language Resource Center of the University of Michigan, spoke as a representative of the International Association of Learning Laboratories. She pointed out that educational institutions have budgets targeted toward education and research. Because they cannot spare resources for defending lawsuits involving copyright infringement, they tend to require their faculty members to be very conservative, inhibiting teaching, academic freedom, and creativity. In the end, she argued, the marketplace suffers; materials that could be purchased and used in the class are not bought because the faculty members are afraid to use them in the way that is most useful and, additionally, they are not creating things. They are not going to go out and pursue making a derivative work because the process looks too complicated.</P>
<P>
She added that educators are urged to confront the educational crisis and prevent students from falling behind: "Well, then, let people teach them in the manner which is best suited to their teaching and learning styles by providing materials in the manner in which people want to use them." She argued that schools require that materials be licensable at very reasonable cost.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>Sometimes a very brief amount of footage is the essence of the film. Using such an excerpt is prohibited by fair use, even if it is less than ten percent of the original production and constitutes less than ten percent of the new production under development.</BIG></BIG> - <I>Charles Benton</I></P>
<P>
Crandall and Chairperson Bender discussed various educational "uses," specifically a case in which students are required to view a film as homework for a class in which it will be discussed. Crandall would like to see the classroom exemption extend to all instructional viewing (i.e., restricted to students enrolled in a course), regardless of whether the teachers are present or where the viewing takes place. Bender said that producers would view such a situation as an attempt to avoid the higher cost of performance fees compared to videotape copies. He said that under fair-use guidelines, home video rights are restricted to the classroom, but with public performance rights, the film could be shown anywhere. He further explained that when the 1976 Copyright Law was written, the home video industry was in its infancy. As a result, the law does not address the distinctions between two markets, the commercial market and the educational market.</P>
<P>
Frank Connolly of American University argued that it would be more productive to stop looking back at the traditions of educators and publishers and the way they affect copyright law, but instead look ahead to the future and think about the ideal world in 2006. "After we understand what the ideal will be in the future, let's back off and ask where are we now and how do we go from where we are to there."</P>
<P>
As the discussion continued, Rosemary Talab of AECT pointed out that texts printed on paper are swiftly being replaced with digitized formats, including several refereed journals published on the Internet. There needs to be a hard look at the problems of networked uses of copyrighted materials. She quoted John Seeley Brown of Xerox, who said that "in the future, paper will be for transitory use." There are many unanswered questions with regard to large-scale uses of digitized works.</P>
<P>
In addition, Talab said that portfolios and projects are increasingly a part of K-12 education. Students have to present their portfolios and their projects for review. Teachers in a growing number of school districts must submit portfolios for professional teaching evaluations. Many of these are likely to contain clips from video, compact discs, and other formats, creating yet more copyright and fair-use issues.</P>
<P>
<B>A<SMALL>PPEAL FOR</SMALL> C<SMALL>ONTINUING</SMALL> A<SMALL>CTION</SMALL></B><BR>
Chairperson Bender reiterated the need to look at issues that are likely to develop in the next five or ten years relating to multimedia and fair use. He said that these issues will need to be examined in a more relaxed way over some time. He appealed to participants to indicate their interest in pursuing the questions raised at the conference. He warned, however, that the government seems to be moving quickly, and it is necessary to make views known soon.</P>
<P>
<B>S<SMALL>TREAMLINING</SMALL> P<SMALL>ERMISSIONS</SMALL> R<SMALL>EQUESTS</SMALL></B><BR>
Robert Kern of Paramount Publishing warned that during the transitional period technologies are evolving and new guidelines are being hammered out, and it will be important to find ways to have complete copyright and permissions information travel with digital information and products.</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>The current guidelines are an administrative headache, a nuisance, a piece of overhead that I wish we could do without, and if I can figure out a way to do that, I will.</BIG></BIG> - <I>James Schmidt</I></P>
<P>
Bender commended this idea, suggesting that if access to copyright holders by educational users was improved, a new fair-use definition might be less urgent.  He said that all parties bear some blame for the current situation.  The proprietary community is often slow in responding to requests for permissions and sometimes does not even know how to contact the copyright holder.  The educational community, on the other hand, often goes about requesting permission in ways that make the process more difficult than it needs to be.</P>
<P>
There is the possibility that the Copyright Office may try to implement some kind of prototype of a licensing mechanism.  The problem is particularly complicated in the case of audiovisual products, which may involve many separate copyrighted materials so that producers need to negotiate music rights, directors rights, rights of the author of the script, and performers rights, directors rights, rights of the author of the script, and performers rights.  There needs to be a way to make all of these rights negotiable at the same time.</P>
<P>
M<SMALL>ORE ON</SMALL> A<SMALL>CADEMIC</SMALL> D<SMALL>OMAIN</SMALL><BR>
Gregg Mathis from Carnegie Mellon made two points.  First, he asked if any dollar value could be calculated for academic uses of materials under fair use; and, if so, could some kind f payment be made in return for release of materials to the academic domain?  Second, he pointed out that proprietors would be able to decide whether or not to release materials into the academic domain.</P>
<P>
N<SMALL>ONGEOGRAPHIC</SMALL> E<SMALL>DUCATIONAL</SMALL> E<SMALL>NVIRONMENTS</SMALL><BR>
Jim Mecklenburger, a journalist and representative of Global Village Schools Institute, pointed out that the representation at the conference and the issues discussed were informed by traditional players and "well-entrenched enterprises - government, legal, schools operations, and publishers of many kinds of media."  He said there is a need to bring in some interests who will be important players in the future.  Among these are "the world of telephony" and video producers such as Turner Broadcasting, which has become "an enterprise that is increasingly becoming an educating institution, drawing some of its revenue and some of its activity and some of its talent into being a direct instructor, not merely to a group of folks in one lace, which is largely the context of most of our conversation, but to groups of folks in many, many places."  Because of enterprises like these, educational environments may come to be defined in ways that are not geographic at all.  He mentioned the National Geographic Kids Network and described it as "a schooling community with no locus, but rather a community of folks tens of thousands large that are orchestrated technologically to do some work."</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>Materials that could be purchases and used in class are not bought because faculty members are afraid to use them in the way that is most useful and, additionally, they are not creating things.</BIG></BIG> - <I>Lynne Crandall</I></P>
<P>
Mecklenburger said, "We need a very new set of rubrics, whether its academic domain or some other kinds of ways to think about these matters that arent tied to geography, arent tied to classrooms, arent tied to libraries and arent tied to media centers, but have a much broader context."  He also said that the people who are now pushing the limits of education, publishing, and distribution needed to be brought into the conversation.</P>
<P>
Finally, Mecklenburger stated that OTA is currently working on a study called <I>Teachers and Technology</I>, which is due for release in January 1995.  Kathleen Fulton would know about it.</P>
<P>
Chairperson Bender responded that a number of participants who were invited did not come, but they would be sent a report of the conference.  The sponsors had attempted to include all primary organizations.</P>
<P>
F<SMALL>UTURE</SMALL> D<SMALL>IRECTIONS</SMALL>
Cynthia Rosso with the National Council of Teachers of Mathematics called for focus groups to look at where education, the publishing industry, and the communications industry is heading.</P>
<P>
Chairperson Bender agreed, adding that it was becoming very likely that increasingly the academic community would become a major producer of multimedia programming, to the point that academic institutions might be suppliers of materials that would be disseminated by commercial vendors or distributed in competition with them. The development of university presses is a precedent for this process, as they were first formed to disseminate information that did not interest commercial publishers and then many of them became strong, more general publishers themselves. When academic institutions become producers and distributors, either commercially or nonprofit, an entirely new set of questions will arise.</P>
<P>
<B>C<SMALL>ONCLUSION</SMALL></B><BR>
Lisa Livingston, from City College of New York and a representative of CCUMC, offered parting words to participants representing proprietary interests. She said, "The technology that is being integrated and used in the classroom today might not need to be considered or should not need to be considered the way technology was used in the past. We are talking about technology changing the way we educate and changing the way kids learn. We're talking about linear and nonlinear integration, and we're talking about for the first time maybe in our entire lifeteaching the entire community. If we consider that as a reality, then that means that we all have a tremendous responsibility to try to work together to come up with some sort of solution so that we don't leave behind people that are disabled, people that do not have the money to purchase, and people that are making and working hard to create for us in education."</P>
<P>
<BIG><BIG>Texts printed on paper are swiftly being replaced with digitized formats, and there are many unanswered questions with regard to large-scale uses of digitized works.</BIG></BIG> - <I>Rosemary Talab</I></P>
<P>
Ken Komoski extended Livingston's remarks by referring to "the ecology of learning." He pointed out that children typically spend nineteen percent of their time over a year in school, and traditionally this time has dominated their learning experience. "But now that we've got this enormous activity going on in homes, it's increasing and forcing us to look more broadly at this ecology." He mentioned a commentary he had published in <I>Education Week</I> (January 25, 1994) called "The 81-Percent Solution to Educational Problems."</P>
<P>
Chairperson Bender then thanked the sponsors, the Consortium of College and University Media Centers and the Agency for Instructional Technology, as well as National Video Resources, which had underwritten some costs of the conference, and Dynacom, which had also contributed. He acknowledged the important contribution of the presenters and all the participants.</P>
<P>
Bender then affirmed that the effort will continue, especially in working with government agencies. He hoped to pull together a "small core of individuals" to keep up the dialogue.</P>
<P>
Charles Benton joined Ken Komoski in thanking Bender for his leadership role in the conference and expressed great satisfaction in having been able to attend.</P>
<P>
Joann Stevens, from the Association of American Colleges and Universities, added that new media will provide a voice and images for "different kinds of people, cultures, and women who have not been fairly represented or accurately represented in our education within the past." She said that technology will make "what we learn more accurate and broader than it has been."</P>
<P>
Bender expressed appreciation to American University for hosting the conference.</P>
<P>
The Educational Fair Access and the New Media National Conference concluded at 11:30 a.m., June 17, 1994.  <IMG SRC="/images/micro_ait.jpg"></P>

<HR>
<B>Ivan R. Bender</B> is an attorney in private practice in Chicago who specializes in copyright law and the issues dealing with the educational and library use of video, film, and computer software. He represents a wide range of clients, including many educational institutions for whom he has served as a consultant in the development of their copyright policies. In his capacity as general counsel to the Association for Information Media and Equipment (AIME), Bender has established the AIME Copyright Hotline for use by educators and librarians. He was general counsel to Encyclopaedia Britannica Educational Corporation for 15 years and was a special consultant to the register of copyrights of the U.S. Copyright Office in Washington, D.C. Bender was instrumental in establishing the committee that negotiated the Guidelines for Off-Air Recording of Broadcast Programming for Educational Purposes and served on that committee. Author of the script and user guide for the video "Copyright: What Every School, College, and Library Should Know," he is a frequent lecturer on copyright to regional, state, and national educational organizations and is the author of many articles on the subject.<P>

<HR>
