<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIT Board of Directors - Judith A. Billings</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0></A>
<H1>AIT Board of Directors</H1>
<HR>


<IMG SRC="billings.jpg" ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE="6" ALIGN HSPACE="14">
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER><I>Judith A. Billings</I></H2>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><B>
Superintendent of Public Instruction<BR>
Washington State<BR>
Biographical Information</B>
</P>
<HR>
<P><BR>
Born in Kalispell, Montana, Judith attended schools in Libby, Montana, until a family move took her to Portland, Oregon, where she graduated from high school. Her college experience was at Pacific Lutheran University in Tacoma where she graduated with a B.A. degree in education.
</P>
<P>
After two years of teaching in the Franklin Pierce School District, Billings moved to Albuquerque, New Mexico, where she earned her master's  degree in communications from the University of New Mexico. Her classroom teaching career continued in Fresno, California, and Puyallup, Washington, and eventually totaled 13 years.
</P>
<P>
While at Puyallup, Billings developed an interest and concern for the students who were not making progress or graduating from the public school system. This inspired her to become involved in the formation of Puyallup Continuation School where she eventually served as program coordinator. Her Principal's Credentials were obtained from Western Washington University. In 1972 she married teacher-colleague, Donald Billings.
</P>
<P>
In 1979, Judith's career took another turn as she took a position with the Office of State Superintendent of Public Instruction. As state director of the federally funded program for disadvantaged children (Title I), Judith visited almost every school district in the state, gaining an understanding of the vast differences in Washington's urban, suburban and rural schools. Supervision of the state Remediation Assistance Program was added to her responsibilities in 1984.
</P>
<P>
During her tenure as state Title I director, Judith provided leadership in the process of writing a federal audit handbook and serving as legislative committee coordinator from 1984 - 1987. This piqued her interest in the legal aspects of education administration, and while continuing to work at the state agency, she began attending the University of Puget Sound Law School evening classes.
</P>
<P>
Her knowledge of the state and federal programs led to a legal internship with the U.S. House of Representatives Education Committee in Washington, D.C., where she prepared a subcommittee report on compensatory education programs. Returning to Washington State, she completed law school, graduating with a Juris Doctorate, Cum Laude in 1987. She was admitted to the Washington State Bar in December 1987. She transferred to the Legal Services Section of the State Education Agency upon her return from Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
The reauthorization of the federal Chapter 1 program prompted another request for federal service. Judith was asked to provide guidance to the U.S. House of Representatives congressional subcommittee on elementary, secondary and vocational education with the reauthorization process. She assisted in negotiating much of the legal language in the Stafford-Hawkins Elementary and Secondary School Improvement Amendments of 1988.
</P>
<P>
While in Washington, D.C., for the second time, a write-in campaign began in Washington State. Educators from across the state were mounting a campaign to place an educator on the ballot for State Superintendent of Public Instruction.  Judith A. Billings was the target of that campaign. She was elected to that office by the voters of the state of Washington on November 8, 1988, becoming the state's 13th Superintendent of Public Instruction on January 11, 1989.
</P>
<P>
During her first term, Superintendent Billings emphasized the need for the education system to improve the programs and systems that support successful families and children who come to school prepared to learn. Her advocacy has helped impel improved funding for early childhood education programs, improved counseling and testing and expanded school based child care programs. A leader in interagency programs, by working with five state departmental secretaries, Superintendent Billings also has helped establish and lead the Family Policy Initiative, an effort to coordinate family and children policies across agency and departmental lines.
</P>
<P>
She has also supported new initiatives in technology, making Washington a participant in the Star Schools program. New proposals also have resulted in better funding for school construction projects, improved teacher salaries and reduced class size in early grades.
</P>
<P>
In 1991 Judith was appointed to the Governor's Council on Education Reform and Funding. This 21-member Council of education, business and legislative leaders worked over an 18-month period to produce recommendations which would lay the groundwork for education reform in the state of Washington.
</P>
<P>
As her second term of office began in 1993, she worked closely with the Legislature to support the passage of Engrossed Substitute House Bill 1209, Washington's comprehensive systemic education reform bill. Judith is vice chair of the Commission on Student Learning which is establishing essential academic learning requirements and assessments that will shift Washington's schools to a performance-based system by the year 2000. She established a Center for the Improvement of Student Learning at the state agency to disseminate the work of the Commission, provide technical assistance to school districts on restructuring &quot;best practices&quot; and to involve parents and community members in the education change process.
</P>
<P>
Judith's work at the national level continues as the Vice President of the Council of Chief State School Officers (CCSSO) for the 1996 term. Judith served as the President of CCSSO for the 1995 term.
</P>
<P>
Judith also serves as a member of the Board of Natural Resources, the Workforce Training and Education Coordinating Board, the School to Work Taskforce, and numerous other boards and commissions dealing with technology, environmental, arts, and partnership issues.
</P>

<H5 ALIGN=RIGHT>(2/96) Revised</H5>

<HR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="/ait/aboard.htm">Return to Listing of AIT's Board Members</A>
</P>

