<HEAD>
<TITLE>AIT Board of Directors - Sandra L. McBrayer</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/backgrnd.jpg" TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="FF00FF" ALINK="FF0000">
<TABLE WIDTH="100%">
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP WIDTH=40><IMG SRC="/images/bgspace.gif" BORDER=0 HSPACE=0 VSPACE=0></TD><TD>
<A HREF="/ait/aait.htm"><IMG SRC="/images/aitlogo.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT BORDER=0></A>
<H1>AIT Board of Directors</H1>
<HR>


<IMG SRC="mcbrayer.jpg" ALIGN=RIGHT VSPACE="10" ALIGN=HSPACE="10">
<P>
<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Sandra L. McBrayer</H2>

<HR>
<UL>
<LI><B>Sandra McBrayer</B> was the 1994 "National Teacher of the Year" and the 1993-94 "California Teacher of the Year."
<LI><B>Sandra</B> founded and developed the first successful school in the United States for homeless and unattended youth.
<LI><B>Sandra</B> has served as Head Teacher at the Homeless Outreach School for the San Diego County Office of Education since 1988.
<LI><B>Sandra</B> received her B.A. and M.A., San Diego States University.
<LI><B>Sandra</B> has been a lecturer and consultant at the School of Teacher Education and the Center for Careers in Education, San Diego State
University, since 1990.
<LI><B>Sandra</B> was the recipient of the "Distinguished Alumna of the Year Education" award from San Diego State University in 1992.
<LI><B>Sandra</B> also consults with the California State Department of Education, collaborates with school districts concerning equity, education and excellence, and develops meaning-based curriculum for the homeless population.
<LI><B>Sandra</B> has been featured on <I>Good Morning America, CNN, 48hours, Lifetime Magazine</I>, and <I>CBS This Morning</I>. Newspaper stories have appeared in <I>USA TODAY, Christian Science Monitor, Los Angeles Times</I> and <I>San Diego Union-Tribune</I>. Radio interviews have aired on National Public Radio and Voice of America.
<LI><B>Sandra</B> was recognized with the 'Women of Vision in Education" award from the League of Women Voters in 1992.
<LI><B>Sandra's</B> Homeless Outreach Program was recognized in 1993 with a "Golden Bell Award" from the California School Boards Association.
</UL>
<P>
<B>The Homeless Outreach Education Program</B> is a comprehensive secondary school program providing education for homeless youth, ages 12 through 19. These students live on the streets in San Diego or in an emergency shelter (there is only one 20-bed emergency shelter currently available in San Diego for homeless teenagers). The Homeless Outreach Program allows students to continue pursuing all the requirements necessary to obtain a high school diploma, G.E.D., or California High School Proficiency certificate. Each course of study is tailored to the student's individual educational needs. This program also offers extensive career guidance, employment referrals, and personal counseling through a variety of community-based agencies.
</P>

<HR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<A HREF="/ait/aboard.htm">Return to Listing of AIT's Board Members</A>
</P>

<A HREF="/AIT/aitcopy.htm">&copy; AIT</A>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
